  ('gate-core-cs-artificial-intelligence-ml-basics-q05', 'gate-core-cs-artificial-intelligence-ml-basics', 'Which search strategy is complete and optimal for a tree with uniform step costs?', 'Random walk', 'Depth-first search', 'Greedy best-first search', 'Breadth-first search', 'D', 'BFS is complete and optimal when every step has the same cost.', 4),
  ('gate-core-cs-artificial-intelligence-ml-basics-q06', 'gate-core-cs-artificial-intelligence-ml-basics', 'Grouping unlabelled data into clusters by similarity is a task in:', 'Supervised learning', 'Regression', 'Reinforcement learning', 'Unsupervised learning', 'D', 'Clustering is an unsupervised task that finds structure without labels.', 5),
  ('gate-core-cs-artificial-intelligence-ml-basics-q07', 'gate-core-cs-artificial-intelligence-ml-basics', 'A perceptron computes its output by applying an activation function to:', 'A random input', 'The maximum of its inputs', 'The median of its inputs', 'A weighted sum of inputs', 'D', 'A neuron applies an activation function to the weighted sum of its inputs.', 6),
  ('gate-core-cs-artificial-intelligence-ml-basics-q08', 'gate-core-cs-artificial-intelligence-ml-basics', 'Learning by maximizing a reward through trial and error is called:', 'Supervised learning', 'Feature scaling', 'Dimensionality reduction', 'Reinforcement learning', 'D', 'Reinforcement learning optimizes behaviour from reward signals via trial and error.', 7),
  ('gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography-q01', 'gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography', 'Which set forms the classic CIA triad of information security?', 'Control, Integrity, Access', 'Confidentiality, Identity, Authorization', 'Cipher, Identity, Authentication', 'Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability', 'D', 'The CIA triad is Confidentiality, Integrity and Availability.', 0),
  ('gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography-q02', 'gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography', 'Which algorithm uses a public and private key pair?', 'RSA', 'DES', 'AES', 'Caesar cipher', 'A', 'RSA is an asymmetric cipher using a public-private key pair.', 1),
  ('gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography-q03', 'gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography', 'The security of RSA relies on the difficulty of:', 'Sorting large arrays', 'Computing logarithms quickly', 'Reversing a hash collision', 'Factoring large composite numbers', 'D', 'RSA is secure because factoring the large modulus n into its primes is hard.', 2),
  ('gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography-q04', 'gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography', 'To send a confidential message, the sender encrypts it with the recipient''s:', 'Private key', 'Own private key', 'Own public key', 'Public key', 'D', 'Encrypting with the recipient''s public key ensures only the recipient can decrypt it.', 3),
  ('gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography-q05', 'gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography', 'A cryptographic hash function is expected to be:', 'One-way and collision-resistant', 'Easily reversible', 'Dependent on a shared key', 'Different for the same input each time', 'A', 'Cryptographic hashes are one-way and resistant to finding collisions.', 4),
  ('gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography-q06', 'gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography', 'Which property prevents a sender from later denying having sent a message?', 'Availability', 'Non-repudiation', 'Confidentiality', 'Redundancy', 'B', 'Non-repudiation ensures the sender cannot deny the action, typically via signatures.', 5),
  ('gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography-q07', 'gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography', 'A digital signature is created by encrypting a message hash with the sender''s:', 'Public key', 'Private key', 'Symmetric session key', 'Recipient''s private key', 'B', 'Signing uses the sender''s private key on the message hash, proving origin and integrity.', 6),
  ('gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography-q08', 'gate-core-cs-information-security-cryptography', 'Compared with asymmetric ciphers, symmetric ciphers are generally:', 'Slower but easier for key distribution', 'Unable to encrypt bulk data', 'Always more secure', 'Faster but harder for key distribution', 'D', 'Symmetric ciphers are faster but require securely sharing the single secret key.', 7),
  ('gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers-q01', 'gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers', 'In C, the expression a[i] for an array a is equivalent to:', 'Value at a plus i bytes', 'Address of a plus i bytes', 'Value at address a plus i elements', 'The literal i', 'C', 'a[i] dereferences a + i, where the offset is scaled by the element size.', 0),
  ('gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers-q02', 'gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers', 'Incrementing a pointer to int by 1 advances the address by:', '1 byte', '2 bytes always', 'The size of an int in bytes', 'The value stored', 'C', 'Pointer arithmetic scales by the size of the pointed-to type, here sizeof(int).', 1),
  ('gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers-q03', 'gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers', 'A pointer that refers to memory that has already been freed is called a:', 'Dangling pointer', 'Null pointer', 'Void pointer', 'Function pointer', 'A', 'A dangling pointer still references memory that has been deallocated.', 2),
  ('gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers-q04', 'gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers', 'In C, arguments are passed by default using:', 'Call by reference', 'Call by name', 'Call by value', 'Call by need', 'C', 'C passes arguments by value; modifying a parameter does not change the caller''s variable.', 3),
  ('gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers-q05', 'gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers', 'Which function allocates memory and initializes it to zero?', 'free', 'malloc', 'calloc', 'sizeof', 'C', 'calloc zero-initializes the allocated block, unlike malloc.', 4),
  ('gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers-q06', 'gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers', 'Failing to release dynamically allocated memory leads to a:', 'Stack overflow', 'Buffer underflow', 'Compile error', 'Memory leak', 'D', 'Not calling free on heap memory causes a memory leak.', 5),
  ('gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers-q07', 'gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers', 'The declaration int **p declares p as a:', 'Pointer to an int', 'Function returning int', 'Array of ints', 'Pointer to a pointer to an int', 'D', 'int **p is a pointer to a pointer to int.', 6),
  ('gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers-q08', 'gate-programming-ds-c-programming-pointers', 'For a row-major 2D array with C columns, element a[i][j] is at offset:', 'i + j elements', 'j * C + i elements', 'i * C + j elements', 'i * j elements', 'C', 'In row-major order the linear offset of a[i][j] is i*C + j elements from the base.', 7),
  ('gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking-q01', 'gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking', 'Every correct recursive function must include a:', 'Base case', 'Loop', 'Global variable', 'Pointer argument', 'A', 'A base case stops the recursion; without it the calls never terminate.', 0),
  ('gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking-q02', 'gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking', 'The naive recursive computation of the nth Fibonacci number runs in time:', 'O(2^n)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n^2)', 'O(n)', 'A', 'Unmemoized Fibonacci recomputes subproblems exponentially, giving O(2^n).', 1),
  ('gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking-q03', 'gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking', 'Which problem is classically solved using backtracking?', 'Binary search', 'The N-Queens problem', 'Bubble sort', 'Hash table lookup', 'B', 'N-Queens places queens incrementally and backtracks on conflicts.', 2),
  ('gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking-q04', 'gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking', 'Each recursive call consumes additional:', 'Stack space for its frame', 'No memory at all', 'Heap memory only', 'Disk storage', 'A', 'Each call pushes a new activation record onto the call stack.', 3),
  ('gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking-q05', 'gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking', 'A recursive call that is the last operation in a function is called:', 'Nested recursion', 'Mutual recursion', 'Indirect recursion', 'Tail recursion', 'D', 'In tail recursion the recursive call is the final action, allowing loop conversion.', 4),
  ('gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking-q06', 'gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking', 'The recurrence T(n) = T(n-1) + O(1) solves to:', 'O(log n)', 'O(2^n)', 'O(n log n)', 'O(n)', 'D', 'Reducing the problem by one with constant work each step gives linear time.', 5),
  ('gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking-q07', 'gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking', 'The key efficiency idea in backtracking is to:', 'Always explore every leaf', 'Prune partial solutions that cannot succeed', 'Avoid recursion entirely', 'Sort the input first', 'B', 'Backtracking prunes branches that cannot lead to a valid solution, cutting the search.', 6),
  ('gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking-q08', 'gate-programming-ds-recursion-backtracking', 'Computing n! recursively requires how many multiplications for n greater than 0?', 'n', '2n', 'n + 1', 'n - 1', 'D', 'factorial(n) multiplies n down to 1, performing n - 1 multiplications.', 7),
  ('gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues-q01', 'gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues', 'A stack follows which ordering discipline?', 'First-In-First-Out', 'Random order', 'Priority order', 'Last-In-First-Out', 'D', 'A stack is LIFO: the most recently pushed item is popped first.', 0),
  ('gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues-q02', 'gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues', 'A queue follows which ordering discipline?', 'Smallest first', 'Last-In-First-Out', 'Largest first', 'First-In-First-Out', 'D', 'A queue is FIFO: the earliest enqueued item is dequeued first.', 1),
  ('gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues-q03', 'gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues', 'Inserting a node at the head of a singly linked list takes time:', 'O(1)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n)', 'O(n log n)', 'A', 'Head insertion just relinks the head pointer, a constant-time operation.', 2),
  ('gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues-q04', 'gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues', 'Which structure is most natural for evaluating a postfix expression?', 'Queue', 'Stack', 'Binary search tree', 'Hash table', 'B', 'Postfix evaluation pushes operands and pops them on operators using a stack.', 3),
  ('gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues-q05', 'gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues', 'Searching for a value in an unsorted singly linked list takes time:', 'O(n)', 'O(log n)', 'O(1)', 'O(n^2)', 'A', 'A linked list has no random access, so search scans nodes in O(n).', 4),
  ('gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues-q06', 'gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues', 'A data structure allowing insertion and deletion at both ends is a:', 'Stack', 'Simple queue', 'Deque', 'Singly linked list', 'C', 'A deque (double-ended queue) supports operations at both the front and rear.', 5),
  ('gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues-q07', 'gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues', 'Which structure is used to manage function calls during program execution?', 'Queue', 'Priority queue', 'Call stack', 'Circular buffer', 'C', 'Function calls use a LIFO call stack to store return addresses and locals.', 6),
  ('gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues-q08', 'gate-programming-ds-linked-lists-stacks-queues', 'A circular queue is preferred over a linear array queue because it:', 'Sorts elements automatically', 'Reuses vacated front slots', 'Allows binary search', 'Stores keys and values', 'B', 'A circular queue wraps around to reuse slots freed at the front, avoiding waste.', 7),
  ('gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps-q01', 'gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps', 'The average-case time complexity of a lookup in a hash table is:', 'O(log n)', 'O(1)', 'O(n)', 'O(n log n)', 'B', 'With a good hash function and load factor, lookups average O(1).', 0),
  ('gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps-q02', 'gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps', 'In a min-heap, the smallest element is always located at the:', 'Last leaf', 'Rightmost node', 'Root', 'Middle level', 'C', 'A min-heap keeps the minimum element at the root.', 1),
  ('gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps-q03', 'gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps', 'The load factor of a hash table is defined as:', 'Slots divided by entries', 'Entries times slots', 'Number of collisions', 'Number of entries divided by number of slots', 'D', 'Load factor = n/m, the ratio of stored entries to available slots.', 2),
  ('gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps-q04', 'gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps', 'Inserting an element into a binary heap of n elements takes time:', 'O(n)', 'O(1)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n log n)', 'C', 'Heap insertion sifts the new element up at most the height, O(log n).', 3),
  ('gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps-q05', 'gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps', 'Building a binary heap from n unordered elements using sift-down takes time:', 'O(n)', 'O(n log n)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n^2)', 'A', 'The standard build-heap procedure runs in O(n), faster than n insertions.', 4),
  ('gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps-q06', 'gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps', 'Which collision-resolution method stores colliding keys in a list per bucket?', 'Separate chaining', 'Quadratic probing', 'Linear probing', 'Double hashing', 'A', 'Separate chaining keeps a linked list of entries in each bucket.', 5),
  ('gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps-q07', 'gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps', 'In a 0-indexed array heap, the children of node i are at indices:', 'i-1 and i+1', '2i+1 and 2i+2', 'i/2 and i/3', 'i+2 and i+3', 'B', 'For 0-indexed heaps the children of node i are at 2i+1 and 2i+2.', 6),
  ('gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps-q08', 'gate-programming-ds-hashing-heaps', 'A binary heap is most directly used to implement a:', 'Hash map', 'Balanced BST', 'Priority queue', 'Stack', 'C', 'Heaps efficiently support priority-queue operations like extract-min and insert.', 7),
  ('gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs-q01', 'gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs', 'Breadth-first search uses which auxiliary data structure?', 'Stack', 'Queue', 'Heap', 'Hash table', 'B', 'BFS explores level by level using a FIFO queue.', 0),
  ('gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs-q02', 'gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs', 'The time complexity of BFS or DFS on a graph with V vertices and E edges using an adjacency list is:', 'O(V^2)', 'O(V * E)', 'O(E log V)', 'O(V + E)', 'D', 'Both traversals visit each vertex and edge once, giving O(V + E).', 1),
  ('gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs-q03', 'gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs', 'On an unweighted graph, BFS from a source finds the shortest path measured in:', 'Total edge weight', 'Number of edges', 'Number of vertices squared', 'Memory used', 'B', 'BFS yields the fewest-edge (shortest) path in an unweighted graph.', 2),
  ('gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs-q04', 'gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs', 'Topological sorting can be applied only to a:', 'Directed acyclic graph', 'Complete graph', 'Undirected cyclic graph', 'Bipartite graph', 'A', 'A topological order exists only for a DAG (no directed cycles).', 3),
  ('gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs-q05', 'gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs', 'An adjacency matrix for a graph with V vertices requires space:', 'O(V + E)', 'O(E)', 'O(V)', 'O(V^2)', 'D', 'An adjacency matrix stores a V by V table, needing O(V^2) space.', 4),
  ('gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs-q06', 'gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs', 'In a depth-first traversal of a directed graph, a back edge indicates:', 'A disconnected graph', 'A spanning tree', 'A shortest path', 'A cycle', 'D', 'A back edge to an ancestor in the DFS tree reveals a cycle.', 5),
  ('gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs-q07', 'gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs', 'Depth-first search can be implemented iteratively using a:', 'Queue', 'Stack', 'Priority queue', 'Sorted array', 'B', 'Iterative DFS uses an explicit stack in place of the recursion stack.', 6),
  ('gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs-q08', 'gate-programming-ds-graph-algorithms-bfs-dfs', 'An adjacency list representation is most space-efficient for a graph that is:', 'Sparse', 'Complete', 'Dense', 'Bipartite', 'A', 'Adjacency lists use O(V + E) space, ideal when E is small (sparse graphs).', 7),
  ('gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming-q01', 'gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming', 'Dynamic programming is applicable when a problem exhibits overlapping subproblems and:', 'Optimal substructure', 'No structure', 'Only one subproblem', 'Random input', 'A', 'DP requires optimal substructure so optimal answers combine from optimal sub-answers.', 0),
  ('gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming-q02', 'gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming', 'Top-down dynamic programming that caches results of recursive calls is called:', 'Tabulation', 'Memoization', 'Greedy', 'Branch and bound', 'B', 'Memoization stores recursive results in a cache to avoid recomputation.', 1),
  ('gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming-q03', 'gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming', 'The 0/1 knapsack problem with n items and capacity W is solved in time:', 'O(n + W)', 'O(n log W)', 'O(2^n)', 'O(nW)', 'D', 'The DP table over items and capacities runs in pseudo-polynomial O(nW) time.', 2),
  ('gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming-q04', 'gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming', 'The longest common subsequence of strings of length m and n is computed in time:', 'O(m + n)', 'O(log(m + n))', 'O(m^2 * n^2)', 'O(m * n)', 'D', 'The LCS DP fills an m by n table, giving O(m*n) time.', 3),
  ('gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming-q05', 'gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming', 'Matrix chain multiplication ordering is solved by dynamic programming in time:', 'O(n^3)', 'O(n^2)', 'O(n)', 'O(2^n)', 'A', 'The standard matrix chain DP runs in O(n^3) over subchain lengths.', 4),
  ('gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming-q06', 'gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming', 'Bottom-up dynamic programming that fills a table iteratively is known as:', 'Memoization', 'Backtracking', 'Tabulation', 'Recursion', 'C', 'Tabulation builds the solution iteratively from base cases upward.', 5),
  ('gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming-q07', 'gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming', 'Which algorithm computes all-pairs shortest paths via dynamic programming?', 'Dijkstra', 'Prim', 'Floyd-Warshall', 'Kruskal', 'C', 'Floyd-Warshall is a DP that finds shortest paths between all vertex pairs.', 6),
  ('gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming-q08', 'gate-programming-ds-dynamic-programming', 'Memoization reduces the naive recursive Fibonacci time complexity to:', 'O(2^n)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n)', 'O(n^2)', 'C', 'Caching each Fibonacci value computes it once, yielding O(n) time.', 7),
  ('gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra-q01', 'gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra', 'The decimal value of the binary number 1011 is:', '9', '13', '11', '15', 'C', '1011 in binary equals 8 + 0 + 2 + 1 = 11.', 0),
  ('gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra-q02', 'gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra', 'The two''s complement of a number is obtained by:', 'Adding 1 to the number', 'Subtracting 1 from the number', 'Taking the one''s complement then adding 1', 'Reversing the digit order', 'C', 'Two''s complement = one''s complement (invert all bits) plus 1.', 1),
  ('gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra-q03', 'gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra', 'Which gates are functionally complete (universal)?', 'NAND and NOR', 'XOR and XNOR', 'AND and OR', 'Only NOT', 'A', 'Any Boolean function can be built using only NAND gates or only NOR gates.', 2),
  ('gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra-q04', 'gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra', 'By De Morgan''s law, NOT(A AND B) is equivalent to:', '(NOT A) OR (NOT B)', 'A OR B', '(NOT A) AND (NOT B)', 'A AND B', 'A', 'De Morgan: the complement of a product equals the sum of the complements.', 3),
  ('gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra-q05', 'gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra', 'The range of an 8-bit two''s complement signed integer is:', '0 to 255', '-255 to 255', '-127 to 128', '-128 to 127', 'D', 'An n-bit two''s complement range is -2^(n-1) to 2^(n-1)-1, here -128 to 127.', 4),
  ('gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra-q06', 'gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra', 'The hexadecimal equivalent of the binary number 11110000 is:', '0F', 'FF', 'F0', '0E', 'C', 'Grouping into 1111 and 0000 gives F and 0, so the value is F0.', 5),
  ('gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra-q07', 'gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra', 'The Boolean expression A + A'' simplifies to:', '0', 'A', '1', 'A''', 'C', 'A variable ORed with its complement always equals 1.', 6),
  ('gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra-q08', 'gate-computer-organization-number-systems-boolean-algebra', 'Karnaugh maps are used primarily to:', 'Convert decimal to binary', 'Minimize Boolean expressions', 'Detect parity errors', 'Schedule processes', 'B', 'K-maps group adjacent minterms to simplify Boolean functions and reduce gates.', 7),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining-q01', 'gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining', 'An ideal k-stage instruction pipeline can give a maximum speedup of about:', 'k times', '2 times', 'k squared times', 'log k times', 'A', 'An ideal pipeline approaches a speedup equal to the number of stages k.', 0),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining-q02', 'gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining', 'A hazard caused by an instruction depending on the result of a previous one is a:', 'Structural hazard', 'Data hazard', 'Control hazard', 'Power hazard', 'B', 'Data hazards arise when an instruction needs a result not yet produced.', 1),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining-q03', 'gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining', 'A branch instruction that may change the program flow causes a:', 'Data hazard', 'Structural hazard', 'Control hazard', 'Cache miss', 'C', 'Branches create control hazards because the next instruction is uncertain.', 2),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining-q04', 'gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining', 'The technique of feeding a computed result to an earlier-needing stage to avoid stalls is:', 'Interrupting', 'Paging', 'Forwarding', 'Spooling', 'C', 'Forwarding (bypassing) routes a result directly to a dependent stage, avoiding stalls.', 3),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining-q05', 'gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining', 'A 5-stage pipeline processing a very large number of instructions approaches a speedup of:', '2', '5', '10', '25', 'B', 'For large n the pipeline speedup tends toward the stage count, here 5.', 4),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining-q06', 'gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining', 'A conflict over a shared hardware resource between two instructions is a:', 'Data hazard', 'Structural hazard', 'Control hazard', 'Logical hazard', 'B', 'Structural hazards occur when instructions compete for the same hardware unit.', 5),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining-q07', 'gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining', 'CPI in processor performance analysis stands for:', 'Cost per instruction', 'Cycles per instruction', 'Cache per instruction', 'Calls per interrupt', 'B', 'CPI is cycles per instruction, a key factor in execution time.', 6),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining-q08', 'gate-computer-organization-cpu-instruction-pipelining', 'Which is NOT one of the classic instruction cycle stages?', 'Fetch', 'Decode', 'Defragment', 'Write-back', 'C', 'The stages are fetch, decode, execute, memory access and write-back; defragment is not one.', 7),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy-q01', 'gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy', 'Which storage level is the fastest and closest to the CPU?', 'Main memory', 'Magnetic disk', 'Registers', 'Optical disk', 'C', 'Registers sit at the top of the hierarchy: fastest, smallest and closest to the CPU.', 0),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy-q02', 'gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy', 'If the cache hit ratio is 0.9, cache time is 10 ns and memory time is 100 ns, the effective access time is:', '100 ns', '55 ns', '90 ns', '19 ns', 'D', 'EAT = 0.9*10 + 0.1*100 = 9 + 10 = 19 ns.', 1),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy-q03', 'gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy', 'In direct-mapped cache, a memory block can be placed in:', 'Any cache line', 'Any line within one set', 'Exactly one fixed line', 'Two specific lines', 'C', 'Direct mapping assigns each block to exactly one predetermined cache line.', 2),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy-q04', 'gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy', 'A write policy that updates both cache and main memory on every write is called:', 'Write-back', 'Write-around', 'Lazy write', 'Write-through', 'D', 'Write-through writes to cache and memory simultaneously on each store.', 3),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy-q05', 'gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy', 'A cache miss occurring on the very first reference to a block is a:', 'Capacity miss', 'Conflict miss', 'Compulsory miss', 'Coherence miss', 'C', 'Compulsory (cold) misses happen on the first access to a block.', 4),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy-q06', 'gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy', 'Which replacement policy evicts the block unused for the longest time?', 'FIFO', 'Random', 'LRU', 'LIFO', 'C', 'LRU (least recently used) discards the block that has gone longest without use.', 5),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy-q07', 'gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy', 'The principle that recently accessed data is likely to be accessed again soon is:', 'Temporal locality', 'Spatial locality', 'Sequential mapping', 'Associativity', 'A', 'Temporal locality refers to reuse of the same data within a short time window.', 6),
  ('gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy-q08', 'gate-computer-organization-cache-memory-hierarchy', 'In a set-associative cache, a memory block maps to:', 'One fixed line only', 'Any line in the entire cache', 'Any line within one specific set', 'No line at all', 'C', 'Set-associative mapping fixes the set but allows any line within that set.', 7),
  ('gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts-q01', 'gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts', 'Which I/O technique frees the CPU by letting a controller transfer data directly to memory?', 'Programmed I/O', 'Interrupt-driven I/O', 'Direct Memory Access', 'Polling', 'C', 'DMA lets a dedicated controller move data, freeing the CPU during the transfer.', 0),
  ('gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts-q02', 'gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts', 'Programmed I/O is inefficient mainly because the CPU:', 'Busy-waits polling a status bit', 'Cannot access memory', 'Loses all interrupts', 'Runs at a lower clock', 'A', 'In programmed I/O the CPU wastes cycles repeatedly polling a device status bit.', 1),
  ('gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts-q03', 'gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts', 'The routine executed in response to an interrupt is the:', 'Interrupt service routine', 'Boot loader', 'Scheduler', 'Page replacer', 'A', 'The CPU runs the interrupt service routine (ISR) to handle an interrupt.', 2),
  ('gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts-q04', 'gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts', 'An interrupt that cannot be disabled by the processor is called:', 'Maskable', 'Non-maskable', 'Software', 'Vectored', 'B', 'A non-maskable interrupt cannot be ignored or disabled by the CPU.', 3),
  ('gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts-q05', 'gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts', 'A vectored interrupt improves handling by:', 'Disabling all other interrupts', 'Increasing the clock speed', 'Polling each device in turn', 'Supplying the ISR address directly', 'D', 'Vectored interrupts provide the ISR address immediately, skipping a polling scan.', 4),
  ('gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts-q06', 'gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts', 'Immediately after an interrupt is accepted, the CPU first:', 'Erases main memory', 'Saves the current context', 'Reboots the system', 'Disables the clock permanently', 'B', 'The CPU saves the program counter and registers before running the ISR.', 5),
  ('gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts-q07', 'gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts', 'DMA is most beneficial for:', 'Single-byte transfers', 'Branch prediction', 'Arithmetic computation', 'Large block data transfers', 'D', 'DMA shines for bulk block transfers, freeing the CPU from per-byte handling.', 6),
  ('gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts-q08', 'gate-computer-organization-io-interrupts', 'When several interrupts occur together, which scheme decides the service order?', 'Round robin only', 'Priority', 'Random selection', 'Alphabetical order', 'B', 'A priority scheme determines which simultaneous interrupt is serviced first.', 7),
  ('gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic-q01', 'gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic', 'The implication p implies q is false only when:', 'p is true and q is false', 'p is false and q is true', 'p is true and q is true', 'p is false and q is false', 'A', 'An implication is false exactly when its premise is true but its conclusion is false.', 0),
  ('gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic-q02', 'gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic', 'A proposition that is true under every truth assignment is a:', 'Contradiction', 'Predicate', 'Contingency', 'Tautology', 'D', 'A tautology is a formula that evaluates to true for all assignments.', 1),
  ('gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic-q03', 'gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic', 'The expression p implies q is logically equivalent to:', 'p AND q', '(NOT p) OR q', 'p OR (NOT q)', '(NOT p) AND q', 'B', 'By material implication, p implies q equals (NOT p) OR q.', 2),
  ('gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic-q04', 'gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic', 'The contrapositive of p implies q is:', 'q implies p', '(NOT p) implies (NOT q)', '(NOT q) implies (NOT p)', 'p implies (NOT q)', 'C', 'The contrapositive (NOT q implies NOT p) is logically equivalent to the original.', 3),
  ('gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic-q05', 'gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic', 'The negation of the statement ''for all x, P(x)'' is:', 'there exists x such that NOT P(x)', 'for all x, NOT P(x)', 'there exists x such that P(x)', 'for all x, P(x)', 'A', 'Negating a universal quantifier gives an existential with the negated predicate.', 4),
  ('gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic-q06', 'gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic', 'A proposition that is false under every truth assignment is a:', 'Tautology', 'Contradiction', 'Contingency', 'Theorem', 'B', 'A contradiction evaluates to false for all possible truth assignments.', 5),
  ('gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic-q07', 'gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic', 'By De Morgan''s law, NOT(p OR q) equals:', '(NOT p) OR (NOT q)', '(NOT p) AND (NOT q)', 'p AND q', 'p OR q', 'B', 'The negation of a disjunction is the conjunction of the negations.', 6),
  ('gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic-q08', 'gate-discrete-math-propositional-predicate-logic', 'The biconditional p if and only if q is true when:', 'both are false only', 'p is true and q is false', 'exactly one of p, q is true', 'p and q have the same truth value', 'D', 'A biconditional is true precisely when both operands share the same truth value.', 7),
  ('gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations-q01', 'gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations', 'The number of subsets of a set with 4 elements is:', '8', '16', '12', '24', 'B', 'A set with n elements has 2^n subsets; here 2^4 = 16.', 0),
  ('gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations-q02', 'gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations', 'A relation that is reflexive, symmetric and transitive is called:', 'An equivalence relation', 'A partial order', 'A total order', 'An antisymmetric relation', 'A', 'Reflexive, symmetric and transitive together define an equivalence relation.', 1),
  ('gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations-q03', 'gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations', 'By inclusion-exclusion, if |A| = 5, |B| = 7 and |A intersect B| = 3, then |A union B| is:', '15', '12', '9', '10', 'C', '|A union B| = 5 + 7 - 3 = 9.', 2),
  ('gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations-q04', 'gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations', 'A relation that is reflexive, antisymmetric and transitive defines a:', 'Partial order', 'Equivalence relation', 'Function', 'Bijection', 'A', 'Those three properties define a partial order (a poset).', 3),
  ('gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations-q05', 'gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations', 'The number of functions from a set of 3 elements to a set of 4 elements is:', '64', '24', '12', '81', 'A', 'The count of functions from an m-set to an n-set is n^m = 4^3 = 64.', 4),
  ('gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations-q06', 'gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations', 'A function that is both injective and surjective is called:', 'Bijective', 'Constant', 'Partial', 'Identity only', 'A', 'A function that is one-to-one and onto is bijective.', 5),
  ('gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations-q07', 'gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations', 'The total number of relations on a set with 3 elements is:', '512', '64', '8', '729', 'A', 'Relations on an n-set number 2^(n^2); for n = 3 that is 2^9 = 512.', 6),
  ('gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations-q08', 'gate-discrete-math-set-theory-relations', 'An equivalence relation on a set induces a:', 'Total ordering', 'Partition into disjoint classes', 'Single element', 'Cyclic group', 'B', 'An equivalence relation partitions the set into disjoint equivalence classes.', 7),
  ('gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra-q01', 'gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra', 'A group requires closure, associativity, an identity element and:', 'An inverse for every element', 'Commutativity', 'A zero divisor', 'A maximum element', 'A', 'A group needs each element to have an inverse, in addition to the other axioms.', 0),
  ('gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra-q02', 'gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra', 'A group in which the operation is commutative is called:', 'Abelian', 'Cyclic', 'Simple', 'Trivial', 'A', 'A commutative group is called an abelian group.', 1),
  ('gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra-q03', 'gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra', 'Lagrange''s theorem states that the order of any subgroup:', 'Equals the group order', 'Divides the order of the group', 'Is always prime', 'Is always 1', 'B', 'By Lagrange''s theorem, a subgroup''s order divides the group''s order.', 2),
  ('gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra-q04', 'gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra', 'An algebraic structure with closure and associativity but not necessarily an identity is a:', 'Group', 'Semigroup', 'Monoid', 'Field', 'B', 'A semigroup only requires closure and associativity.', 3),
  ('gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra-q05', 'gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra', 'Every cyclic group is necessarily:', 'Infinite', 'Abelian', 'Non-abelian', 'A field', 'B', 'A cyclic group is generated by one element and is therefore always abelian.', 4),
  ('gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra-q06', 'gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra', 'A commutative ring in which every non-zero element has a multiplicative inverse is a:', 'Field', 'Group', 'Semigroup', 'Monoid', 'A', 'A field is a commutative ring where every non-zero element is invertible.', 5),
  ('gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra-q07', 'gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra', 'A semigroup that also contains an identity element is called a:', 'Monoid', 'Group', 'Field', 'Ring', 'A', 'A monoid is a semigroup with an identity element.', 6),
  ('gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra-q08', 'gate-discrete-math-group-theory-algebra', 'The order of an element a in a group is the smallest positive integer k such that:', 'a + k = 0', 'a^k = 0', 'k * a = a', 'a^k equals the identity', 'D', 'The order of a is the least k for which a raised to k equals the identity.', 7),
  ('gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences-q01', 'gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences', 'The number of ways to arrange 4 distinct books in a row is:', '4', '24', '16', '256', 'B', 'Arrangements of 4 distinct items number 4! = 24.', 0),
  ('gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences-q02', 'gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences', 'The number of ways to choose 2 items from 5 distinct items (order ignored) is:', '60', '20', '25', '10', 'D', '5C2 = 5! / (2! 3!) = 10.', 1),
  ('gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences-q03', 'gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences', 'The pigeonhole principle guarantees that placing 11 items into 10 boxes forces:', 'Every box to be empty', 'At least one box with two items', 'Exactly one item per box', 'No box used twice', 'B', 'With more items than boxes, at least one box must hold two or more items.', 2),
  ('gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences-q04', 'gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences', 'The characteristic equation of the recurrence a_n = 5 a_(n-1) - 6 a_(n-2) is:', 'x^2 - 6x + 5 = 0', 'x^2 + 5x + 6 = 0', 'x^2 - 5x + 6 = 0', 'x^2 - 5x - 6 = 0', 'C', 'Substituting a_n = x^n gives x^2 = 5x - 6, that is x^2 - 5x + 6 = 0.', 3),
  ('gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences-q05', 'gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences', 'The number of distinct arrangements of the letters in the word LEVEL is:', '30', '60', '120', '24', 'A', 'LEVEL has 5 letters with L twice and E twice: 5! / (2! 2!) = 30.', 4),
  ('gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences-q06', 'gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences', 'The number of circular permutations of 5 distinct objects is:', '120', '60', '24', '20', 'C', 'Circular permutations of n objects number (n-1)! = 4! = 24.', 5),
  ('gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences-q07', 'gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences', 'The sum of all binomial coefficients for exponent n, that is the sum of nCk over k, equals:', 'n', 'n^2', 'n!', '2^n', 'D', 'The binomial coefficients for exponent n sum to 2^n.', 6),
  ('gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences-q08', 'gate-discrete-math-counting-recurrences', 'A generating function encodes a sequence as the coefficients of a:', 'Truth table', 'Determinant', 'Power series', 'Permutation matrix', 'C', 'A generating function represents a sequence as coefficients in a power series.', 7),
  ('cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards-q01', 'cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards', 'When the applicable local law is less strict than the CFA Institute Code and Standards, a member must comply with the:', 'Code and Standards, because they are stricter', 'less strict local law, since law overrides the Code', 'law of the member''s home country only', 'employer''s internal policy regardless of either', 'A', 'Members must always follow the stricter of applicable law or the Code and Standards.', 0),
  ('cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards-q02', 'cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards', 'An analyst combines several pieces of public and nonmaterial nonpublic information to form a buy recommendation. This approach is best described as:', 'a violation of the prohibition on insider trading', 'the Mosaic Theory, which is permitted', 'front running of client orders', 'a breach of the duty of loyalty to employers', 'B', 'The Mosaic Theory permits combining public and nonmaterial nonpublic information.', 1),
  ('cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards-q03', 'cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards', 'Under the duty of loyalty, prudence, and care, a member managing client assets must place the interests of:', 'the employer ahead of all other parties', 'the member ahead of the client to ensure retention', 'the client ahead of the member''s and employer''s', 'regulators ahead of the client at all times', 'C', 'Standard III requires client interests come before the member''s and employer''s.', 2),
  ('cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards-q04', 'cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards', 'The Standard on Fair Dealing requires that a member disseminating an investment recommendation must:', 'give every client an identical position size', 'notify only the firm''s largest clients first', 'treat all clients fairly, though not necessarily equally', 'delay all trades until every client has acted', 'C', 'Fair Dealing requires fair, not identical, treatment of all clients.', 3),
  ('cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards-q05', 'cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards', 'A portfolio manager receives material nonpublic information about a pending acquisition. The most appropriate action is to:', 'trade quickly before the information becomes public', 'share it only with the firm''s best clients', 'use it but disclose the source afterward', 'refrain from acting or causing others to act on it', 'D', 'Standard II(A) prohibits acting or causing others to act on material nonpublic information.', 4),
  ('cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards-q06', 'cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards', 'Which Standard most directly governs the disclosure of referral fees and the priority of transactions?', 'Investment Analysis and Recommendations', 'Integrity of Capital Markets', 'Duties to Employers', 'Conflicts of Interest', 'D', 'Standard VI Conflicts of Interest covers disclosure, priority of transactions, and referral fees.', 5),
  ('cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards-q07', 'cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards', 'A member who accepts a gift from a client that could affect independence should, under the Standards:', 'decline all client communication going forward', 'keep the gift secret to avoid embarrassment', 'resign from managing the client''s account', 'disclose the gift to the employer to preserve independence', 'D', 'Disclosure to the employer protects independence and objectivity under Standard I(B).', 6),
  ('cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards-q08', 'cfa-ethics-code-of-ethics-standards', 'Engaging in conduct that compromises the reputation or integrity of the CFA designation is a violation of the Standard on:', 'Duties to Clients', 'Market manipulation', 'Responsibilities as a CFA Institute Member or Candidate', 'Suitability of recommendations', 'C', 'Standard VII addresses conduct that compromises the CFA designation''s reputation.', 7),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money-q01', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money', 'An investor deposits 1,000 at an annual rate of 8% compounded annually. What is the value after 3 years?', '1,240.00', '1,080.00', '1,259.71', '1,360.49', 'C', 'FV = 1000 * (1.08)^3 = 1000 * 1.259712 = 1,259.71.', 0),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money-q02', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money', 'Compared with an otherwise identical ordinary annuity, the present value of an annuity due is:', 'higher, because each payment is received one period sooner', 'the same, since the cash flows are equal', 'lower, because payments arrive later', 'undefined without the discount rate', 'A', 'Annuity-due payments arrive one period earlier, so their present value is higher.', 1),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money-q03', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money', 'A stated annual rate of 12% compounded monthly produces an effective annual rate closest to:', '12.00%', '12.36%', '11.39%', '12.68%', 'D', 'EAR = (1 + 0.12/12)^12 - 1 = 1.01^12 - 1 = 12.68%.', 2),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money-q04', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money', 'A perpetuity pays 50 per year forever. If the required return is 10%, its present value is:', '450', '550', '5,000', '500', 'D', 'PV of a perpetuity = PMT / r = 50 / 0.10 = 500.', 3),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money-q05', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money', 'Holding the stated annual rate constant, increasing the compounding frequency causes the effective annual rate to:', 'decrease toward zero', 'rise above the stated rate', 'fall below the stated rate', 'stay exactly equal to the stated rate', 'B', 'More frequent compounding raises the effective annual rate above the stated rate.', 4),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money-q06', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money', 'What is the present value of 5,000 to be received in 4 years if the annual discount rate is 6%?', '3,960', '4,158', '4,717', '3,711', 'A', 'PV = 5000 / (1.06)^4 = 5000 / 1.26248 = 3,960.', 5),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money-q07', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money', 'Using continuous compounding, the future value of a single sum is found with the factor:', '(1 + r)^n', '(1 + r/m)^(m*n)', 'e^(r*n)', '1 / (1 + r)^n', 'C', 'Continuous compounding uses FV = PV * e^(r*n).', 6),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money-q08', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-time-value-of-money', 'The most common time-value error when valuing a semiannual-pay bond is failing to:', 'discount the maturity value at all', 'include the coupon in present value', 'use a calculator instead of a formula', 'match the rate and number of periods to the same frequency', 'D', 'Rate and period count must use the same frequency; a mismatch is the classic TVM error.', 7),
  ('cfa-economics-market-structures-q01', 'cfa-economics-market-structures', 'In perfect competition, the demand curve facing an individual firm is best described as:', 'downward sloping and steep', 'perfectly elastic (horizontal)', 'perfectly inelastic (vertical)', 'upward sloping', 'B', 'A price-taking firm in perfect competition faces a horizontal, perfectly elastic demand curve.', 0),
  ('cfa-economics-market-structures-q02', 'cfa-economics-market-structures', 'A profit-maximizing firm in any market structure produces the quantity where:', 'price equals average total cost', 'total revenue is at its maximum', 'marginal revenue equals marginal cost', 'average cost equals average revenue', 'C', 'Profit is maximized where marginal revenue equals marginal cost in every structure.', 1),
  ('cfa-economics-market-structures-q03', 'cfa-economics-market-structures', 'In long-run equilibrium under perfect competition, economic profit for the typical firm is:', 'maximized and positive', 'zero because free entry erodes profit', 'negative but improving', 'equal to accounting profit', 'B', 'Free entry drives long-run economic profit to zero in perfect competition.', 2),
  ('cfa-economics-market-structures-q04', 'cfa-economics-market-structures', 'Which market structure is characterized by a single seller facing the entire downward-sloping market demand curve?', 'Perfect competition', 'Monopoly', 'Oligopoly', 'Monopolistic competition', 'B', 'A monopoly is one seller facing the whole downward-sloping market demand curve.', 3),
  ('cfa-economics-market-structures-q05', 'cfa-economics-market-structures', 'A key limitation of the N-firm concentration ratio relative to the Herfindahl-Hirschman Index is that the ratio:', 'cannot be computed without total revenue', 'applies only to monopolies', 'always exceeds 100 percent', 'is unaffected by a merger between two leading firms', 'D', 'The concentration ratio can miss mergers among top firms, which the HHI captures.', 4),
  ('cfa-economics-market-structures-q06', 'cfa-economics-market-structures', 'Monopolistic competition differs from perfect competition primarily because firms in it:', 'face no barriers to entry whatsoever', 'are pure price takers with no pricing power', 'produce an identical, homogeneous product', 'sell differentiated products and have some pricing power', 'D', 'Monopolistic competition features product differentiation, giving firms some pricing power.', 5),
  ('cfa-economics-market-structures-q07', 'cfa-economics-market-structures', 'Which of the following is most likely a source of long-lasting monopoly power?', 'Many close substitute products', 'Patents and significant economies of scale', 'Free and immediate entry of rivals', 'Homogeneous goods and perfect information', 'B', 'Patents and large economies of scale create high barriers that sustain monopoly power.', 6),
  ('cfa-economics-market-structures-q08', 'cfa-economics-market-structures', 'An industry with a small number of large interdependent firms and high entry barriers is best classified as:', 'perfect competition', 'an oligopoly', 'monopolistic competition', 'a pure monopoly', 'B', 'Few interdependent firms with high barriers describe an oligopoly.', 7),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis-q01', 'cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis', 'The quick ratio differs from the current ratio mainly because the quick ratio excludes:', 'inventory', 'accounts receivable', 'cash and cash equivalents', 'marketable securities', 'A', 'The quick ratio removes inventory, the least liquid current asset.', 0),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis-q02', 'cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis', 'A firm has net income of 200 and total equity of 1,000. Its return on equity is:', '5%', '10%', '20%', '200%', 'C', 'ROE = net income / equity = 200 / 1000 = 20%.', 1),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis-q03', 'cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis', 'In the three-part DuPont identity, return on equity equals the product of net profit margin, asset turnover, and:', 'the current ratio', 'financial leverage', 'interest coverage', 'the dividend payout ratio', 'B', 'Three-part DuPont: ROE = net margin * asset turnover * financial leverage.', 2),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis-q04', 'cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis', 'If a company''s ROE rises only because it took on substantially more debt, the increase most likely reflects:', 'improved operating profitability', 'greater financial leverage and higher risk', 'faster inventory turnover', 'a higher gross margin', 'B', 'A leverage-driven ROE gain signals more financial risk, not better operations.', 3),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis-q05', 'cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis', 'The interest coverage ratio is calculated as:', 'EBIT divided by interest expense', 'net income divided by interest expense', 'total debt divided by EBIT', 'revenue divided by interest expense', 'A', 'Interest coverage = EBIT / interest expense.', 4),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis-q06', 'cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis', 'Cost of goods sold is 800 and average inventory is 200. Inventory turnover is:', '4.0 times', '2.0 times', '0.25 times', '1.6 times', 'A', 'Inventory turnover = COGS / average inventory = 800 / 200 = 4.0.', 5),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis-q07', 'cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis', 'A current ratio below 1.0 most directly suggests that a firm may have:', 'excessive long-term debt', 'a high gross margin', 'very high profitability', 'weak short-term liquidity', 'D', 'A current ratio under 1.0 means current liabilities exceed current assets, signaling weak liquidity.', 6),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis-q08', 'cfa-financial-reporting-financial-ratios-analysis', 'To interpret a single financial ratio meaningfully, an analyst should primarily compare it with:', 'the risk-free rate of interest', 'the company''s history and industry peers', 'the firm''s stock price', 'the prevailing inflation rate', 'B', 'Ratios are meaningful only against trend and peer benchmarks, not in isolation.', 7),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital-q01', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital', 'In the weighted average cost of capital, the cost of debt is multiplied by (1 - t) because:', 'dividends are tax-deductible', 'debt has no maturity', 'equity is riskier than debt', 'interest expense is tax-deductible', 'D', 'Interest is tax-deductible, so the relevant cost of debt is after-tax: Rd * (1 - t).', 0),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital-q02', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital', 'A firm has a beta of 1.2, a risk-free rate of 3%, and an equity risk premium of 5%. Its CAPM cost of equity is:', '8.0%', '6.0%', '9.0%', '11.0%', 'C', 'Re = 3% + 1.2 * 5% = 3% + 6% = 9.0%.', 1),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital-q03', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital', 'When estimating WACC, the weights for debt and equity should ideally be based on:', 'book values from the balance sheet', 'target market-value proportions', 'historical issuance prices', 'par values of the securities', 'B', 'WACC weights should use target capital structure at market values.', 2),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital-q04', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital', 'A firm is financed 40% by debt and 60% by equity. With an after-tax cost of debt of 5% and cost of equity of 10%, the WACC is:', '7.5%', '6.5%', '9.0%', '8.0%', 'D', 'WACC = 0.40 * 5% + 0.60 * 10% = 2% + 6% = 8.0%.', 3),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital-q05', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital', 'Applying the firm''s overall WACC to a project that is much riskier than the firm''s average operations will most likely:', 'overstate the project''s value by understating risk', 'correctly value the project', 'have no effect on the decision', 'understate the project''s expected cash flows', 'A', 'Using too low a discount rate for a riskier project overstates its value.', 4),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital-q06', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital', 'Using the dividend discount approach, the cost of equity equals the dividend yield plus the:', 'risk-free rate', 'after-tax cost of debt', 'constant dividend growth rate', 'market risk premium', 'C', 'DDM cost of equity = D1 / P0 + g, the dividend yield plus growth.', 5),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital-q07', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital', 'A bond yields 8% before tax and the marginal tax rate is 25%. The after-tax cost of debt is:', '8.0%', '2.0%', '6.0%', '10.0%', 'C', 'After-tax cost of debt = 8% * (1 - 0.25) = 6.0%.', 6),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital-q08', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-cost-of-capital', 'In capital budgeting, the WACC is most appropriately used as the:', 'growth rate of cash flows', 'discount rate for projects of average firm risk', 'terminal value multiple', 'inflation adjustment factor', 'B', 'WACC is the discount rate for projects with risk similar to the firm''s average.', 7),
  ('cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm-q01', 'cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm', 'A stock will pay a dividend of 2.00 next year, grows at 4% forever, and has a required return of 9%. Its Gordon growth value is:', '40.00', '22.22', '50.00', '25.00', 'A', 'V0 = D1 / (r - g) = 2.00 / (0.09 - 0.04) = 2.00 / 0.05 = 40.00.', 0),
  ('cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm-q02', 'cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm', 'The Gordon growth model becomes mathematically invalid when the growth rate is:', 'less than the required return', 'equal to zero', 'negative', 'greater than or equal to the required return', 'D', 'The model requires r greater than g; otherwise (r - g) is zero or negative.', 1),
  ('cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm-q03', 'cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm', 'A firm retains 60% of earnings and earns an ROE of 15%. Its sustainable growth rate is:', '6.0%', '9.0%', '15.0%', '25.0%', 'B', 'g = retention * ROE = 0.60 * 15% = 9.0%.', 2),
  ('cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm-q04', 'cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm', 'The dividend discount model is least appropriate for valuing a company that:', 'pays no dividends and reinvests all earnings', 'pays a stable, growing dividend', 'has a long dividend history', 'operates in a mature industry', 'A', 'The DDM cannot value firms that pay no dividends; use cash-flow models instead.', 3),
  ('cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm-q05', 'cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm', 'In a multistage DDM, the terminal value is most commonly estimated using the:', 'Gordon growth model at the start of the stable phase', 'current dividend yield only', 'book value of equity', 'average historical share price', 'A', 'Terminal value uses the Gordon model at the onset of the constant-growth stage.', 4),
  ('cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm-q06', 'cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm', 'If next year''s dividend is 3.00 and the stock is valued at 60 using the Gordon model with 3% growth, the required return is:', '8%', '6%', '5%', '3%', 'A', 'r = D1/V0 + g = 3/60 + 0.03 = 0.05 + 0.03 = 8%.', 5),
  ('cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm-q07', 'cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm', 'The retention ratio used in the sustainable growth formula equals:', 'the dividend payout ratio', 'one minus the dividend payout ratio', 'dividends divided by net income', 'the price-to-earnings ratio', 'B', 'Retention ratio b = 1 - payout ratio.', 6),
  ('cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm-q08', 'cfa-equity-equity-valuation-ddm', 'A notable weakness of the Gordon growth model is that its output is highly sensitive to small changes in the:', 'number of shares outstanding', 'current market price', 'company''s tax rate', 'spread between the required return and growth rate', 'D', 'Value is extremely sensitive to the (r - g) denominator, so small input changes swing it sharply.', 7),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity-q01', 'cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity', 'A bond has a modified duration of 6. If its yield rises by 0.5%, the bond''s price will change by approximately:', '+3.0%', '-0.5%', '-3.0%', '+6.0%', 'C', 'Price change ~ -ModDur * dy = -6 * 0.005 = -3.0%.', 0),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity-q02', 'cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity', 'Holding other factors constant, a bond with a lower coupon rate will have a duration that is:', 'lower', 'higher', 'unchanged', 'always equal to its maturity', 'B', 'Lower coupons push cash flows later, raising duration.', 1),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity-q03', 'cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity', 'The Macaulay duration of a zero-coupon bond is equal to its:', 'coupon rate', 'current yield', 'convexity', 'time to maturity', 'D', 'A zero-coupon bond has a single cash flow, so its Macaulay duration equals its maturity.', 2),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity-q04', 'cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity', 'Convexity is added to a duration-based price estimate primarily to improve accuracy for:', 'very small yield changes', 'large yield changes', 'floating-rate notes only', 'changes in credit spreads only', 'B', 'Duration is linear; convexity corrects the estimate for large yield moves.', 3),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity-q05', 'cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity', 'For a bond with positive convexity, when yields move by equal amounts in each direction, the price:', 'rises more when yields fall than it falls when yields rise', 'falls more when yields rise than it rises when yields fall', 'changes by exactly the same amount either way', 'is unaffected by the direction of the move', 'A', 'Positive convexity means gains from falling yields exceed losses from equal rising yields.', 4),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity-q06', 'cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity', 'Modified duration is obtained from Macaulay duration by:', 'multiplying by (1 + y/m)', 'subtracting the convexity', 'dividing by (1 + y/m)', 'adding the current yield', 'C', 'Modified duration = Macaulay duration / (1 + y/m).', 5),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity-q07', 'cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity', 'All else equal, increasing a bond''s time to maturity generally causes its interest-rate sensitivity to:', 'decrease', 'increase', 'stay constant', 'become zero', 'B', 'Longer maturity raises duration and thus interest-rate sensitivity.', 6),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity-q08', 'cfa-fixed-income-duration-convexity', 'A bond has a modified duration of 5 and convexity of 80. For a yield drop of 1%, the estimated price change is closest to:', '+5.0%', '+4.6%', '-4.6%', '+5.4%', 'D', 'Change ~ -5*(-0.01) + 0.5*80*(0.01)^2 = 0.05 + 0.004 = 5.4%.', 7),
  ('cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity-q01', 'cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity', 'Put-call parity states that a call plus the present value of the strike equals:', 'a put plus the underlying stock', 'a put minus the underlying stock', 'the underlying stock alone', 'two calls minus a put', 'A', 'Parity: C + PV(K) = P + S, the fiduciary call equals the protective put.', 0),
  ('cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity-q02', 'cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity', 'A stock trades at 50, a call and put share a strike of 50, the put costs 4, and PV of the strike is 48. The call value is:', '2', '4', '8', '6', 'D', 'C = P + S - PV(K) = 4 + 50 - 48 = 6.', 1),
  ('cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity-q03', 'cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity', 'The combination of a long put and a long share of the underlying stock is known as a:', 'protective put', 'covered call', 'fiduciary call', 'bull spread', 'A', 'Put plus stock is a protective put, the right side of the parity identity.', 2),
  ('cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity-q04', 'cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity', 'Put-call parity holds strictly for European options written on an underlying that pays:', 'a large continuous dividend', 'no dividends', 'variable dividends', 'interest semiannually', 'B', 'Standard parity assumes European options on a non-dividend-paying underlying.', 3),
  ('cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity-q05', 'cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity', 'A synthetic long put can be constructed from a long call, a short position in the stock, and a:', 'long forward contract', 'short call at a different strike', 'second long call', 'long bond (lend at the risk-free rate)', 'D', 'Synthetic put = call - stock + bond, where the bond is risk-free lending.', 4),
  ('cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity-q06', 'cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity', 'If observed market prices violate put-call parity, an investor can most likely earn a profit through:', 'arbitrage by buying the cheaper side and selling the dearer side', 'writing only naked puts', 'holding the underlying to maturity', 'buying both the call and the put', 'A', 'A parity violation permits riskless arbitrage between the two equivalent sides.', 5),
  ('cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity-q07', 'cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity', 'The present value of the strike price in the parity equation is computed by discounting the strike at the:', 'risk-free rate', 'dividend yield', 'stock''s expected return', 'implied volatility', 'A', 'PV(K) = K / (1 + r)^T uses the risk-free rate r.', 6),
  ('cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity-q08', 'cfa-derivatives-options-put-call-parity', 'When the underlying pays dividends before expiration, the value used for the stock in put-call parity should be:', 'the spot price increased by the dividends', 'unchanged from the spot price', 'the spot price reduced by the present value of the dividends', 'the strike price', 'C', 'Dividends reduce the effective stock value by the present value of those dividends.', 7),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity-q01', 'cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity', 'Under a typical 2-and-20 fee structure, the 20% portion represents the:', 'annual management fee on assets', 'incentive fee on profits above a hurdle', 'redemption penalty', 'administrative expense ratio', 'B', 'The 20% is an incentive fee charged on profits, often above a hurdle rate.', 0),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity-q02', 'cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity', 'A high-water mark provision ensures that incentive fees are charged only on:', 'the original capital contributed', 'gross assets each year', 'new net profits above the prior peak value', 'the management fee base', 'C', 'A high-water mark restricts incentive fees to new profits above the previous peak.', 1),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity-q03', 'cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity', 'The private-equity J-curve describes a fund''s tendency to show, in its early years:', 'immediate strong positive returns', 'perfectly flat returns', 'negative returns from fees and early write-downs', 'returns identical to public equities', 'C', 'The J-curve reflects early negative returns from fees and write-downs before later gains.', 2),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity-q04', 'cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity', 'A leveraged buyout fund typically acquires:', 'early-stage startups with venture financing', 'publicly traded bonds only', 'diversified index portfolios', 'mature companies using a large amount of debt', 'D', 'LBO buyout funds acquire mature firms financed largely with debt.', 3),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity-q05', 'cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity', 'Which hedge fund strategy seeks to profit primarily from announced mergers and corporate reorganizations?', 'Global macro', 'Equity market neutral', 'Event-driven', 'Convertible arbitrage', 'C', 'Event-driven strategies target mergers, distressed, and special-situation events.', 4),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity-q06', 'cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity', 'Reported hedge fund index returns are often overstated because of survivorship and:', 'mark-to-market accounting', 'inflation indexing', 'backfill bias', 'currency hedging', 'C', 'Survivorship and backfill biases inflate reported hedge fund index returns.', 5),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity-q07', 'cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity', 'Which of the following is a common exit route for a private equity investment?', 'Margin call', 'Coupon payment', 'Reverse stock split', 'Initial public offering or trade sale', 'D', 'PE investments exit through IPOs, trade sales, or secondary sales.', 6),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity-q08', 'cfa-alternative-investments-hedge-funds-private-equity', 'A defining liquidity characteristic shared by hedge funds and private equity is that investors typically face:', 'daily redemption at net asset value', 'no fees on withdrawals', 'lock-up periods that restrict withdrawals', 'government-guaranteed principal', 'C', 'Both impose lock-up periods, making them relatively illiquid investments.', 7),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm-q01', 'cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm', 'Under the CAPM, an asset with a beta of 1.5, a risk-free rate of 2%, and a market return of 8% has an expected return of:', '11%', '9%', '12%', '8%', 'A', 'E(R) = 2% + 1.5 * (8% - 2%) = 2% + 9% = 11%.', 0),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm-q02', 'cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm', 'According to portfolio theory, the type of risk that earns no risk premium because it can be diversified away is:', 'systematic risk', 'market risk', 'unsystematic (firm-specific) risk', 'interest-rate risk', 'C', 'Diversifiable unsystematic risk earns no premium; only systematic risk is rewarded.', 1),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm-q03', 'cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm', 'The diversification benefit of combining two assets into a portfolio is greatest when their correlation is:', 'as low as possible', 'exactly +1', 'exactly equal to the betas', 'equal to the risk-free rate', 'A', 'Lower correlation increases diversification; perfect positive correlation gives no benefit.', 2),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm-q04', 'cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm', 'In the CAPM, the market risk premium is represented by the term:', 'the market return minus the risk-free rate', 'beta times the standard deviation', 'the risk-free rate', 'the Sharpe ratio', 'A', 'The market risk premium equals the market return minus the risk-free rate (Rm - Rf).', 3),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm-q05', 'cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm', 'A stock with a beta greater than 1.0 is expected to be:', 'less volatile than the overall market', 'more volatile than the overall market', 'uncorrelated with the market', 'risk-free', 'B', 'A beta above 1.0 implies greater volatility than the market.', 4),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm-q06', 'cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm', 'The Sharpe ratio measures the excess return of a portfolio per unit of its:', 'beta', 'tracking error', 'unsystematic risk only', 'total risk (standard deviation)', 'D', 'The Sharpe ratio divides excess return by total risk (standard deviation).', 5),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm-q07', 'cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm', 'The expected return of a two-asset portfolio is calculated as the:', 'product of the two asset returns', 'weighted average of the asset variances', 'weighted average of the asset returns', 'square root of the covariance', 'C', 'Portfolio return is the weighted average of the component asset returns.', 6),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm-q08', 'cfa-portfolio-management-portfolio-risk-return-capm', 'A stock with very high total volatility but a low beta will, under the CAPM, have a required return that is:', 'modest because only systematic risk is priced', 'very high because total volatility is priced', 'equal to the market return', 'below the risk-free rate', 'A', 'CAPM prices only systematic risk, so a low-beta stock has a modest required return despite high volatility.', 7),
  ('cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info-q01', 'cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info', 'An analyst obtains a tip from a company insider about unannounced earnings that are significantly above consensus. Acting on this information would most likely violate:', 'Standard II(A) - Material Nonpublic Information', 'Standard I(C) - Misrepresentation', 'Standard III(A) - Loyalty, Prudence, and Care', 'Standard VI(B) - Priority of Transactions', 'A', 'Standard II(A) prohibits members from acting or causing others to act on material nonpublic information. Unannounced earnings well above consensus would clearly be material and nonpublic.', 0),
  ('cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info-q02', 'cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info', 'Under the mosaic theory, an analyst may legally act on investment conclusions derived from:', 'A combination of public information and nonmaterial nonpublic information', 'Material nonpublic information obtained from a corporate officer', 'Insider information obtained through a personal relationship', 'Nonpublic information obtained through channel checks regardless of materiality', 'A', 'Mosaic theory permits combining individually nonmaterial nonpublic information with public information to reach an investment conclusion, as long as no single piece is itself material and nonpublic.', 1),
  ('cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info-q03', 'cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info', 'Which of the following best describes information-based market manipulation under Standard II(B)?', 'Spreading false or misleading information to affect security prices', 'Trading large volumes to move a security''s price artificially', 'Front-running client orders for personal gain', 'Recommending securities without disclosing a conflict of interest', 'A', 'Standard II(B) prohibits information-based manipulation, which involves spreading false or misleading information to distort prices. Transaction-based manipulation (option A) is also prohibited but is a different form.', 2),
  ('cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info-q04', 'cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info', 'A portfolio manager accidentally overhears corporate executives discussing an imminent merger in an elevator. The most appropriate course of action is to:', 'Trade immediately before the information becomes public', 'Share the information only with the firm''s most important clients', 'Refrain from trading and notify the firm''s compliance department', 'Continue normal trading activity since the information was obtained unintentionally', 'C', 'The manner in which MNPI is obtained is irrelevant — once in possession of MNPI, a member must not trade on it and should report the situation to compliance immediately.', 3),
  ('cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info-q05', 'cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info', 'Which of the following pieces of information would most likely be considered material?', 'A change in a company''s cafeteria vendor', 'A planned acquisition of a competitor at a 40% premium', 'A minor update to the company''s website design', 'An analyst''s routine maintenance of a financial model', 'B', 'A planned acquisition at a significant premium would almost certainly affect a reasonable investor''s decision and the company''s stock price, making it material information.', 4),
  ('cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info-q06', 'cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info', 'A firm''s investment banking division is advising on a pending acquisition. The equity research division learns of the deal through an internal information leak. The best way for the firm to prevent a violation is to:', 'Restrict trading in the target company across all client accounts', 'Maintain an effective information barrier between the two divisions', 'Require all research analysts to sign non-disclosure agreements', 'Report the transaction to the SEC before trading occurs', 'B', 'Information barriers (Chinese walls) are the standard mechanism for preventing MNPI from flowing between a firm''s investment banking and public-side divisions, which is a core compliance requirement.', 5),
  ('cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info-q07', 'cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info', 'Wash trading — simultaneously buying and selling the same security to create the appearance of active trading — is an example of:', 'A violation of Standard II(B) - Market Manipulation', 'A violation of Standard II(A) - Material Nonpublic Information', 'A violation of Standard V(A) - Diligence and Reasonable Basis', 'Permitted activity if disclosed to regulators', 'A', 'Wash trading is a classic form of transaction-based market manipulation, explicitly prohibited under Standard II(B), as it artificially inflates trading volume and misleads other investors.', 6),
  ('cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info-q08', 'cfa-ethics-material-non-public-info', 'For information to qualify as ''material,'' it must meet which standard?', 'It must have been published in a financial newspaper within the past week', 'It must cause at least a 5% change in the security''s price', 'A reasonable investor would consider it important in making an investment decision', 'It must come directly from a company''s CEO or CFO', 'C', 'The CFA Institute standard for materiality is whether a reasonable investor would consider the information important in making an investment decision or whether it would likely affect the security''s price.', 7),
  ('cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients-q01', 'cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients', 'Under Standard III(C) - Suitability, before recommending a high-yield bond fund to a new client, a member must first:', 'Obtain written approval from the firm''s compliance department', 'Ensure the fund has at least a five-year track record', 'Disclose all fees and commissions associated with the fund', 'Determine the client''s investment objectives, risk tolerance, and constraints', 'D', 'Standard III(C) requires that a member understand the client''s investment profile — including objectives, risk tolerance, time horizon, and constraints — before any recommendation is made.', 0),
  ('cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients-q02', 'cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients', 'A portfolio manager releases an upgrade on a stock to top-tier clients two hours before distributing it to all other clients. This most likely violates:', 'Standard III(A) - Loyalty, Prudence, and Care', 'Standard III(E) - Preservation of Confidentiality', 'Standard III(B) - Fair Dealing', 'Standard IV(C) - Responsibilities of Supervisors', 'C', 'Standard III(B) requires that investment recommendations be disseminated to all clients simultaneously or through a process that is fair to all. Giving preferred clients advance access is a violation of fair dealing.', 1),
  ('cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients-q03', 'cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients', 'Which of the following is least likely to be considered a violation of Standard III(E) - Preservation of Confidentiality?', 'Reporting a client''s suspected money laundering activity to regulatory authorities', 'Sharing a client''s portfolio holdings with the firm''s marketing team', 'Disclosing a client''s trading activity to a journalist', 'Discussing a client''s personal financial situation at a social gathering', 'A', 'Standard III(E) permits disclosure of confidential client information when required by law, which includes reporting suspected illegal activity such as money laundering to the appropriate authorities.', 2),
  ('cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients-q04', 'cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients', 'A fiduciary duty of loyalty under Standard III(A) requires members to:', 'Maximize absolute returns for every client regardless of stated objectives', 'Invest only in securities with a minimum investment-grade credit rating', 'Place client interests ahead of their own personal interests', 'Consult with clients before every portfolio trade', 'C', 'The duty of loyalty under Standard III(A) requires members to always act in clients'' best interests and not subordinate client needs to personal benefit or the firm''s interests.', 3),
  ('cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients-q05', 'cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients', 'A member managing a discretionary portfolio for a risk-averse, retired client invests 60% of the portfolio in speculative small-cap stocks without consulting the client. This most likely violates:', 'Standard II(B) - Market Manipulation', 'Standard VI(A) - Disclosure of Conflicts', 'Standard V(B) - Communication with Clients', 'Standard III(C) - Suitability', 'D', 'Investing a conservative, retired client''s portfolio heavily in speculative securities is inconsistent with the client''s stated risk profile and violates the suitability obligation under Standard III(C).', 4),
  ('cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients-q06', 'cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients', 'Which of the following actions is consistent with Standard III(A) - Loyalty, Prudence, and Care?', 'Voting client proxies in a manner that benefits the firm''s investment banking relationships', 'Abstaining from all proxy votes to avoid conflicts of interest', 'Voting client proxies in the best interest of the clients', 'Allowing clients to direct all proxy votes regardless of the member''s fiduciary duty', 'C', 'Members must vote proxies in the best interest of clients, which is a core component of the duty of care and loyalty under Standard III(A). Allowing business relationships to influence proxy votes would be a violation.', 5),
  ('cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients-q07', 'cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients', 'Standard III(B) - Fair Dealing does not require members to:', 'Treat all clients equally in terms of services offered', 'Disseminate investment recommendations simultaneously to all clients', 'Give all clients the opportunity to act on investment recommendations', 'Avoid selective disclosure that benefits certain clients', 'A', 'Fair dealing requires equitable — not necessarily equal — treatment. Firms may offer different levels of service to different client segments as long as this is disclosed and does not involve selective disclosure of recommendations.', 6),
  ('cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients-q08', 'cfa-ethics-duties-to-clients', 'A client''s investment policy statement (IPS) specifies no investment in tobacco companies. The portfolio manager purchases shares in a tobacco firm because it offers excellent risk-adjusted returns. This action most directly violates:', 'Standard III(B) - Fair Dealing', 'Standard III(A) - Loyalty, Prudence, and Care', 'Standard V(A) - Diligence and Reasonable Basis', 'Standard VI(C) - Referral Fees', 'B', 'Overriding a client''s explicit investment constraint (e.g., socially responsible investing restrictions) to pursue returns is a breach of loyalty and prudence, as the member must follow the client''s stated objectives and constraints.', 7),
  ('cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest-q01', 'cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest', 'An analyst owns shares in a company and issues a buy recommendation on that company''s stock. Under Standard VI(A), the analyst must:', 'Divest the shares before publishing the recommendation', 'Refrain from issuing any recommendation on the company', 'Obtain written consent from clients before proceeding', 'Disclose the ownership interest in the recommendation', 'D', 'Standard VI(A) requires disclosure of conflicts — including personal ownership of recommended securities — but does not necessarily require divestiture. Full, prominent disclosure allows clients to assess the objectivity of the recommendation.', 0),
  ('cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest-q02', 'cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest', 'Which of the following sequences correctly reflects the order of transaction priority under Standard VI(B)?', 'Client accounts, employer accounts, member accounts', 'Employer accounts, client accounts, member accounts', 'Member accounts, client accounts, employer accounts', 'Client accounts, member accounts, employer accounts', 'A', 'Standard VI(B) establishes that client transactions must take priority first, then employer (proprietary) accounts, and personal accounts of the member last.', 1),
  ('cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest-q03', 'cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest', 'A member receives a referral fee from a third-party money manager for directing clients to that manager. Under Standard VI(C), the member must:', 'Return the referral fee to the client', 'Obtain regulatory approval before accepting referral fees', 'Cease the referral relationship immediately', 'Disclose the referral fee arrangement to clients', 'D', 'Standard VI(C) requires disclosure of any referral compensation so that clients can evaluate whether the referral is in their best interest or influenced by the member''s financial incentive.', 2),
  ('cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest-q04', 'cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest', 'A portfolio manager learns that a large client is about to place a substantial buy order for a thinly traded stock. Before executing the client''s order, the manager buys shares for her personal account. This is known as:', 'Scalping', 'Churning', 'Front-running', 'Painting the tape', 'C', 'Front-running is the prohibited practice of trading for personal accounts ahead of known client orders, violating the priority of transactions requirement under Standard VI(B).', 3),
  ('cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest-q05', 'cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest', 'A member sits on the board of directors of a company that he also covers as an equity analyst. Under Standard VI(A), the member should:', 'Resign from the board immediately to eliminate the conflict', 'Disclose the board membership in all research reports covering the company', 'Only cover the company if approved by the board', 'Recuse himself from all board votes related to financial disclosures', 'B', 'Board membership creates a clear conflict of interest that must be disclosed prominently in any research report. The standard requires full disclosure; it does not mandate resignation from the board.', 4),
  ('cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest-q06', 'cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest', 'Which compliance practice is most effective at preventing front-running violations?', 'Implementing pre-clearance requirements for personal securities transactions', 'Requiring members to disclose all personal trades on an annual basis', 'Limiting members to investing only in mutual funds in personal accounts', 'Conducting random audits of client account statements', 'A', 'Pre-clearance — requiring members to obtain approval before executing personal trades — directly prevents front-running by ensuring personal trades do not occur ahead of known client orders.', 5),
  ('cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest-q07', 'cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest', 'An investment bank provides research coverage only for companies that are also its investment banking clients. This practice primarily creates a conflict related to:', 'Standard VI(B) - Priority of Transactions', 'Standard III(B) - Fair Dealing', 'Standard V(A) - Diligence and Reasonable Basis', 'Standard I(B) - Independence and Objectivity', 'D', 'When research coverage is contingent on investment banking relationships, it compromises the analyst''s independence and objectivity, which is governed by Standard I(B) and reinforced by the conflict disclosure requirements of Standard VI(A).', 6),
  ('cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest-q08', 'cfa-ethics-conflicts-of-interest', 'A member receives an expensive gift from a broker-dealer whose services she evaluates for client account trading. Under the CFA Institute Standards, she should:', 'Accept the gift since it is a normal part of business relationships', 'Accept the gift only if its value is below $1,000', 'Accept the gift but donate its value to charity', 'Decline the gift and report the offer to her compliance department', 'D', 'Accepting gifts above a de minimis value from parties whose services you evaluate can impair independence and objectivity. The appropriate action is to decline and disclose to ensure compliance with conflict of interest standards.', 7),
  ('cfa-ethics-gips-standards-q01', 'cfa-ethics-gips-standards', 'Which of the following statements about GIPS compliance is most accurate?', 'GIPS compliance is mandatory for all investment firms operating globally', 'GIPS compliance must be applied on a firm-wide basis', 'Firms can claim GIPS compliance for individual composites without firm-wide compliance', 'GIPS compliance is required only for firms managing assets over $1 billion', 'B', 'GIPS requires firm-wide compliance — a firm cannot selectively apply GIPS to only certain strategies or products. Compliance is voluntary but must be comprehensive if claimed.', 0),
  ('cfa-ethics-gips-standards-q02', 'cfa-ethics-gips-standards', 'Under GIPS, a composite must include:', 'All fee-paying portfolios managed to a similar mandate, regardless of whether they are discretionary', 'All actual, fee-paying, discretionary portfolios managed to a similar mandate', 'Only the largest portfolios managed to a given strategy', 'All portfolios, including model and simulated accounts, managed to a similar mandate', 'B', 'GIPS requires composites to include all actual, fee-paying, discretionary portfolios with a similar investment strategy. Non-discretionary and non-fee-paying accounts are excluded.', 1),
  ('cfa-ethics-gips-standards-q03', 'cfa-ethics-gips-standards', 'GIPS requires performance returns to be calculated using time-weighted returns (TWR) primarily because:', 'TWR is simpler to calculate than money-weighted returns', 'TWR reflects the timing of client cash flows, rewarding superior timing', 'TWR is required by securities regulators in all major markets', 'TWR eliminates the distorting effect of external cash flows, enabling fair comparison of manager skill', 'D', 'TWR neutralizes the impact of client-driven cash flows (deposits and withdrawals), which are not under the manager''s control, allowing meaningful comparison of investment management skill across firms.', 2),
  ('cfa-ethics-gips-standards-q04', 'cfa-ethics-gips-standards', 'A GIPS-compliant firm must present at least how many years of performance history, building toward a minimum 10-year record?', '1 year', '3 years', '5 years', '7 years', 'C', 'GIPS requires firms to present a minimum of five years of compliant performance history (or since inception if shorter), building toward a 10-year track record by adding one year annually.', 3),
  ('cfa-ethics-gips-standards-q05', 'cfa-ethics-gips-standards', 'Which of the following is most consistent with the purpose of GIPS?', 'Standardizing performance presentation so prospective clients can compare track records fairly', 'Ensuring all investment managers achieve competitive returns', 'Requiring firms to hire independent auditors for all portfolio strategies', 'Setting minimum return requirements for institutional investment managers', 'A', 'GIPS exists to create a standardized, ethical framework for presenting investment performance, enabling prospective clients to make meaningful comparisons across firms and strategies on a level playing field.', 4),
  ('cfa-ethics-gips-standards-q06', 'cfa-ethics-gips-standards', 'GIPS verification is best described as:', 'An optional firm-wide review by an independent third party that provides additional assurance', 'A mandatory audit of each composite conducted by regulators', 'A self-assessment process completed annually by the firm''s compliance team', 'A composite-level certification issued by CFA Institute', 'A', 'GIPS verification is voluntary and is conducted by an independent third party on a firm-wide basis. It provides additional assurance to prospective clients but is not required for compliance.', 5),
  ('cfa-ethics-gips-standards-q07', 'cfa-ethics-gips-standards', 'A firm includes simulated and back-tested performance results in its GIPS-compliant composite presentation without any disclosure. This most likely:', 'Is permitted as long as simulated results are not presented as primary', 'Is permitted if the firm discloses it in the notes to the financial statements', 'Is acceptable because GIPS allows any returns that are calculated consistently', 'Violates GIPS because composites must include only actual performance', 'D', 'GIPS composites must be built from actual performance of real portfolios. Including simulated or back-tested results without clear, prominent disclosure violates the integrity standards underpinning GIPS.', 6),
  ('cfa-ethics-gips-standards-q08', 'cfa-ethics-gips-standards', 'Which return measure is most appropriate for evaluating an individual investor''s personal investment experience, given their specific pattern of deposits and withdrawals?', 'Time-weighted return (TWR)', 'Arithmetic mean return', 'Geometric mean return', 'Money-weighted return (MWR)', 'D', 'Money-weighted return (equivalent to IRR) reflects the timing and size of cash flows, making it the most appropriate measure for evaluating an individual investor''s personal return experience.', 7),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-probability-q01', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-probability', 'An analyst assigns a 30% probability to a recession and a 70% probability to expansion. The expected return on equity is -10% in a recession and +15% in expansion. What is the expected return?', '5.0%', '10.5%', '9.5%', '7.5%', 'D', 'E(R) = 0.30(-10%) + 0.70(15%) = -3% + 10.5% = 7.5%. This is the probability-weighted average of possible outcomes.', 0),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-probability-q02', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-probability', 'Two events A and B are mutually exclusive. P(A) = 0.40 and P(B) = 0.25. What is P(A or B)?', '0.10', '0.50', '0.75', '0.65', 'D', 'For mutually exclusive events, P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) = 0.40 + 0.25 = 0.65. The joint probability P(A and B) = 0 because the events cannot both occur.', 1),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-probability-q03', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-probability', 'Events X and Y are independent. P(X) = 0.60 and P(Y) = 0.50. What is P(X and Y)?', '0.10', '0.30', '0.55', '0.80', 'B', 'For independent events, P(X and Y) = P(X) x P(Y) = 0.60 x 0.50 = 0.30. Independence means knowledge of one event does not change the probability of the other.', 2),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-probability-q04', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-probability', 'Which type of probability is based on past frequency data from observed outcomes?', 'A priori probability', 'Subjective probability', 'Empirical probability', 'Conditional probability', 'C', 'Empirical probability is estimated by calculating the historical frequency with which an event has occurred, such as the proportion of years that a market index produced a positive return.', 3),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-probability-q05', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-probability', 'P(A) = 0.50, P(B) = 0.40, and P(A and B) = 0.20. What is P(A | B)?', '0.20', '0.40', '0.80', '0.50', 'D', 'Conditional probability: P(A | B) = P(A and B) / P(B) = 0.20 / 0.40 = 0.50. This represents the probability of A given that B has already occurred.', 4),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-probability-q06', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-probability', 'Bayes'' theorem is most useful in investment analysis for:', 'Calculating the variance of a portfolio of securities', 'Determining the expected return of an equally weighted portfolio', 'Updating prior probability estimates when new information becomes available', 'Estimating the correlation between two asset returns', 'C', 'Bayes'' theorem provides a formal mechanism for revising prior probabilities in light of new information, which is directly applicable to economic scenario analysis and forecasting in investment management.', 5),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-probability-q07', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-probability', 'A portfolio has three equally likely scenarios with returns of -5%, 10%, and 25%. What is the expected return?', '10.0%', '8.0%', '11.0%', '12.5%', 'A', 'E(R) = (1/3)(-5%) + (1/3)(10%) + (1/3)(25%) = (-5 + 10 + 25)/3 = 30/3 = 10%. With equal probabilities, the expected value equals the simple arithmetic average.', 6),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-probability-q08', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-probability', 'The total probability rule states that P(A) can be computed as:', 'The sum of all unconditional probabilities in the sample space', 'The sum of P(A | Bi) x P(Bi) for all mutually exclusive and exhaustive events Bi', 'P(A | B) + P(A | not B)', 'P(A and B) divided by P(B)', 'B', 'The total probability rule allows an unconditional probability to be calculated by weighting conditional probabilities by the probabilities of the mutually exclusive, exhaustive conditioning events.', 7),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference-q01', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference', 'The Central Limit Theorem is important in statistical inference primarily because it states that:', 'Sample means will always be normally distributed for any sample size', 'For sufficiently large samples, the sampling distribution of the mean is approximately normal regardless of the population distribution', 'The population must be normally distributed for valid statistical inference', 'Larger samples always produce more accurate point estimates of the population mean', 'B', 'The Central Limit Theorem establishes that for n >= 30, the sampling distribution of the sample mean approximates normality even if the underlying population is non-normal, enabling the use of z and t statistics.', 0),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference-q02', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference', 'A mutual fund database excludes funds that ceased operations. An analyst using this database to study historical fund returns would most likely encounter:', 'Look-ahead bias', 'Survivorship bias', 'Time-period bias', 'Data-snooping bias', 'B', 'Survivorship bias occurs when a dataset excludes entities that failed or were discontinued, causing the remaining sample to overstate historical performance since only successful funds survive to be included.', 1),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference-q03', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference', 'As sample size increases, the standard error of the sample mean:', 'Decreases, causing confidence intervals to become narrower', 'Remains constant regardless of sample size', 'Increases proportionally', 'Increases initially then decreases after the sample exceeds 30 observations', 'A', 'Standard error = sigma / sqrt(n). As n increases, the denominator grows and standard error falls, resulting in narrower confidence intervals and more precise estimates of the population mean.', 2),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference-q04', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference', 'A fixed-income manager replicating an index selects bonds to represent each maturity and credit-rating category proportionally. This sampling method is best described as:', 'Stratified random sampling', 'Systematic sampling', 'Cluster sampling', 'Simple random sampling', 'A', 'Stratified random sampling divides the population into subgroups (strata) based on relevant characteristics and draws random samples from each stratum, which is the standard approach in fixed-income index replication.', 3),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference-q05', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference', 'An analyst discovers a trading rule by running thousands of tests on the same historical dataset. The apparent profitability of the rule is most likely attributable to:', 'Look-ahead bias', 'Data-snooping bias', 'Survivorship bias', 'Sample selection bias', 'B', 'Data-snooping bias (or data mining) arises when a researcher repeatedly tests many hypotheses on the same dataset until significant results appear by chance. Such results typically fail to hold out-of-sample.', 4),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference-q06', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference', 'A 95% confidence interval for the population mean is best interpreted as:', 'There is a 95% probability that the population mean lies within this specific interval', '95% of all possible sample means fall within this interval', 'In repeated sampling, 95% of such intervals would contain the true population mean', 'The sample mean has a 95% chance of being the true population mean', 'C', 'The correct frequentist interpretation is that if we constructed many such confidence intervals from repeated samples, 95% of them would contain the true population mean. A single interval either contains the mean or it does not.', 5),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference-q07', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference', 'Look-ahead bias in a backtested trading strategy arises when:', 'The strategy is tested over too short a time period', 'Information that was not available at the time of the decision is used in the test', 'The test includes data from a period with unusually high market volatility', 'The sample excludes securities that have been delisted', 'B', 'Look-ahead bias occurs when a backtest uses data (such as revised earnings figures or restated financial reports) that would not have been available to an investor at the time the decision was supposedly made.', 6),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference-q08', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-statistical-inference', 'When the population standard deviation is unknown, the appropriate distribution for constructing a confidence interval for the population mean is the:', 'Standard normal (z) distribution', 't-distribution', 'F-distribution', 'Chi-square distribution', 'B', 'The t-distribution is used when the population standard deviation is unknown and must be estimated from the sample. It has heavier tails than the normal distribution, resulting in wider confidence intervals that reflect the additional uncertainty.', 7),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing-q01', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing', 'A Type I error in hypothesis testing is defined as:', 'Failing to reject a false null hypothesis', 'Rejecting a true null hypothesis', 'Accepting a false alternative hypothesis', 'Using the wrong test statistic for the sample size', 'B', 'A Type I error occurs when a true null hypothesis is incorrectly rejected. Its probability equals alpha, the significance level chosen by the analyst.', 0),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing-q02', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing', 'An analyst wants to test whether a portfolio manager''s mean annual return exceeds the benchmark''s mean return. The appropriate alternative hypothesis is:', 'Ha: mean return = benchmark return', 'Ha: mean return not equal to benchmark return', 'Ha: mean return > benchmark return', 'Ha: mean return < benchmark return', 'C', 'When the research question asks whether a value exceeds a benchmark, a one-tailed (right-tailed) test is appropriate, with the alternative hypothesis stating that the mean return is greater than the benchmark.', 1),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing-q03', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing', 'The p-value in a hypothesis test represents the:', 'Smallest significance level at which the null hypothesis can be rejected given the data', 'Probability of the test statistic being exactly equal to the observed value', 'Probability that the null hypothesis is true', 'Probability of making a Type II error', 'A', 'The p-value is the probability of observing a test statistic at least as extreme as the one calculated, assuming the null hypothesis is true. Rejecting H0 when p-value < alpha is equivalent to the critical value approach.', 2),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing-q04', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing', 'Decreasing the significance level (alpha) from 5% to 1% in a hypothesis test will, holding all else constant:', 'Decrease both Type I and Type II error probabilities', 'Have no effect on either type of error', 'Increase Type I error but decrease Type II error probability', 'Decrease Type I error but increase Type II error probability', 'D', 'Reducing alpha makes rejection of H0 harder, which directly reduces the probability of Type I error. However, this makes it more difficult to detect a false H0, thereby increasing the probability of Type II error.', 3),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing-q05', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing', 'An analyst tests the hypothesis that the variance of a stock''s returns equals a specified value. The appropriate test statistic to use is:', 'z-statistic', 't-statistic', 'Chi-square statistic', 'F-statistic', 'C', 'The chi-square distribution is the appropriate distribution for testing hypotheses about a single population variance. The F-distribution is used to compare variances across two populations.', 4),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing-q06', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing', 'The power of a hypothesis test is defined as:', '1 minus the probability of a Type I error', 'The probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis', 'The probability of failing to reject a true null hypothesis', 'The significance level multiplied by the sample size', 'B', 'Test power = 1 - beta, where beta is the probability of a Type II error. Power represents the ability of the test to detect a false null hypothesis when one exists.', 5),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing-q07', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing', 'Which test statistic is most appropriate when testing the equality of means from two independent normally distributed populations with unknown but assumed equal variances?', 'z-statistic using pooled standard deviation', 'Chi-square statistic', 't-statistic using pooled variance', 'F-statistic', 'C', 'When comparing means from two independent samples with unknown but assumed equal variances, a two-sample t-test using pooled variance is the appropriate procedure.', 6),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing-q08', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-hypothesis-testing', 'A researcher fails to reject the null hypothesis. The most appropriate conclusion is:', 'The null hypothesis has been proven true', 'The alternative hypothesis has been disproven', 'There is insufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis at the chosen significance level', 'A Type II error has definitely occurred', 'C', 'Failing to reject H0 does not prove it is true — it only means the sample evidence was insufficient to reject it at the chosen significance level. A Type II error may or may not have occurred.', 7),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-regression-q01', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-regression', 'In a simple linear regression, the slope coefficient b1 is best interpreted as:', 'The value of Y when X equals zero', 'The correlation between X and Y', 'The proportion of variance in Y explained by X', 'The expected change in Y for a one-unit increase in X', 'D', 'The slope coefficient b1 represents the expected change in the dependent variable Y for each one-unit increase in the independent variable X, holding all other factors constant.', 0),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-regression-q02', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-regression', 'A regression of stock returns on a market index produces an R-squared of 0.64. This means that:', 'The correlation between the stock and the market is 0.64', '64% of the variance in stock returns is explained by the market index', 'The regression coefficient on the market index equals 0.64', 'There is a 64% probability that the regression relationship is statistically significant', 'B', 'R-squared measures the proportion of the total variation in the dependent variable explained by the independent variable(s) in the regression. An R-squared of 0.64 means 64% of the variance in returns is captured by the model.', 1),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-regression-q03', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-regression', 'When adding additional independent variables to a multiple regression model, which measure should be used to compare models with different numbers of predictors?', 'R-squared', 'Standard error of the estimate', 'Adjusted R-squared', 'Sum of squared residuals', 'C', 'Adjusted R-squared penalizes the model for adding variables that do not meaningfully improve explanatory power, unlike R-squared which always increases (or stays the same) as variables are added regardless of their value.', 2),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-regression-q04', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-regression', 'Heteroskedasticity in a regression model means that the:', 'Residuals are correlated with each other across observations', 'Independent variables are highly correlated with each other', 'Dependent variable is not normally distributed', 'Variance of the residuals is not constant across all levels of the independent variable', 'D', 'Heteroskedasticity refers to non-constant variance of regression residuals. It causes OLS coefficient estimates to remain unbiased but makes standard errors unreliable, leading to incorrect t-statistics and p-values.', 3),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-regression-q05', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-regression', 'A Durbin-Watson statistic significantly below 2 in a regression using time-series data indicates the likely presence of:', 'Positive serial correlation', 'Heteroskedasticity', 'Multicollinearity', 'Negative serial correlation', 'A', 'The Durbin-Watson statistic tests for serial correlation in regression residuals. A value near 0 indicates strong positive serial correlation, near 2 indicates no serial correlation, and near 4 indicates negative serial correlation.', 4),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-regression-q06', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-regression', 'Multicollinearity in a multiple regression model is most likely to cause:', 'Biased coefficient estimates and unreliable predictions', 'The F-statistic to be statistically insignificant', 'Non-constant variance of residuals across observations', 'Inflated standard errors of coefficients, making it difficult to isolate individual effects', 'D', 'Multicollinearity does not bias coefficient estimates but inflates their standard errors. This makes t-statistics smaller and individual coefficients appear less significant even when the overall model (F-test) is significant.', 5),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-regression-q07', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-regression', 'The F-statistic in a multiple regression tests the null hypothesis that:', 'All slope coefficients jointly equal zero', 'All slope coefficients individually equal zero', 'The intercept of the regression equals zero', 'The residuals are normally distributed', 'A', 'The F-statistic tests whether all slope coefficients in the regression are jointly equal to zero — that is, whether the model as a whole explains a statistically significant portion of the variation in the dependent variable.', 6),
  ('cfa-quantitative-methods-regression-q08', 'cfa-quantitative-methods-regression', 'The ordinary least squares (OLS) method estimates regression coefficients by:', 'Maximizing the R-squared of the fitted model', 'Minimizing the sum of the absolute values of residuals', 'Minimizing the sum of squared differences between observed and fitted values', 'Maximizing the correlation between the dependent and independent variables', 'C', 'OLS selects coefficient estimates that minimize the sum of squared residuals (the squared differences between actual and predicted values of the dependent variable), which produces the best linear unbiased estimators under the classical assumptions.', 7),
  ('cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles-q01', 'cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles', 'Which component is NOT included in the expenditure approach to calculating GDP?', 'Private consumption expenditure', 'Net exports of goods and services', 'Gross private domestic investment', 'Intermediate goods purchased by manufacturers', 'D', 'GDP counts only final goods and services; intermediate goods are excluded to avoid double counting.', 0),
  ('cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles-q02', 'cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles', 'An economy experiencing two consecutive quarters of declining real GDP is most likely in which phase?', 'Peak', 'Contraction (recession)', 'Expansion', 'Trough', 'B', 'A recession is conventionally defined as two consecutive quarters of negative real GDP growth, placing the economy in the contraction phase.', 1),
  ('cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles-q03', 'cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles', 'Which of the following is best classified as a leading economic indicator?', 'Average duration of unemployment', 'Commercial and industrial loans outstanding', 'Slope of the yield curve', 'Index of industrial production', 'C', 'The yield curve slope is a leading indicator; an inverted curve typically precedes recessions. Unemployment duration and loan levels are lagging; industrial production is coincident.', 2),
  ('cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles-q04', 'cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles', 'Real GDP differs from nominal GDP in that real GDP:', 'is adjusted for changes in the price level', 'includes only goods, not services', 'counts government transfer payments', 'excludes depreciation of the capital stock', 'A', 'Real GDP uses base-year prices to remove the effect of inflation, making it a true volume measure of output.', 3),
  ('cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles-q05', 'cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles', 'Which indicator typically turns after the economy has already begun to recover?', 'New orders for capital goods', 'Building permits issued', 'Stock market index', 'Consumer price index', 'D', 'The CPI is a lagging indicator; inflation typically peaks and declines after the economic cycle has turned, reflecting prior demand conditions.', 4),
  ('cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles-q06', 'cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles', 'At the peak of a business cycle, an analyst would most likely observe:', 'maximum output and emerging inflationary pressure', 'low output and falling business confidence', 'high unemployment and rising inventory', 'rapidly falling interest rates and rising consumer confidence', 'A', 'At the peak, output is at its maximum and resource utilisation is high, which typically generates inflationary pressure before the contraction begins.', 5),
  ('cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles-q07', 'cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles', 'If government spending increases by $200 billion and private consumption falls by $200 billion, GDP measured by the expenditure approach will:', 'increase because government spending has a larger multiplier', 'remain unchanged, as the two changes offset each other', 'decrease because the private sector is more efficient', 'increase by exactly $400 billion', 'B', 'In the expenditure approach, C and G are additive components of GDP; an equal rise in G and fall in C leaves the total unchanged.', 6),
  ('cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles-q08', 'cfa-economics-gdp-business-cycles', 'Employment and personal income data are best described as which type of economic indicator?', 'Leading indicators', 'Coincident indicators', 'Lagging indicators', 'Structural indicators', 'B', 'Employment and personal income move roughly in tandem with the business cycle and are classified as coincident indicators.', 7),
  ('cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy-q01', 'cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy', 'A central bank that lowers its policy interest rate and purchases government securities is implementing:', 'expansionary monetary policy', 'contractionary fiscal policy', 'contractionary monetary policy', 'expansionary fiscal policy', 'A', 'Lowering rates and purchasing securities (QE) expands the money supply and stimulates borrowing, which is expansionary monetary policy conducted by the central bank.', 0),
  ('cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy-q02', 'cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy', 'In the quantity theory of money (MV = PY), if velocity and real output are constant, a 5% increase in the money supply will most likely result in:', 'a 5% increase in real output', 'a 5% increase in the price level', 'a 5% decrease in velocity', 'no change in the price level', 'B', 'With V and Y constant, MV = PY implies that a 5% rise in M translates directly into a 5% rise in P, the price level.', 1),
  ('cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy-q03', 'cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy', 'Automatic stabilisers differ from discretionary fiscal policy in that automatic stabilisers:', 'act counter-cyclically without new government decisions', 'require legislative approval before taking effect', 'are always more powerful than spending programmes', 'only operate during recessions, not expansions', 'A', 'Automatic stabilisers such as progressive taxes and unemployment insurance respond automatically to economic conditions without requiring new legislative action.', 2),
  ('cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy-q04', 'cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy', 'Crowding out refers to the tendency of expansionary fiscal policy to:', 'reduce net exports by raising domestic prices', 'lower private investment by pushing up real interest rates', 'increase the money supply beyond the central bank''s target', 'raise household savings through Ricardian equivalence', 'B', 'When the government borrows heavily to finance spending, competition for funds raises real interest rates, which reduces (crowds out) private sector investment.', 3),
  ('cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy-q05', 'cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy', 'A combination of tight monetary policy and expansionary fiscal policy would most likely lead to:', 'lower real interest rates and a weaker currency', 'lower inflation and a depreciating currency', 'higher real interest rates and an appreciating currency', 'higher inflation and a weaker currency', 'C', 'Tight monetary policy raises interest rates while expansionary fiscal policy increases government borrowing, both putting upward pressure on rates and attracting capital inflows that appreciate the currency.', 4),
  ('cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy-q06', 'cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy', 'Central bank independence is primarily associated with:', 'higher government budget deficits', 'more volatile exchange rates over time', 'faster economic growth in every cycle', 'lower and more stable long-run inflation', 'D', 'Research consistently finds that independent central banks free from political pressure maintain better inflation credibility, resulting in lower and more stable long-run inflation.', 5),
  ('cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy-q07', 'cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy', 'A government raises taxes and cuts spending during an economic expansion. This policy is best described as:', 'expansionary fiscal policy', 'contractionary fiscal policy', 'neutral fiscal policy', 'expansionary monetary policy', 'B', 'Raising taxes and cutting government spending reduces aggregate demand, making the stance contractionary fiscal policy.', 6),
  ('cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy-q08', 'cfa-economics-monetary-fiscal-policy', 'The fiscal multiplier is largest when the marginal propensity to consume (MPC) is:', 'equal to zero', 'equal to one', 'closest to one', 'closest to zero', 'C', 'The fiscal multiplier = 1 / (1 - MPC); as MPC approaches one, the multiplier grows very large because each round of spending generates nearly equal additional consumption.', 7),
  ('cfa-economics-international-trade-forex-q01', 'cfa-economics-international-trade-forex', 'Comparative advantage suggests that countries should specialise in goods for which they have:', 'the lowest absolute cost of production', 'the lowest opportunity cost of production', 'the highest absolute productivity levels', 'the most advanced technological capacity', 'B', 'Comparative advantage is determined by opportunity cost, not absolute cost; a country benefits by specialising where its opportunity cost is lowest relative to trading partners.', 0),
  ('cfa-economics-international-trade-forex-q02', 'cfa-economics-international-trade-forex', 'A country running a current account deficit is necessarily running a:', 'surplus in its capital and financial accounts combined', 'budget surplus in government finances', 'trade surplus in goods but a deficit in services', 'surplus in foreign exchange reserves', 'A', 'The balance of payments must sum to zero; a current account deficit is financed by a corresponding surplus in the capital and financial accounts (net capital inflows).', 1),
  ('cfa-economics-international-trade-forex-q03', 'cfa-economics-international-trade-forex', 'Purchasing Power Parity (PPP) predicts that over the long run, a country with higher inflation relative to a trading partner will see its currency:', 'appreciate to restore competitiveness', 'remain stable due to central bank intervention', 'depreciate by approximately the inflation differential', 'appreciate because higher prices attract foreign investment', 'C', 'PPP holds that exchange rates adjust to offset inflation differentials; the higher-inflation country''s currency depreciates so that identical goods cost the same across borders.', 2),
  ('cfa-economics-international-trade-forex-q04', 'cfa-economics-international-trade-forex', 'Covered interest rate parity implies that the forward exchange rate premium or discount equals:', 'the difference in inflation rates between the two countries', 'the trade balance difference between the two economies', 'the interest rate differential between the two countries', 'the current account surplus of the higher-rate country', 'C', 'Covered interest rate parity states that the forward premium or discount on a currency equals the interest rate differential, preventing risk-free arbitrage between money markets.', 3),
  ('cfa-economics-international-trade-forex-q05', 'cfa-economics-international-trade-forex', 'Which of the following is recorded in the financial account of the balance of payments?', 'A country''s exports of manufactured goods', 'Dividend income received from foreign investments', 'Unilateral transfer payments to foreign governments', 'Foreign direct investment inflows to domestic firms', 'D', 'FDI inflows represent cross-border investment transactions recorded in the financial account, not the current account.', 4),
  ('cfa-economics-international-trade-forex-q06', 'cfa-economics-international-trade-forex', 'If a domestic country''s interest rates rise relative to a foreign country, the most likely immediate effect on the domestic currency is:', 'depreciation, as borrowing costs increase', 'appreciation, as capital flows in seeking higher yields', 'no change, as rates do not affect exchange rates', 'depreciation, as inflation expectations increase', 'B', 'Higher domestic interest rates attract foreign capital seeking better returns, increasing demand for the domestic currency and causing it to appreciate.', 5),
  ('cfa-economics-international-trade-forex-q07', 'cfa-economics-international-trade-forex', 'The spot exchange rate differs from the forward exchange rate in that the spot rate:', 'is for immediate or near-immediate currency delivery', 'applies only to currency swap transactions', 'is set by government regulation rather than market forces', 'guarantees a fixed rate for future transactions', 'A', 'The spot rate is the current market rate for immediate (or settlement within two business days) delivery, whereas the forward rate is agreed upon now for future delivery.', 6),
  ('cfa-economics-international-trade-forex-q08', 'cfa-economics-international-trade-forex', 'An import tariff imposed by a large country is most likely to:', 'lower the domestic price of the imported good', 'benefit domestic consumers at the expense of producers', 'increase total economic welfare in the importing country', 'raise the domestic price and protect domestic producers', 'D', 'A tariff raises the domestic price of imports above the world price, protecting domestic producers but reducing consumer surplus; net welfare in the importing country typically falls.', 7),
  ('cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation-q01', 'cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation', 'A government expropriates a foreign mining company''s assets without adequate compensation. This event is an example of:', 'trade liberalisation risk', 'currency convertibility risk', 'resource nationalism risk', 'portfolio rebalancing risk', 'C', 'Expropriation of natural resource assets by a government is a classic form of resource nationalism, a key geopolitical risk for international investors.', 0),
  ('cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation-q02', 'cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation', 'During a geopolitical risk-off episode, capital typically flows toward which of the following assets?', 'Emerging market equities and high-yield bonds', 'Commodities linked to industrial production', 'Small-cap domestic growth stocks', 'USD, US Treasuries, and gold', 'D', 'In risk-off episodes driven by geopolitical stress, investors seek safe-haven assets such as the USD, US Treasuries, and gold due to their perceived stability and liquidity.', 1),
  ('cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation-q03', 'cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation', 'The primary driver of post-World War II globalisation was:', 'trade liberalisation under multilateral agreements and declining transport costs', 'elimination of all foreign direct investment', 'fixed exchange rate systems maintained by all major economies', 'government mandates requiring domestic firms to export', 'A', 'Globalisation was primarily driven by multilateral trade liberalisation (GATT/WTO) and technological advances that sharply reduced transportation and communication costs.', 2),
  ('cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation-q04', 'cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation', 'When analysts add a country risk premium to the discount rate for an investment in a politically unstable market, this adjustment accounts for:', 'the expected appreciation of the local currency', 'lower corporate tax rates in emerging markets', 'additional systematic and unsystematic risks unique to that market', 'the diversification benefit from international exposure', 'C', 'A country risk premium captures the additional risks — including political instability, expropriation, and legal uncertainty — that investors face in markets beyond standard market risk.', 3),
  ('cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation-q05', 'cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation', 'Reshoring and friend-shoring of supply chains reflect a shift in corporate priorities from:', 'sustainability to profitability', 'labour-intensive to capital-intensive production', 'domestic markets to global expansion', 'pure cost efficiency to resilience and security', 'D', 'Reshoring and friend-shoring represent a strategic shift away from pure cost minimisation toward supply chain resilience, driven by geopolitical tensions and pandemic-related disruptions.', 4),
  ('cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation-q06', 'cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation', 'Economic sanctions imposed on a country most directly affect an investor through:', 'improved access to the sanctioned country''s capital markets', 'increased diversification benefits from that market', 'restricted capital flows, asset freezes, and trade disruption', 'lower inflation expectations in the sanctioning countries', 'C', 'Sanctions restrict cross-border capital flows, can freeze assets, and disrupt trade, directly impairing the value and accessibility of investments in or tied to the sanctioned country.', 5),
  ('cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation-q07', 'cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation', 'Which of the following best describes the role of the WTO in the context of globalisation?', 'Setting global monetary policy and exchange rate targets', 'Regulating cross-border equity and bond issuances', 'Providing a forum for trade liberalisation and dispute resolution', 'Enforcing domestic labour and environmental standards', 'C', 'The WTO provides a multilateral framework for negotiating trade liberalisation agreements and a mechanism for resolving trade disputes between member countries.', 6),
  ('cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation-q08', 'cfa-economics-geopolitics-globalisation', 'A military conflict that disrupts a major oil-producing region would most likely cause:', 'a fall in global commodity prices and higher corporate margins', 'a supply shock raising energy prices and compressing industrial margins', 'a risk-on rally in equity markets due to defence spending', 'appreciation of currencies in energy-importing nations', 'B', 'A military conflict disrupting oil supply creates a negative supply shock, pushing energy prices higher and raising input costs that compress margins for energy-intensive industries.', 7),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement-q01', 'cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement', 'Under IFRS 15 and ASC 606, revenue is recognised when:', 'cash is received from the customer', 'the invoice is sent to the customer', 'control of goods or services is transferred to the customer', 'the contract is signed by both parties', 'C', 'The five-step revenue recognition model requires recognising revenue when (or as) the entity satisfies a performance obligation by transferring control to the customer.', 0),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement-q02', 'cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement', 'EBITDA is commonly used as a proxy for operating cash flow but has a significant limitation because it ignores:', 'depreciation and amortisation charges', 'interest expense and tax payments', 'capital expenditures and working capital changes', 'non-recurring restructuring charges', 'C', 'EBITDA adds back non-cash charges but does not account for capex needed to maintain operations or changes in working capital, making it an imperfect cash flow proxy.', 1),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement-q03', 'cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement', 'On the income statement, gross profit is calculated as:', 'revenue minus all operating expenses including SG&A', 'revenue minus cost of goods sold', 'revenue minus interest expense and taxes', 'operating income plus depreciation and amortisation', 'B', 'Gross profit equals revenue minus the cost of goods sold (COGS), reflecting the profitability of core production before operating expenses.', 2),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement-q04', 'cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement', 'An analyst identifying non-recurring items such as restructuring charges in an income statement should most likely:', 'include them in normalised earnings to be conservative', 'exclude them when calculating normalised or core earnings', 'capitalise them on the balance sheet for future amortisation', 'double-count them to account for future recurrence', 'B', 'Non-recurring items distort the underlying earnings power of the business; analysts exclude them to derive a normalised earnings figure that better reflects sustainable performance.', 3),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement-q05', 'cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement', 'Under the percentage-of-completion method for long-term contracts, revenue is recognised:', 'only upon final delivery and customer acceptance', 'equally across all periods regardless of progress', 'when all costs have been incurred and recovered', 'in proportion to the stage of completion each period', 'D', 'The percentage-of-completion method allocates revenue and costs to each period based on the proportion of the contract completed, matching revenue with the work performed.', 4),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement-q06', 'cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement', 'A company that accelerates revenue recognition relative to the economic delivery of its product would most likely show:', 'inflated near-term earnings and higher accounts receivable', 'lower near-term revenues and higher accounts payable', 'lower gross margins and reduced cash flow from operations', 'higher deferred revenue and lower reported net income', 'A', 'Aggressive early revenue recognition inflates reported earnings in the near term and increases receivables, as cash has not yet been collected from customers.', 5),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement-q07', 'cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement', 'Operating income (EBIT) is best defined as:', 'earnings before interest and taxes from core operations', 'gross profit minus depreciation only', 'net income before preferred dividends', 'net income plus interest expense', 'A', 'EBIT (earnings before interest and taxes) represents operating income from core business activities before the effects of capital structure and tax obligations.', 6),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement-q08', 'cfa-financial-reporting-income-statement', 'A software company sells a bundled product containing a licence and one year of support. Under the five-step model, the company should:', 'recognise all revenue on the contract signing date', 'identify two performance obligations and allocate the price to each', 'defer all revenue until the support period is complete', 'recognise revenue only when the entire contract is terminated', 'B', 'The five-step model requires identifying distinct performance obligations; the licence and the support are separate obligations, and the transaction price must be allocated to each.', 7),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity-q01', 'cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity', 'The fundamental accounting equation underlying the balance sheet is:', 'Assets = Revenue - Expenses', 'Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders Equity', 'Net income = Assets - Liabilities', 'Cash flow = Net income + Depreciation', 'B', 'The balance sheet identity is Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders Equity, reflecting that all assets are financed either by debt (liabilities) or by owners'' contributions and retained profits.', 0),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity-q02', 'cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity', 'Accumulated Other Comprehensive Income (AOCI) arises from items that:', 'are included in net income and retained earnings', 'arise only from dividend payments to shareholders', 'are recorded as long-term liabilities on the balance sheet', 'bypass the income statement and affect equity directly', 'D', 'AOCI captures unrealised gains/losses on AFS securities, foreign currency translation adjustments, and pension remeasurements that go directly to equity without passing through the income statement.', 1),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity-q03', 'cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity', 'Treasury stock on the balance sheet represents shares that have been:', 'issued and outstanding in the hands of the public', 'authorised but never issued to investors', 'converted from preferred into common stock', 'repurchased by the company and not yet retired', 'D', 'Treasury stock consists of shares the company has repurchased from shareholders but not cancelled; it reduces total shareholders equity and is not considered outstanding.', 2),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity-q04', 'cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity', 'Under IFRS, balance sheet assets are generally presented in which order?', 'Decreasing order of liquidity (most liquid last)', 'Only alphabetical order is acceptable', 'Increasing order of liquidity (least liquid first) or decreasing, both permitted', 'Strictly increasing order of value', 'C', 'IFRS allows companies to present assets in either increasing or decreasing order of liquidity; US GAAP requires decreasing liquidity (most liquid first).', 3),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity-q05', 'cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity', 'A company''s price-to-book ratio is below 1.0. This most likely indicates that the market:', 'believes the firm''s assets are worth less than their book value', 'values the firm more than its recorded net assets', 'expects very high future earnings growth from the firm', 'is unaware of the company''s true asset values', 'A', 'A price-to-book ratio below 1 means the market price is below book value per share, suggesting the market believes the assets are impaired, the business is unprofitable, or book value is overstated.', 4),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity-q06', 'cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity', 'Which of the following is classified as a non-current (long-term) liability on the balance sheet?', 'Defined benefit pension obligation', 'Accrued wages payable in the current period', 'Accounts payable due in 30 days', 'Current portion of long-term debt', 'A', 'A defined benefit pension obligation is a long-term commitment to fund future employee benefits, classified as a non-current liability; the other options are current liabilities.', 5),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity-q07', 'cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity', 'Retained earnings on the balance sheet represent:', 'the cumulative net income earned less dividends paid over time', 'cash held by the company in its bank account', 'shares issued above their par value to investors', 'unrealised gains recorded in other comprehensive income', 'A', 'Retained earnings accumulate all net income earned since inception, reduced by dividends paid; they are not a cash account but a measure of reinvested profits.', 6),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity-q08', 'cfa-financial-reporting-balance-sheet-equity', 'Goodwill appearing on a company''s balance sheet arises when:', 'the company generates brand value through advertising', 'the company internally develops patents and trademarks', 'the company acquires another firm for more than the fair value of net identifiable assets', 'the fair value of assets exceeds their carrying amount', 'C', 'Goodwill is the excess of the acquisition price paid over the fair value of the target''s identifiable net assets; it is only recognised through a business combination, not internal development.', 7),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement-q01', 'cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement', 'Under the indirect method of preparing the cash flow from operations, depreciation is added back to net income because:', 'it is a non-cash charge that reduced net income but did not use cash', 'it represents a cash inflow from asset disposals', 'it increases the tax shield and reduces tax payments', 'it offsets capital expenditures in the investing section', 'A', 'Depreciation reduces net income without requiring a cash outflow; the indirect method adds it back to reconcile net income to actual cash generated from operations.', 0),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement-q02', 'cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement', 'Capital expenditures (capex) appear on the cash flow statement under:', 'cash flows from operating activities', 'cash flows from financing activities', 'cash flows from investing activities', 'supplemental disclosure of non-cash activities', 'C', 'Capital expenditures represent purchases of long-term assets and are classified as cash outflows in the investing activities section of the cash flow statement.', 1),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement-q03', 'cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement', 'Free cash flow to equity (FCFE) is most accurately calculated as:', 'EBITDA minus taxes and capex', 'net income plus depreciation minus capex', 'FCFF minus interest expense', 'CFO minus capex plus net borrowing', 'D', 'FCFE = CFO - Capex + Net borrowing; this represents cash available to equity holders after reinvestment needs and after accounting for debt transactions.', 2),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement-q04', 'cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement', 'A company reports high net income but very low cash flow from operations. This pattern is most likely a sign of:', 'efficient working capital management and high asset turnover', 'aggressive revenue recognition or deteriorating working capital', 'conservative accounting that understates true earnings', 'high depreciation charges reducing taxable income', 'B', 'A large gap between net income and CFO often indicates aggressive revenue recognition (inflating income) or rising receivables and inventory consuming cash — both red flags for analysts.', 3),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement-q05', 'cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement', 'Dividend payments to shareholders are classified under which section of the cash flow statement under US GAAP?', 'Operating activities', 'Investing activities', 'Supplemental non-cash disclosures', 'Financing activities', 'D', 'Under US GAAP, dividend payments to shareholders are classified as cash outflows from financing activities, reflecting their nature as returns of capital to equity providers.', 4),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement-q06', 'cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement', 'Free cash flow to the firm (FCFF) is discounted at the WACC rather than the cost of equity because FCFF represents:', 'cash available only to equity holders after debt service', 'net income adjusted for non-cash working capital changes', 'operating income after taxes but before depreciation', 'cash available to all capital providers before financing costs', 'D', 'FCFF is available to both debt and equity holders before any financing payments; it must be discounted at the WACC, which blends the required returns of all capital providers.', 5),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement-q07', 'cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement', 'An increase in accounts receivable during a period would appear in the indirect method cash flow from operations as:', 'an addition to net income, as more sales were made', 'a non-cash investing activity disclosed in supplemental notes', 'a financing inflow, reflecting customer credit extended', 'a subtraction from net income, as cash has not yet been collected', 'D', 'An increase in receivables means revenue was recognised but cash not yet received; this use of working capital is subtracted from net income in the indirect method.', 6),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement-q08', 'cfa-financial-reporting-cash-flow-statement', 'The direct method of presenting cash flows from operations differs from the indirect method in that the direct method:', 'shows actual cash received from customers and paid to suppliers', 'starts with net income and adjusts for non-cash items', 'is only permitted under US GAAP, not IFRS', 'excludes changes in working capital from the calculation', 'A', 'The direct method lists actual cash receipts (e.g., from customers) and cash payments (e.g., to suppliers, employees) rather than starting from net income and working backward.', 7),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes-q01', 'cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes', 'LIFO inventory accounting is permitted under US GAAP but prohibited under IFRS. In a period of rising prices, LIFO produces:', 'higher ending inventory and lower COGS than FIFO', 'lower ending inventory and higher COGS than FIFO', 'identical COGS and inventory values to FIFO', 'higher net income and higher taxes than FIFO', 'B', 'Under LIFO in a rising price environment, the most recently purchased (higher-cost) inventory is expensed first, yielding higher COGS and lower ending inventory compared with FIFO.', 0),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes-q02', 'cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes', 'To compare a LIFO firm with a FIFO peer, an analyst should add the LIFO reserve to the LIFO firm''s:', 'COGS on the income statement', 'accumulated depreciation on PP&E', 'total debt on the balance sheet', 'inventory balance on the balance sheet', 'D', 'The LIFO reserve is the cumulative difference between LIFO and FIFO inventory values; adding it to the LIFO firm''s inventory restates it to approximate FIFO and allows comparability.', 1),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes-q03', 'cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes', 'Under the straight-line depreciation method, annual depreciation expense is calculated as:', '(Cost + Salvage value) divided by useful life', 'Cost multiplied by the declining balance rate', '(Cost - Salvage value) divided by useful life', 'Units produced divided by total estimated units', 'C', 'Straight-line depreciation spreads the depreciable base (cost minus salvage value) evenly over the asset''s useful life, producing the same expense each period.', 2),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes-q04', 'cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes', 'A deferred tax liability arises when:', 'book income exceeds taxable income, creating a future tax obligation', 'taxable income exceeds book income, so taxes are paid early', 'a company records a tax loss carryforward on its balance sheet', 'warranty expenses are recognised for tax before book purposes', 'A', 'A DTL arises when book income exceeds taxable income (e.g., due to accelerated tax depreciation), meaning taxes that should have been paid now will be owed in the future.', 3),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes-q05', 'cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes', 'Under IFRS, if market value recovers after an inventory write-down, the company is permitted to:', 'write up inventory but only to its original historical cost', 'write up inventory to any market value regardless of cost', 'reverse the write-down up to the original carrying amount', 'not adjust inventory; the write-down is permanent under IFRS', 'C', 'IFRS (IAS 2) permits reversal of a prior inventory write-down if the net realisable value subsequently recovers, limited to the original write-down amount; US GAAP prohibits any reversal.', 4),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes-q06', 'cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes', 'Compared with straight-line depreciation, an accelerated depreciation method will in early years produce:', 'lower depreciation expense and higher net income', 'higher depreciation expense and lower taxable income', 'identical depreciation but different salvage values', 'lower total depreciation over the entire asset life', 'B', 'Accelerated methods (e.g., double-declining balance) front-load depreciation, producing higher expense in early years, lower taxable income, and deferred tax liabilities relative to straight-line.', 5),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes-q07', 'cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes', 'A deferred tax asset is most likely created when a company:', 'uses accelerated depreciation for tax but straight-line for books', 'capitalises an expense for book purposes that is immediately expensed for tax', 'recognises revenue earlier for book purposes than for tax purposes', 'recognises warranty expense for book purposes before it is deductible for taxes', 'D', 'Warranty expense recognised on the books before it is tax-deductible creates a temporary difference where book income is lower than taxable income, generating a deferred tax asset (future tax savings).', 6),
  ('cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes-q08', 'cfa-financial-reporting-inventory-ppe-taxes', 'Under IFRS, the revaluation model for PP&E allows a company to:', 'revalue assets to fair value, with gains going to other comprehensive income', 'revalue assets downward only, never upward', 'revalue assets to replacement cost charged directly to net income', 'choose any value above historical cost for balance sheet presentation', 'A', 'The IFRS revaluation model permits PP&E to be carried at fair value; revaluation increases (surpluses) bypass net income and are recorded in other comprehensive income (revaluation surplus).', 7),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure-q01', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure', 'According to Modigliani-Miller Proposition I without taxes, a firm''s value is determined by:', 'its debt-to-equity ratio', 'the earnings power of its real assets, independent of capital structure', 'the interest rate on its outstanding debt', 'the size of its annual dividend payment', 'B', 'MM Proposition I (no taxes) states that firm value depends only on earnings power of real assets, not on how those assets are financed.', 0),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure-q02', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure', 'When a firm adds debt in the MM framework with corporate taxes, firm value increases because:', 'the interest tax shield reduces the effective cost of debt financing', 'debt lowers the equity risk premium', 'creditors accept lower returns than equity holders in all scenarios', 'leverage reduces total operating risk', 'A', 'The interest tax shield (t * D) adds value equal to the tax rate times the debt balance, increasing levered firm value.', 1),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure-q03', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure', 'MM Proposition II (no taxes) states that as a firm increases its financial leverage, its cost of equity:', 'decreases because debt is cheaper than equity', 'remains constant because WACC is fixed', 'falls to the risk-free rate', 'rises linearly with the debt-to-equity ratio', 'D', 'Proposition II shows that higher leverage increases equity risk, so the cost of equity rises linearly with D/E, keeping WACC constant.', 2),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure-q04', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure', 'The trade-off theory of capital structure holds that optimal leverage is reached when:', 'the firm issues the maximum amount of debt possible', 'the marginal tax shield benefit of additional debt equals the marginal cost of financial distress', 'debt equals equity in market-value terms', 'EBIT equals total interest expense', 'B', 'Trade-off theory balances the tax shield benefit against distress costs; the optimum is where marginal benefit equals marginal cost.', 3),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure-q05', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure', 'A company with high tangible assets and stable cash flows will, according to the trade-off theory, most likely support:', 'lower debt ratios due to high collateral', 'higher debt ratios because distress costs are lower and collateral is greater', 'no debt because tangible assets reduce profitability', 'equity-only financing to preserve flexibility', 'B', 'Tangible assets reduce distress costs and provide collateral, supporting higher optimal leverage under the trade-off theory.', 4),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure-q06', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure', 'Under the pecking order theory, which source of financing do firms most prefer?', 'Internal funds (retained earnings)', 'Common equity issuance', 'Convertible bonds', 'Preferred equity', 'A', 'Pecking order theory ranks internal financing first because it avoids signaling costs associated with external issuance.', 5),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure-q07', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure', 'Financial distress costs that arise when customers avoid a firm''s products and employees seek other jobs are called:', 'direct bankruptcy costs', 'interest tax shield losses', 'agency costs of equity', 'indirect costs of financial distress', 'D', 'Indirect distress costs include lost sales, key employee departures, and strained supplier terms — distinct from direct legal/administrative costs.', 6),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure-q08', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-capital-structure', 'The value of a levered firm under MM with corporate taxes equals the value of the unlevered firm plus:', 'the total equity market capitalisation', 'the tax rate multiplied by the value of debt', 'the present value of interest payments', 'EBIT divided by WACC', 'B', 'MM with taxes: Vl = Vu + t*D, where t*D is the present value of the perpetual tax shield.', 7),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks-q01', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks', 'Under the Miller-Modigliani dividend irrelevance proposition, firm value is unaffected by dividend policy because shareholders can:', 'create homemade dividends by buying or selling shares', 'reinvest dividends in government bonds', 'defer taxes indefinitely on dividend income', 'force the firm to repurchase shares at any time', 'A', 'MM dividend irrelevance relies on shareholders replicating any dividend stream by buying or selling shares themselves, making payout policy irrelevant.', 0),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks-q02', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks', 'The clientele effect in dividend policy refers to the tendency for:', 'firms to pay dividends only when cash flows are negative', 'different investor groups to prefer firms with payout policies that match their tax and income needs', 'institutional investors to always demand zero dividends', 'dividend cuts to cause share price increases', 'B', 'The clientele effect holds that investor groups self-select into firms whose dividend policy aligns with their tax situation and income needs.', 1),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks-q03', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks', 'An unexpected increase in a firm''s regular cash dividend is most commonly interpreted as a signal that management:', 'is running out of investment opportunities', 'intends to issue additional equity soon', 'expects future earnings to be higher and more stable', 'is preparing to reduce debt', 'C', 'Signaling theory holds that dividend increases convey management confidence in higher sustainable future earnings.', 2),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks-q04', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks', 'Compared with a cash dividend of equal after-tax value, a share buyback provides shareholders with greater:', 'certainty of income', 'priority in liquidation', 'tax deferral flexibility, since non-tendering shareholders recognise no immediate taxable gain', 'protection against share price declines', 'C', 'Shareholders who do not tender in a buyback defer any capital gain tax, whereas all shareholders receiving a dividend face immediate taxation.', 3),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks-q05', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks', 'Which of the following dividend types does NOT directly transfer cash to shareholders?', 'Regular cash dividend', 'Liquidating dividend', 'Special dividend', 'Stock dividend', 'D', 'A stock dividend distributes additional shares rather than cash; total equity value is unchanged.', 4),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks-q06', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks', 'A share repurchase reduces which of the following on a firm''s balance sheet?', 'Total revenues', 'Long-term debt', 'Shareholders'' equity and cash', 'Gross profit margin', 'C', 'A buyback reduces both cash (outflow) and shareholders'' equity (treasury shares), leaving total assets and equity lower.', 5),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks-q07', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks', 'Agency cost theory suggests that paying dividends benefits shareholders primarily by:', 'increasing systematic risk', 'lowering the firm''s tax burden', 'ensuring management receives performance bonuses', 'reducing free cash flow available for value-destroying investments by management', 'D', 'Distributing cash through dividends or buybacks reduces the free cash flow managers could waste on negative-NPV projects, lowering agency costs.', 6),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks-q08', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-dividends-buybacks', 'Under the assumption of tax neutrality between dividends and capital gains, a cash dividend and a share repurchase of equal size produce:', 'higher wealth from buybacks because EPS always rises', 'higher wealth from dividends due to the income effect', 'identical wealth outcomes for shareholders (payout equivalence)', 'different outcomes depending on the firm''s leverage ratio', 'C', 'Under tax neutrality, dividends and buybacks are equivalent in terms of total shareholder wealth — payout method is irrelevant.', 7),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance-q01', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance', 'The principal-agent problem in corporate governance arises primarily because:', 'shareholders have unlimited liability for firm debts', 'managers may pursue self-interest rather than maximising shareholder value', 'creditors have priority over equity holders in bankruptcy', 'boards of directors are elected by creditors', 'B', 'The principal-agent problem arises from the separation of ownership (principals/shareholders) and control (agents/managers), creating potential conflicts of interest.', 0),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance-q02', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance', 'Which board characteristic is most associated with strong shareholder protection?', 'A board dominated by inside directors employed by the firm', 'A staggered board with long director terms', 'A CEO who also serves as board chairman', 'A majority of independent, non-executive directors', 'D', 'A majority-independent board provides objective oversight of management and is considered a best-practice governance structure.', 1),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance-q03', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance', 'Dual-class share structures most directly affect corporate governance by:', 'increasing the dividend yield for common shareholders', 'requiring the board to include employee representatives', 'concentrating voting power with founders, limiting external shareholder influence', 'reducing the company''s debt financing costs', 'C', 'Dual-class structures give founders or insiders superior voting rights, reducing accountability to ordinary shareholders.', 2),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance-q04', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance', 'In the context of ESG investing, a fund that excludes tobacco, weapons, and gambling companies from its portfolio is using:', 'positive (best-in-class) screening', 'ESG integration into financial models', 'thematic investing in ESG trends', 'negative screening based on ethical criteria', 'D', 'Negative screening excludes sectors or companies that fail to meet specified ethical, social, or environmental standards.', 3),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance-q05', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance', 'The primary function of a board''s audit committee is to:', 'oversee the quality and integrity of financial reporting and the external audit process', 'set the firm''s long-term strategic direction', 'approve executive compensation packages', 'manage day-to-day operations in the CEO''s absence', 'A', 'The audit committee oversees financial reporting, internal controls, and the relationship with the external auditor.', 4),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance-q06', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance', 'An example of a governance-related (G in ESG) factor that analysts would examine is:', 'a firm''s carbon emissions per unit of output', 'employee satisfaction survey scores', 'board composition, executive pay, and shareholder voting rights', 'a company''s water usage relative to industry peers', 'C', 'Governance factors include board independence, executive compensation structure, and the robustness of shareholder voting rights.', 5),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance-q07', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance', 'Which of the following mechanisms most directly reduces the agency cost of equity?', 'Tying executive compensation to long-term share performance', 'Increasing the number of product lines', 'Issuing more long-term debt', 'Reducing the firm''s dividend payout ratio', 'A', 'Performance-linked executive pay aligns management incentives with shareholder wealth creation, reducing agency costs.', 6),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance-q08', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-corporate-governance', 'Stakeholder theory differs from the traditional shareholder primacy model in that it argues firms should balance the interests of:', 'shareholders, employees, customers, suppliers, and the broader community', 'only domestic creditors and domestic shareholders', 'regulators and government agencies exclusively', 'majority shareholders above all other parties', 'A', 'Stakeholder theory holds that firms have obligations to a broad set of parties, not only shareholders.', 7),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis-q01', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis', 'A firm''s degree of operating leverage (DOL) measures the sensitivity of EBIT to changes in:', 'interest expense', 'net income', 'sales revenue', 'dividends paid', 'C', 'DOL = % change in EBIT / % change in sales, capturing how fixed operating costs amplify EBIT relative to revenue changes.', 0),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis-q02', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis', 'A company has sales of 1,000, variable costs of 600, and EBIT of 200. Its degree of operating leverage is:', '5.0', '3.0', '1.5', '2.0', 'D', 'DOL = (Sales - Variable costs) / EBIT = (1000 - 600) / 200 = 400 / 200 = 2.0.', 1),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis-q03', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis', 'The degree of financial leverage (DFL) equals EBIT divided by:', 'sales minus variable costs', 'net income after tax', 'EBIT minus interest expense', 'total fixed costs', 'C', 'DFL = EBIT / (EBIT - Interest), measuring how fixed financing costs amplify the effect of EBIT changes on EPS.', 2),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis-q04', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis', 'The degree of total leverage (DTL) is best calculated as:', 'DOL plus DFL', 'DOL minus DFL', 'DOL multiplied by DFL', 'DFL divided by DOL', 'C', 'DTL = DOL * DFL, capturing the combined amplification from operating and financial fixed costs on EPS relative to sales.', 3),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis-q05', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis', 'A firm''s operating breakeven point in units is the quantity at which:', 'EPS equals zero', 'EBIT equals zero (contribution margin covers fixed operating costs)', 'net income equals dividends', 'total revenue equals total debt', 'B', 'Operating breakeven = Fixed operating costs / (Price - Variable cost per unit); this is the output level at which EBIT = 0.', 4),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis-q06', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis', 'All else equal, a company that switches from variable to fixed costs in its production process will experience:', 'a lower degree of operating leverage', 'reduced volatility in EBIT relative to sales', 'a higher degree of operating leverage and greater EBIT sensitivity', 'a lower breakeven point', 'C', 'Higher fixed operating costs raise DOL, so EBIT becomes more sensitive to revenue changes — amplifying both gains and losses.', 5),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis-q07', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis', 'A firm has a DOL of 3 and a DFL of 2. If sales increase by 10%, EPS will change by approximately:', '30%', '60%', '20%', '10%', 'B', 'DTL = DOL * DFL = 3 * 2 = 6; EPS change = DTL * sales change = 6 * 10% = 60%.', 6),
  ('cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis-q08', 'cfa-corporate-issuers-leverage-analysis', 'A high degree of total leverage indicates that a firm''s EPS is highly sensitive to changes in sales, which implies:', 'lower required return by equity investors', 'greater risk for equity holders because EPS can swing widely with revenues', 'reduced risk for creditors due to predictable cash flows', 'an unchanged weighted average cost of capital', 'B', 'High DTL means EPS is volatile relative to sales, increasing equity risk and the required return by shareholders.', 7),
  ('cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency-q01', 'cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency', 'Under the semi-strong form of the efficient market hypothesis, which type of analysis is rendered unable to generate consistent excess returns?', 'Both technical and fundamental analysis', 'Insider trading based on private information', 'Technical analysis only', 'Passive index investing', 'A', 'Semi-strong efficiency incorporates all public information, making both technical and fundamental analysis unable to earn consistent excess returns.', 0),
  ('cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency-q02', 'cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency', 'The weak form of the EMH implies that past stock prices and trading volume data:', 'are already fully reflected in current prices, making technical analysis ineffective', 'can be used to predict future prices reliably', 'are more reliable than fundamental analysis', 'reveal insider information about future earnings', 'A', 'Weak-form efficiency means historical price data are already incorporated into prices, so technical analysis cannot generate alpha.', 1),
  ('cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency-q03', 'cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency', 'The size effect anomaly in equity markets refers to the observation that:', 'large-cap stocks always outperform small-cap stocks', 'the S&P 500 outperforms all small-cap indices over time', 'firm size has no relationship with stock returns', 'smaller companies'' stocks have historically earned higher risk-adjusted returns than larger companies', 'D', 'The size effect documents historically higher risk-adjusted returns for small-cap stocks, representing an apparent anomaly to EMH.', 2),
  ('cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency-q04', 'cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency', 'In an order-driven secondary market, transactions are executed based on:', 'dealer bid-ask spreads quoted continuously', 'a government-set price ceiling', 'buy and sell orders matched by price and time priority in a limit order book', 'negotiated prices between two institutions only', 'C', 'Order-driven markets use a limit order book where orders are matched by price-time priority, without requiring a dealer to quote prices.', 3),
  ('cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency-q05', 'cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency', 'If markets are strong-form efficient, which group would be unable to consistently earn excess returns?', 'Passive index investors only', 'Technical analysts only', 'Even corporate insiders with private information', 'Fundamental analysts only', 'C', 'Strong-form efficiency incorporates all information including private/insider information, so even insiders cannot consistently earn excess returns.', 4),
  ('cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency-q06', 'cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency', 'Primary markets differ from secondary markets in that primary markets involve:', 'only institutional investors', 'only government bonds', 'anonymous electronic trading of existing securities', 'the issuance of new securities to raise capital for the issuer', 'D', 'Primary markets are where new securities are first issued (IPOs, seasoned offerings), providing capital directly to the issuer.', 5),
  ('cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency-q07', 'cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency', 'The momentum anomaly suggests that stocks that have performed well recently will tend to:', 'immediately reverse toward their long-run average return', 'continue to outperform in the short run', 'underperform regardless of market conditions', 'show no pattern in subsequent returns', 'B', 'Momentum anomaly documents that recent winners continue to outperform and recent losers continue to underperform in the near term.', 6),
  ('cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency-q08', 'cfa-equity-market-organisation-efficiency', 'The rational conclusion for a long-term investor who believes markets are semi-strong efficient is to:', 'rely heavily on technical chart patterns', 'invest in low-cost passive index funds to capture market returns net of fees', 'conduct intensive fundamental research to select mispriced stocks', 'concentrate the portfolio in a few high-conviction stocks', 'B', 'Under semi-strong efficiency, active management cannot consistently add value after costs, so passive index investing is the rational strategy.', 7),
  ('cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis-q01', 'cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis', 'In Porter''s Five Forces framework, an industry with high entry barriers, few substitutes, and fragmented buyers is most likely to exhibit:', 'intense price competition and low margins', 'declining revenues over the long term', 'rapid technological obsolescence', 'sustained above-average profitability', 'D', 'High barriers to entry and limited substitutes reduce competitive pressure, allowing incumbents to sustain above-average profitability.', 0),
  ('cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis-q02', 'cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis', 'Which of Porter''s Five Forces is most directly weakened when a firm''s products have many close substitutes?', 'Bargaining power of suppliers', 'Threat of new entrants', 'The firm''s own pricing power', 'Rivalry among existing competitors', 'C', 'Many substitutes cap pricing power because customers can easily switch, limiting the firm''s ability to raise prices.', 1),
  ('cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis-q03', 'cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis', 'In the industry life cycle, the shakeout stage is characterised by:', 'very rapid growth, abundant new entrants, and high prices', 'negative growth and mass industry exit', 'stable and predictable growth with high barriers', 'slowing growth, industry consolidation, and declining margins for weaker players', 'D', 'The shakeout stage sees growth slow from the high-growth phase, forcing consolidation and margin compression as weaker players exit.', 2),
  ('cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis-q04', 'cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis', 'A firm creates economic value when its return on invested capital (ROIC) is:', 'less than its weighted average cost of capital (WACC)', 'equal to zero', 'greater than its weighted average cost of capital (WACC)', 'equal to its dividend yield', 'C', 'ROIC > WACC means the firm earns more than investors require, creating positive economic profit and shareholder value.', 3),
  ('cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis-q05', 'cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis', 'A company strategy built around producing at the lowest cost in the industry is best described as:', 'cost leadership strategy', 'focus strategy', 'differentiation strategy', 'blue-ocean strategy', 'A', 'Cost leadership means achieving the lowest production cost to win on price or earn higher margins at market price.', 4),
  ('cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis-q06', 'cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis', 'Strong bargaining power of suppliers in Porter''s framework will most likely result in:', 'lower input costs for the industry', 'higher input costs and compressed margins for firms in the industry', 'higher margins for downstream producers', 'increased threat of new entrants', 'B', 'Powerful suppliers extract higher prices for inputs, squeezing downstream industry margins.', 5),
  ('cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis-q07', 'cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis', 'The embryonic stage of the industry life cycle is characterised by which of the following?', 'Low prices, mature technology, and stable market share', 'Slow growth, high prices, limited product awareness, and high risk', 'Rapid customer adoption and falling prices', 'Consolidation among a few dominant players', 'B', 'In the embryonic stage, the product is new, growth is slow, prices are high, and customer awareness is limited, making it a high-risk environment.', 6),
  ('cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis-q08', 'cfa-equity-industry-company-analysis', 'SWOT analysis is best described as a framework for assessing a company''s internal:', 'leverage and liquidity ratios', 'dividend policy and capital structure decisions', 'strengths and weaknesses alongside external opportunities and threats', 'governance structure and board composition', 'C', 'SWOT examines internal Strengths and Weaknesses alongside external Opportunities and Threats to frame strategic positioning.', 7),
  ('cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation-q01', 'cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation', 'Free cash flow to the firm (FCFF) is best described as the cash flow available to:', 'equity holders only, after interest payments', 'creditors only, before operating expenses', 'the government after taxes are paid', 'all capital providers (debt and equity) after reinvestment needs', 'D', 'FCFF is pre-interest, available to both debt and equity holders after necessary reinvestment in the business.', 0),
  ('cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation-q02', 'cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation', 'When using FCFF to value a firm, the appropriate discount rate is the:', 'weighted average cost of capital (WACC)', 'risk-free rate', 'cost of equity only', 'cost of debt after tax', 'A', 'Because FCFF belongs to all capital providers, it is discounted at WACC to obtain total firm value.', 1),
  ('cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation-q03', 'cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation', 'FCFE differs from FCFF primarily because FCFE subtracts:', 'after-tax interest expense and adds net borrowing', 'changes in working capital', 'capital expenditures', 'depreciation and amortisation', 'A', 'FCFE = FCFF - Interest*(1-t) + Net borrowing, reflecting cash available to equity holders after all debt obligations.', 2),
  ('cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation-q04', 'cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation', 'In a two-stage DCF model, the terminal value represents:', 'the book value of assets at the end of the forecast period', 'the cumulative sum of all forecast-period cash flows', 'the market capitalisation at the time of the analysis', 'the present value of all cash flows beyond the explicit forecast horizon, usually modeled with a constant growth rate', 'D', 'Terminal value captures the going-concern value beyond the explicit forecast, typically modeled using a perpetuity growth formula.', 3),
  ('cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation-q05', 'cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation', 'The terminal growth rate in a DCF model is most commonly set close to:', 'the long-run nominal GDP growth rate of the economy', 'the firm''s historical earnings growth rate of the past 5 years', 'the current risk-free interest rate', 'the industry''s current revenue growth rate', 'A', 'A perpetual terminal growth rate above nominal GDP is unsustainable; it is typically anchored to long-run nominal GDP growth.', 4),
  ('cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation-q06', 'cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation', 'The portion of total DCF value typically attributed to the terminal value is:', 'less than 10% for most mature companies', 'exactly 50% by construction', 'often 60-80%, making it the dominant value driver', 'irrelevant because terminal value is not discounted', 'C', 'Terminal value typically represents 60-80% of total DCF value, highlighting the outsized importance of long-run growth and discount rate assumptions.', 5),
  ('cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation-q07', 'cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation', 'To convert FCFF-based firm value into equity value, an analyst must:', 'subtract the market value of debt and add any excess cash', 'multiply by the price-to-earnings ratio', 'divide by the number of shares outstanding only', 'add the present value of the tax shield separately', 'A', 'Equity value = Firm value (from FCFF/WACC) minus market value of debt, with excess cash and other non-operating assets added back.', 6),
  ('cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation-q08', 'cfa-equity-dcf-fcf-valuation', 'Sensitivity analysis in DCF valuation is important primarily because:', 'it replaces the need to forecast cash flows', 'it eliminates estimation error from the model', 'it allows the analyst to use accounting earnings instead of cash flows', 'small changes in the terminal growth rate or discount rate can produce large swings in estimated value', 'D', 'DCF value is highly sensitive to growth and discount rate assumptions; stress-testing inputs reveals the range of plausible values.', 7),
  ('cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev-q01', 'cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev', 'Enterprise value (EV) is most correctly calculated as market capitalisation plus debt plus preferred equity plus minority interest, minus:', 'total assets', 'accounts payable', 'intangible assets', 'cash and cash equivalents', 'D', 'EV subtracts cash because an acquirer effectively receives it, reducing the net cost of acquisition.', 0),
  ('cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev-q02', 'cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev', 'The EV/EBITDA multiple is preferred over the P/E ratio when comparing companies across different capital structures because EV/EBITDA is:', 'always smaller in value', 'unaffected by capital structure and depreciation policy differences', 'calculated using after-tax earnings', 'based on book value rather than market value', 'B', 'EV/EBITDA is capital-structure neutral (uses pre-interest EV and EBITDA) and eliminates depreciation differences, enabling cleaner peer comparisons.', 1),
  ('cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev-q03', 'cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev', 'A forward P/E ratio uses which earnings figure in its denominator?', 'Consensus analyst estimate of next 12-month earnings per share', 'The average EPS over the past 10 years (cyclically adjusted)', 'Earnings per share for the most recent fiscal year', 'EPS adjusted for stock-based compensation only', 'A', 'Forward (leading) P/E uses the analyst consensus EPS forecast for the next 12 months.', 2),
  ('cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev-q04', 'cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev', 'The price-to-book (P/B) ratio is most useful for valuing:', 'financial institutions and asset-heavy companies where book value is meaningful', 'high-growth technology companies with few tangible assets', 'companies with highly cyclical earnings', 'companies that pay no dividends', 'A', 'P/B is most meaningful for banks, insurers, and asset-heavy firms where book value approximates liquidation or replacement value.', 3),
  ('cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev-q05', 'cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev', 'The price-to-sales (P/S) ratio is commonly used for valuing loss-making companies because:', 'revenue is always a better indicator of value than earnings', 'revenue growth always leads to profitability', 'sales are easier to manipulate than earnings', 'P/S avoids the undefined P/E that results from negative earnings', 'D', 'When earnings are negative, P/E is undefined; P/S uses revenue, which is positive even for loss-making firms.', 4),
  ('cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev-q06', 'cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev', 'A stock trading at a P/E below its peer group average most likely indicates that the market expects the company to have:', 'faster earnings growth than peers', 'lower growth prospects, higher risk, or weaker profitability than peers', 'lower risk than peers', 'a more generous dividend policy', 'B', 'Lower relative P/E may signal undervaluation but more often reflects lower expected growth, higher perceived risk, or inferior profitability.', 5),
  ('cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev-q07', 'cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev', 'In a comparable company analysis, the first step is to:', 'calculate the target company''s DCF value', 'select a universe of firms that are similar in business model, size, and geography', 'determine the target''s dividend payout ratio', 'compute the target''s weighted average cost of capital', 'B', 'Comps analysis begins with identifying truly comparable companies so that peer multiples are meaningful benchmarks.', 6),
  ('cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev-q08', 'cfa-equity-price-multiples-ev', 'A key limitation of using price multiples for valuation is that they:', 'reflect current market sentiment, which may itself be mispriced relative to intrinsic value', 'cannot be computed from publicly available financial statements', 'always overestimate a company''s true intrinsic value', 'require forecasting cash flows 10 years into the future', 'A', 'Multiples are market-based and relative; if the peer group or market is broadly mispriced, the multiple-based valuation will inherit that mispricing.', 7),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation-q01', 'cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation', 'A bond with a 6% annual coupon rate is priced at 94 per 100 of par. What is the bond''s current yield?', '6.00%', '5.66%', '6.38%', '6.12%', 'C', 'Current yield = Annual coupon / Price = 6 / 94 = 6.38%. Current yield ignores capital gains and time value of money.', 0),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation-q02', 'cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation', 'Which of the following best describes the dirty price of a bond?', 'The price excluding accrued interest, as quoted in the market', 'The present value of all future cash flows, including accrued interest', 'The price adjusted for the embedded option value', 'The bond price assuming immediate default', 'B', 'The dirty price (full price) is the actual price paid by the buyer and includes accrued interest. The clean price is the quoted price that excludes accrued interest.', 1),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation-q03', 'cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation', 'A zero-coupon bond with a face value of 1,000 matures in 5 years. If the required yield is 4%, what is the bond''s price?', '800.00', '820.35', '854.80', '780.12', 'B', 'Price = 1,000 / (1.04)^5 = 1,000 / 1.2167 = 821.93, approximately 820.35. Zero-coupon bonds are priced as the present value of the single par payment.', 2),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation-q04', 'cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation', 'An investor holds a bond purchased between coupon dates. Who receives the full next coupon payment at the next coupon date?', 'The seller, as compensation for holding the bond', 'Neither; the coupon is forfeited when a bond transfers ownership', 'The coupon is split pro-rata between buyer and seller', 'The buyer, who receives the full coupon but compensated the seller via accrued interest in the purchase price', 'D', 'The buyer receives the full next coupon but pays the seller accrued interest as part of the dirty price, compensating the seller for the portion of the coupon period they held the bond.', 3),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation-q05', 'cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation', 'Which embedded option benefits the issuer, and under what rate environment is it most likely to be exercised?', 'A put option; when interest rates rise', 'A call option; when interest rates fall', 'A conversion option; when the stock price falls', 'A call option; when interest rates rise', 'B', 'A call option embedded in a bond benefits the issuer, who will call (redeem) the bond when rates fall so they can reissue cheaper debt, refinancing at a lower coupon rate.', 4),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation-q06', 'cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation', 'A bond with a 5% coupon trades at a premium to par. Which of the following must be true?', 'The bond''s YTM is less than 5%', 'The bond''s YTM is greater than 5%', 'The bond''s current yield equals its YTM', 'The bond is callable', 'A', 'When a bond trades at a premium (price above par), the required yield (YTM) must be below the coupon rate. The bond''s price will pull toward par as maturity approaches.', 5),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation-q07', 'cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation', 'A floating-rate bond pays SOFR + 150 basis points. If SOFR resets from 3.5% to 4.0%, what happens to the bond''s coupon on the next reset date?', 'It decreases by 50 bps because bond prices rise when rates fall', 'The spread narrows to compensate for the higher base rate', 'It stays the same; floating rates only reset annually', 'It increases by 50 bps, from 5.0% to 5.5%', 'D', 'The floating coupon = SOFR + spread. When SOFR rises by 50 bps to 4.0%, the coupon rises from 5.0% (3.5%+1.5%) to 5.5% (4.0%+1.5%), with the spread remaining fixed.', 6),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation-q08', 'cfa-fixed-income-bond-features-valuation', 'Which of the following bond types provides the investor with a right, not an obligation, to sell the bond back to the issuer at par before maturity?', 'Callable bond', 'Convertible bond', 'Step-up bond', 'Putable bond', 'D', 'A putable bond embeds a put option for the bondholder, giving them the right to sell the bond back to the issuer at a specified price (usually par) on specified dates, protecting against rising rates.', 7),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure-q01', 'cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure', 'The yield to maturity (YTM) assumes which of the following?', 'All coupon payments are reinvested at the current yield', 'Coupon payments are received but not reinvested', 'The bond is sold at its clean price before maturity', 'All coupon payments are reinvested at the YTM and the bond is held to maturity', 'D', 'YTM assumes the investor holds the bond to maturity and reinvests all coupon payments at the YTM itself. If reinvestment rates differ, realised return will differ from YTM.', 0),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure-q02', 'cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure', 'If the 1-year spot rate is 3% and the 2-year spot rate is 4%, what is the implied 1-year forward rate one year from now?', '5.01%', '4.0%', '3.5%', '4.5%', 'A', 'Using (1 + S2)^2 = (1 + S1)(1 + 1f1): (1.04)^2 = (1.03)(1 + 1f1), so 1f1 = (1.0816/1.03) - 1 = 5.01%.', 1),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure-q03', 'cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure', 'Which yield spread measure is most appropriate for comparing bonds with embedded options?', 'G-spread', 'Z-spread', 'OAS (option-adjusted spread)', 'Nominal spread', 'C', 'OAS removes the value of the embedded option from the Z-spread, leaving only the spread attributable to credit and liquidity risk, making it the most comparable measure across optioned bonds.', 2),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure-q04', 'cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure', 'A par curve shows yields on bonds that are priced at par. What does this imply about the coupon rates on these bonds?', 'The coupon rate equals zero for all maturities', 'The coupon rate equals the YTM for each respective maturity', 'The coupon rate is constant across all maturities', 'The coupon rate is always higher than the spot rate', 'B', 'For a bond priced at par, the coupon rate must equal the YTM. The par curve plots these coupon rates (which equal YTMs) for bonds of different maturities priced at par.', 3),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure-q05', 'cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure', 'Which of the following best describes the Z-spread?', 'A constant spread added to each spot rate on the benchmark curve to make the present value of cash flows equal to the bond''s price', 'The spread over the yield of a single benchmark government bond of similar maturity', 'The yield difference between a corporate bond and a swap rate', 'The option value embedded in a callable bond expressed as a spread', 'A', 'The Z-spread (zero-volatility spread) is a constant spread added to all points on the spot rate curve such that the discounted cash flows equal the bond''s market price, unlike the G-spread which uses a single benchmark yield.', 4),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure-q06', 'cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure', 'An upward-sloping yield curve is most consistent with which expectation about future short-term rates?', 'Short-term rates are expected to decline', 'Short-term rates are expected to rise', 'Short-term rates will remain unchanged', 'Long-term bonds are less risky than short-term bonds', 'B', 'Under the pure expectations theory, an upward-sloping yield curve implies that investors expect short-term interest rates to rise in the future, making longer-term bonds require higher yields.', 5),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure-q07', 'cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure', 'A bond''s yield to call will be lower than its yield to maturity when the bond is:', 'Trading at a premium and the call date is near', 'Trading at a discount and the call price is at par', 'A floating-rate bond with SOFR as the reference rate', 'A zero-coupon bond with no embedded options', 'A', 'YTC is lower than YTM when the bond trades at a premium and the call is near, because the investor faces the prospect of receiving par (below the current price) at call, compressing the yield calculation.', 6),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure-q08', 'cfa-fixed-income-yield-measures-term-structure', 'No-arbitrage pricing of a coupon bond requires that its price equals:', 'The sum of coupon payments divided by the YTM', 'Each cash flow discounted at its corresponding spot rate, summed across all periods', 'The par value discounted at the current short-term rate', 'The average of the spot rates multiplied by the notional value', 'B', 'No-arbitrage pricing strips each cash flow and discounts it at the spot rate for that specific maturity. Using a single YTM is an approximation; true no-arbitrage pricing uses the spot curve.', 7),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis-q01', 'cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis', 'A bond has a 2% probability of default and a recovery rate of 40%. What is the expected loss per 100 of par?', '1.20', '0.80', '2.00', '0.40', 'A', 'Expected loss = PD x LGD = 0.02 x (1 - 0.40) x 100 = 0.02 x 0.60 x 100 = 1.20. LGD is the loss per unit given default, equal to 1 minus the recovery rate.', 0),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis-q02', 'cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis', 'Which of the four Cs of credit analysis refers to the bond indenture provisions that protect bondholders?', 'Covenants', 'Character', 'Collateral', 'Capacity', 'A', 'Covenants are the legally binding terms in the bond indenture, including restrictions (negative covenants) and requirements (affirmative covenants) designed to protect the bondholder''s interests.', 1),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis-q03', 'cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis', 'A bond is rated Ba1 by Moody''s. Which of the following best characterises this rating?', 'Investment grade with very low credit risk', 'Speculative grade (high yield)', 'The highest quality investment-grade rating', 'In default with some recovery expected', 'B', 'Ba1 is Moody''s highest speculative-grade rating (equivalent to BB+ at S&P), falling below the investment-grade cutoff of Baa3/BBB-. Such bonds carry meaningful default risk.', 2),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis-q04', 'cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis', 'Which of the following is an example of a negative covenant in a bond indenture?', 'The issuer is restricted from incurring additional debt above a specified leverage ratio', 'The issuer must provide audited financial statements annually', 'The issuer must maintain adequate insurance on all assets', 'The issuer must pay interest on scheduled dates', 'A', 'Negative covenants restrict the issuer from taking certain actions, such as taking on excessive additional debt. Options A, B, and D describe affirmative covenants requiring specific actions.', 3),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis-q05', 'cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis', 'When credit spreads widen, what happens to corporate bond prices relative to equivalent-maturity government bonds?', 'Corporate bond prices fall relative to government bond prices', 'Corporate bond prices rise relative to government bond prices', 'Both prices fall by an equal amount', 'Prices are unaffected because coupons are fixed', 'A', 'Wider credit spreads mean investors demand higher yields on corporate bonds relative to governments, which drives corporate bond prices down. Government bond prices may be unchanged or move on rate expectations alone.', 4),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis-q06', 'cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis', 'The ''capacity'' component of the four Cs of credit analysis is best measured by:', 'The quality of management''s past statements', 'Cash flow metrics and leverage ratios such as debt/EBITDA', 'The assets pledged as security against the debt', 'The number of restrictive covenants in the indenture', 'B', 'Capacity refers to the borrower''s ability to repay, best measured through cash flow generation and leverage metrics like EBITDA coverage ratios and debt-to-EBITDA, which indicate ability to service and repay debt.', 5),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis-q07', 'cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis', 'Which factor would most likely cause credit rating agencies to downgrade a corporate bond?', 'An increase in the company''s interest coverage ratio', 'Refinancing of existing debt at lower interest rates', 'A significant debt-financed acquisition that substantially increases leverage', 'An improvement in the company''s operating cash flow margin', 'C', 'Debt-financed acquisitions that significantly increase leverage weaken the credit profile by reducing capacity to service debt and increasing default risk, commonly triggering a downgrade.', 6),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis-q08', 'cfa-fixed-income-credit-risk-analysis', 'A senior secured bond and a senior unsecured bond from the same issuer default simultaneously. Which bond will likely have a higher recovery rate?', 'Senior unsecured, because it has priority over operating assets', 'Both will have identical recovery rates', 'Senior secured, because it has a specific claim on pledged collateral', 'Recovery rates depend only on probability of default, not seniority', 'C', 'Senior secured bonds have a claim on specific pledged assets, giving bondholders priority in liquidation and typically resulting in higher recovery rates than senior unsecured bonds of the same issuer.', 7),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs-q01', 'cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs', 'What is the primary purpose of tranching in a securitisation structure?', 'To increase the total amount of interest paid to investors', 'To ensure the originating bank retains all credit risk', 'To eliminate prepayment risk for all investors', 'To create securities with different risk/return profiles from a single asset pool', 'D', 'Tranching divides a single pool of assets into classes (tranches) with different priorities for receiving cash flows and absorbing losses, creating senior (low risk/return) and junior (high risk/return) securities.', 0),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs-q02', 'cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs', 'Which of the following best describes contraction risk for a mortgage-backed security investor?', 'The risk that the pool of mortgages extends in duration as prepayments slow', 'The risk that borrowers default when interest rates rise', 'The risk that prepayments accelerate when rates fall, forcing reinvestment at lower yields', 'The risk that the servicer fails to pass through principal payments', 'C', 'Contraction risk is the risk that declining interest rates accelerate prepayments, returning principal early and forcing investors to reinvest at the now-lower prevailing rates.', 1),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs-q03', 'cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs', 'Which securitisation structure uses leveraged loans as its primary collateral?', 'CLO (collateralised loan obligation)', 'Agency MBS', 'Auto-loan ABS', 'Covered bond', 'A', 'A CLO (collateralised loan obligation) is backed primarily by leveraged loans made to below-investment-grade corporations, typically managed actively by a portfolio manager.', 2),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs-q04', 'cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs', 'Agency MBS issued by Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac carry minimal credit risk because:', 'They are structured with equity tranches absorbing all losses', 'They are backed exclusively by prime mortgages with LTV below 50%', 'They carry an explicit or implicit government guarantee against default', 'The underlying mortgages are insured by private mortgage insurers', 'C', 'Agency MBS are guaranteed by government-sponsored enterprises (GSEs) with implicit or explicit government backing, so investors bear virtually no credit risk on timely payment of principal and interest.', 3),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs-q05', 'cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs', 'In a sequential-pay CMO structure, which tranche receives principal payments first?', 'The longest-maturity tranche', 'The equity (residual) tranche', 'The shortest-maturity (most senior) tranche', 'All tranches receive principal payments pro-rata', 'C', 'In a sequential-pay CMO, all principal cash flows (both scheduled and prepayments) are directed to the shortest-maturity tranche until it is fully paid off, then to the next tranche, providing greater cash flow predictability for senior tranches.', 4),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs-q06', 'cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs', 'Overcollateralisation as a form of credit enhancement means that:', 'The issuer buys credit default swaps to protect investors', 'Excess interest income is used to pay down principal faster', 'A senior bond insurer guarantees principal and interest payments', 'The face value of the asset pool exceeds the face value of securities issued', 'D', 'Overcollateralisation means the securitised pool''s face value exceeds the total notes issued, providing a cushion so that some defaults can be absorbed before investors suffer losses.', 5),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs-q07', 'cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs', 'Extension risk in MBS is most likely to materialise when:', 'Interest rates decline sharply and homeowners refinance', 'The servicer advances delinquent payments to investors', 'Housing prices fall and defaults increase', 'Interest rates rise and prepayment speeds slow significantly', 'D', 'Extension risk occurs when rising rates reduce prepayments, causing the MBS''s average life to lengthen beyond expectations. Investors are locked into lower-yielding securities longer than anticipated.', 6),
  ('cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs-q08', 'cfa-fixed-income-securitisation-abs', 'The waterfall structure in a securitisation primarily determines:', 'The credit ratings assigned to each tranche by rating agencies', 'The interest rate applicable to floating-rate tranches', 'The order in which cash flows are distributed to and losses are absorbed by each tranche', 'The legal ownership of the underlying assets', 'C', 'The waterfall defines the priority rules for distributing interest and principal to tranches (senior first) and for absorbing losses (junior/equity first), determining each tranche''s risk and return characteristics.', 7),
  ('cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures-q01', 'cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures', 'A stock is priced at 100, the risk-free rate is 5% per year, and the stock pays no dividends. What is the no-arbitrage 1-year forward price?', '105.00', '100.00', '110.00', '95.24', 'A', 'Forward price = S0 x (1 + r)^T = 100 x (1.05)^1 = 105. This reflects the cost of carry (financing the spot position) with no income or storage costs.', 0),
  ('cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures-q02', 'cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures', 'Which of the following is the primary difference between a forward contract and a futures contract?', 'Forwards are settled daily; futures settle only at expiration', 'Only futures require an initial margin deposit from both parties', 'Futures expose both parties to unlimited credit risk', 'Futures are standardised and exchange-traded with daily mark-to-market; forwards are OTC and settle at expiration', 'D', 'Futures contracts are standardised, exchange-traded, and marked to market daily (with variation margin), which virtually eliminates counterparty credit risk. Forward contracts are customised OTC agreements settling only at maturity.', 1),
  ('cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures-q03', 'cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures', 'A commodity is in backwardation. This most likely indicates that:', 'Storage costs for the commodity are very high', 'The risk-free rate is below zero', 'Futures prices exceed spot prices for all maturities', 'The convenience yield or near-term supply tightness outweighs carrying costs', 'D', 'Backwardation (futures price below spot) occurs when the convenience yield of holding the physical commodity is high enough to offset or exceed the cost of carry, often reflecting near-term supply tightness or high immediate demand.', 2),
  ('cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures-q04', 'cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures', 'An investor is long a futures contract with a current futures price of 200. The next day the price falls to 195. What is the mark-to-market cash flow to the investor?', '-5 (investor pays variation margin)', '+5 (investor receives variation margin)', '0 (futures only settle at expiration)', '+5 (the long always receives the price change)', 'A', 'A long futures position loses when the futures price falls. The investor''s margin account is debited by 5, requiring them to pay variation margin. Daily settlement is a key feature distinguishing futures from forwards.', 3),
  ('cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures-q05', 'cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures', 'Basis risk in a hedge arises primarily from:', 'The possibility that the futures price converges exactly to spot at expiration', 'The counterparty risk associated with OTC forward contracts', 'The daily mark-to-market requirement of exchange-traded futures', 'A mismatch between the asset being hedged and the asset underlying the futures contract, or an imperfect hedge horizon', 'D', 'Basis risk results when the hedged asset differs from the futures contract''s underlying asset (cross hedge) or when the hedge is lifted before contract expiry, causing the basis to differ from expectations.', 4),
  ('cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures-q06', 'cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures', 'A stock index futures contract is in contango. An investor who rolls long futures positions repeatedly (rolling to the next contract as each expires) will experience:', 'A positive roll yield, as contracts are purchased at a discount', 'No roll yield, as spot and futures prices always converge', 'A negative roll yield, as each new contract is purchased at a higher price than the expiring one', 'A positive roll yield because long positions benefit from rising prices', 'C', 'In contango, the futures curve slopes upward. A long investor sells the expiring (lower-priced) contract and buys the next (higher-priced) one, generating a negative roll yield or ''roll cost''.', 5),
  ('cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures-q07', 'cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures', 'A forward price that is higher than the no-arbitrage price would allow an arbitrageur to profit by:', 'Selling the asset short today and entering a long forward position', 'Doing nothing, since markets are efficient', 'Buying the forward and simultaneously selling another forward at the same price', 'Buying the asset today, financing with borrowed funds, and selling a forward contract', 'D', 'If the forward is overpriced, an arbitrageur buys the spot asset (using borrowed funds) and sells the overpriced forward, locking in a riskless profit equal to the difference between the market forward price and the no-arbitrage price.', 6),
  ('cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures-q08', 'cfa-derivatives-forwards-futures', 'Which of the following assets will have its forward price reduced below S0 x (1+r)^T due to carrying benefits?', 'Gold stored in a vault with significant insurance costs', 'A non-dividend-paying growth stock', 'Crude oil with high storage and transportation costs', 'A dividend-paying stock where dividends are paid during the forward period', 'D', 'Dividends paid during the forward period are a benefit to the asset holder that reduces the cost of carry. The forward price is adjusted downward by the present value of expected dividends: F0 = (S0 - PV(dividends)) x (1+r)^T.', 7),
  ('cfa-derivatives-swaps-q01', 'cfa-derivatives-swaps', 'In a plain vanilla interest rate swap, which party benefits when the floating reference rate rises above the fixed swap rate?', 'Both parties benefit equally', 'The fixed-rate receiver (floating-rate payer)', 'The fixed-rate payer (floating-rate receiver)', 'Neither party benefits; swaps are zero-sum only at inception', 'C', 'The fixed-rate payer pays a set amount and receives the now-higher floating rate, resulting in net receipts. The fixed-rate payer profits when the floating rate rises above the fixed rate.', 0),
  ('cfa-derivatives-swaps-q02', 'cfa-derivatives-swaps', 'At inception, the fixed rate on a plain vanilla interest rate swap is set so that:', 'The fixed-rate payer has a positive net present value position', 'The notional principal is exchanged between both parties', 'The swap has zero value to both counterparties', 'The floating rate equals the fixed rate for the first period only', 'C', 'The swap fixed rate (par rate) is determined so that the present value of expected floating payments equals the present value of fixed payments, giving the swap zero initial value to both parties.', 1),
  ('cfa-derivatives-swaps-q03', 'cfa-derivatives-swaps', 'A corporation has issued floating-rate debt and wants to convert its interest payments to fixed. Which swap position achieves this?', 'Receive fixed, pay floating (the corporation is already floating)', 'Receive floating, receive fixed simultaneously', 'Pay fixed, receive floating', 'Enter a currency swap to convert the debt to another currency', 'C', 'The corporation already pays floating on its debt and receives floating from the swap, with the two floating legs netting. The net result is that the corporation effectively pays only the fixed rate on the swap.', 2),
  ('cfa-derivatives-swaps-q04', 'cfa-derivatives-swaps', 'How does a currency swap differ from an interest rate swap regarding principal?', 'Neither swap involves exchange of principal', 'Currency swaps involve exchange of principal in two currencies at the start and end; interest rate swaps do not exchange principal', 'Interest rate swaps exchange principal only at maturity', 'Both swaps exchange principal at the start but not at maturity', 'B', 'In currency swaps, counterparties exchange equivalent notional amounts in two currencies at inception and re-exchange them at maturity at the originally agreed exchange rate. Interest rate swaps never exchange the notional principal.', 3),
  ('cfa-derivatives-swaps-q05', 'cfa-derivatives-swaps', 'After initiation, a receive-fixed interest rate swap gains value when:', 'Interest rates rise, increasing the value of fixed cash inflows', 'Interest rates fall, increasing the present value of the fixed receipts relative to floating payments', 'The notional principal increases over time', 'Credit spreads tighten in the interbank market', 'B', 'When rates fall, the fixed receipts become more valuable relative to the now-lower expected floating payments. The receive-fixed position gains value, similar to holding a fixed-rate bond.', 4),
  ('cfa-derivatives-swaps-q06', 'cfa-derivatives-swaps', 'Which of the following is NOT a typical use of a currency swap?', 'Speculating on short-term equity price movements', 'Accessing lower borrowing costs in foreign capital markets', 'Hedging long-term foreign currency revenue streams', 'Converting foreign currency debt to domestic currency obligations', 'A', 'Currency swaps are used to manage foreign exchange exposure over long periods, access foreign capital markets, and hedge revenue streams. They are not instruments for short-term equity speculation.', 5),
  ('cfa-derivatives-swaps-q07', 'cfa-derivatives-swaps', 'In an interest rate swap with quarterly settlement, the net payment made by the fixed-rate payer for a given quarter is determined by:', '(Fixed rate - Floating rate) x Notional x (90/360)', '(Floating rate - Fixed rate) x Notional x (90/360)', 'Fixed rate x Notional x (90/360)', 'Floating rate x Notional / 4', 'A', 'The fixed-rate payer''s net quarterly payment is (Fixed rate - Floating rate) x Notional x day count fraction. If positive, the fixed-rate payer makes a net payment; if negative, they receive a net payment.', 6),
  ('cfa-derivatives-swaps-q08', 'cfa-derivatives-swaps', 'An equity swap where one party pays the return on a stock index and receives a fixed rate is most similar to:', 'Selling the stock index and investing the proceeds at the fixed rate', 'Buying the stock index on margin', 'Entering a long forward contract on the stock index', 'Writing a covered call on the stock index', 'A', 'Paying the equity return and receiving fixed replicates the payoff of selling the equity exposure and earning a fixed rate, effectively converting equity risk into a fixed-income position without physically selling assets.', 7),
  ('cfa-derivatives-option-strategies-q01', 'cfa-derivatives-option-strategies', 'An investor holds 100 shares of stock and writes a call option on those shares. This strategy is called a:', 'Covered call', 'Bull call spread', 'Protective put', 'Straddle', 'A', 'A covered call involves holding the underlying asset and writing (selling) a call option on it. The strategy generates premium income but caps upside participation above the strike price.', 0),
  ('cfa-derivatives-option-strategies-q02', 'cfa-derivatives-option-strategies', 'A long straddle position profits when:', 'The underlying price remains near the strike price at expiration', 'The stock pays a large dividend before expiration', 'Implied volatility declines after the position is entered', 'The underlying price makes a large move in either direction', 'D', 'A long straddle (long call + long put at the same strike) profits from large price moves in either direction. The total premium paid is lost if the stock price stays near the strike at expiration.', 1),
  ('cfa-derivatives-option-strategies-q03', 'cfa-derivatives-option-strategies', 'Delta for a long at-the-money call option is approximately:', '0', '+0.5', '+1.0', '-0.5', 'B', 'An at-the-money call option has a delta of approximately 0.5, meaning the option price changes by about 0.50 for each 1.00 change in the underlying asset price. Deep in-the-money calls approach delta of 1; far out-of-the-money calls approach 0.', 2),
  ('cfa-derivatives-option-strategies-q04', 'cfa-derivatives-option-strategies', 'Which Greek measures the rate at which an option loses value purely due to the passage of time, all else equal?', 'Vega', 'Theta', 'Delta', 'Gamma', 'B', 'Theta measures time decay, the rate at which an option''s time value erodes as expiration approaches. Theta is negative for long option positions, meaning the option loses value as time passes.', 3),
  ('cfa-derivatives-option-strategies-q05', 'cfa-derivatives-option-strategies', 'A bull call spread involves:', 'Buying a call with a higher strike and selling a call with a lower strike', 'Buying a call with a lower strike and selling a call with a higher strike', 'Buying both a call and a put at the same strike', 'Selling a put at a lower strike and buying a put at a higher strike', 'B', 'A bull call spread buys a lower-strike call (more expensive) and sells a higher-strike call (cheaper), reducing the net premium cost. It profits from moderate upward price moves with capped maximum gain and limited loss.', 4),
  ('cfa-derivatives-option-strategies-q06', 'cfa-derivatives-option-strategies', 'Vega is highest for options that are:', 'Deep in the money with a very short time to expiration', 'Far out of the money expiring today', 'Deep in the money with a long time to expiration', 'At the money with a long time to expiration', 'D', 'Vega, the sensitivity to implied volatility, is greatest for at-the-money options with long expiries because these options have the most time value that can be affected by volatility changes.', 5),
  ('cfa-derivatives-option-strategies-q07', 'cfa-derivatives-option-strategies', 'A protective put strategy is best described as:', 'Selling a put option to generate premium income on a long stock position', 'Writing both a call and a put at the same strike on the same stock', 'Buying a call option to replace a long stock position', 'Buying a put option on a stock already held long, to limit downside risk', 'D', 'A protective put combines a long stock position with a long put, acting as insurance. The put limits losses below the strike price while preserving the upside. The put premium is the cost of this protection.', 6),
  ('cfa-derivatives-option-strategies-q08', 'cfa-derivatives-option-strategies', 'Gamma is the largest for an option that is:', 'Deep in the money and near expiration', 'Far out of the money with a long time to expiration', 'At the money and near expiration', 'Deep in the money with a long time to expiration', 'C', 'Gamma, the rate of change of delta, peaks for at-the-money options near expiration because small price moves near expiry can rapidly shift whether the option finishes in or out of the money, causing large delta changes.', 7),
  ('cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications-q01', 'cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications', 'A portfolio manager wants to reduce the beta of a 10 million equity portfolio from 1.2 to 0.8 using equity index futures. The futures contract has a price of 250,000. How many contracts should be sold?', '8 contracts', '48 contracts', '16 contracts', '32 contracts', 'C', 'Number of contracts = (Target beta - Portfolio beta) / Futures beta x (Portfolio value / Futures price) = (0.8 - 1.2) / 1.0 x (10,000,000 / 250,000) = -0.4 x 40 = -16. Sell 16 contracts.', 0),
  ('cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications-q02', 'cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications', 'A fixed income portfolio manager expects interest rates to rise and wants to reduce duration. Which derivative action achieves this most directly?', 'Enter a receive-fixed interest rate swap', 'Buy interest rate call options', 'Enter a pay-fixed interest rate swap', 'Sell put options on Treasury bonds', 'C', 'Entering a pay-fixed, receive-floating swap reduces portfolio duration. Paying fixed is equivalent to holding a short position in a fixed-rate bond, offsetting the duration of long fixed-income holdings.', 1),
  ('cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications-q03', 'cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications', 'A US company expects to receive EUR 5 million in 6 months. To hedge the currency risk, the company should:', 'Buy EUR forward (agree to purchase EUR in 6 months at today''s forward rate)', 'Sell EUR forward (agree to sell EUR in 6 months at today''s forward rate)', 'Buy a EUR call option to benefit from EUR appreciation', 'Enter a pay-fixed EUR interest rate swap', 'B', 'The company will receive EUR and needs to convert to USD. It should sell EUR forward (lock in the rate at which it will sell EUR and receive USD), eliminating uncertainty about the USD proceeds.', 2),
  ('cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications-q04', 'cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications', 'An interest rate cap is most useful to:', 'A fixed-rate borrower seeking to benefit from falling rates', 'A floating-rate borrower seeking to limit maximum interest expense', 'An investor who wants to lock in a minimum return on a floating-rate bond', 'A bond portfolio manager seeking to extend duration', 'B', 'An interest rate cap pays the holder when the reference rate exceeds the cap rate, compensating a floating-rate borrower for the excess interest cost. It effectively sets a maximum borrowing rate.', 3),
  ('cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications-q05', 'cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications', 'Translation exposure for a multinational corporation arises from:', 'The risk of currency movements affecting future foreign currency transactions', 'The long-run effect of exchange rate changes on competitive position', 'The accounting impact of converting foreign subsidiary financial statements into the parent''s reporting currency', 'The credit risk of foreign counterparties in derivative contracts', 'C', 'Translation exposure (accounting exposure) arises when consolidating foreign subsidiaries'' financial statements into the parent''s reporting currency. Assets and liabilities denominated in foreign currencies must be converted at current exchange rates.', 4),
  ('cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications-q06', 'cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications', 'To synthetically create an equity position without owning the underlying stock, an investor could:', 'Sell equity index futures and invest the notional in cash', 'Buy equity index futures and invest the notional cash in risk-free assets', 'Enter a receive-fixed, pay-floating interest rate swap', 'Buy put options and simultaneously sell call options at the same strike', 'B', 'Buying futures provides exposure to equity returns while the notional is held in cash (earning the risk-free rate). This synthetic long replicates full equity exposure without purchasing shares directly.', 5),
  ('cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications-q07', 'cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications', 'A portfolio manager holds a large position in a stock and buys put options on that stock. Compared to an unhedged position, this strategy:', 'Eliminates all risk and all potential return above the strike', 'Reduces upside participation but does not limit downside losses', 'Generates income that offsets stock purchase costs', 'Limits downside loss while preserving upside participation, at the cost of the put premium', 'D', 'Buying a put provides downside protection below the strike price (acting as insurance) while the stock position retains upside potential. The cost is the put premium, which reduces overall return by that amount.', 6),
  ('cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications-q08', 'cfa-derivatives-risk-management-applications', 'Economic exposure to currency risk is best described as:', 'The long-run impact of exchange rate changes on a firm''s competitive position and future cash flows', 'The risk of loss on specific foreign currency receivables or payables', 'The short-term accounting impact of translating foreign currency balances', 'The mark-to-market loss on foreign currency derivative contracts', 'A', 'Economic exposure captures the broader, long-run impact of exchange rate fluctuations on a firm''s operating cash flows, pricing power, and competitive position, which is harder to hedge than specific transaction exposures.', 7),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate-q01', 'cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate', 'A property generates annual gross rental income of $500,000 with vacancy losses of $25,000 and operating expenses of $175,000. What is the Net Operating Income (NOI)?', '$300,000', '$325,000', '$500,000', '$475,000', 'A', 'NOI = Gross rent - Vacancy losses - Operating expenses = $500,000 - $25,000 - $175,000 = $300,000. Debt service is excluded from NOI.', 0),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate-q02', 'cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate', 'A property has an NOI of $600,000 and is valued at $8,000,000. What is its capitalization rate?', '13.3%', '5.5%', '8.0%', '7.5%', 'D', 'Cap rate = NOI / Property value = $600,000 / $8,000,000 = 7.5%. A lower cap rate signals a higher valuation relative to income.', 1),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate-q03', 'cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate', 'Compared with direct real estate ownership, Real Estate Investment Trusts (REITs) primarily offer investors:', 'Greater control over property management decisions', 'Lower correlation with equity markets', 'Improved liquidity and easier diversification', 'Tax advantages unavailable in direct ownership', 'C', 'REITs are publicly traded, providing daily liquidity and easy diversification across property types and regions that direct ownership cannot match.', 2),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate-q04', 'cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate', 'During which phase of the real estate cycle do vacancy rates typically fall and rents begin to rise, but new construction has not yet responded?', 'Hyper-supply', 'Recession', 'Expansion', 'Recovery', 'C', 'In the expansion phase, demand absorbs existing supply, vacancy falls, and rents rise, though new development is still ramping up.', 3),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate-q05', 'cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate', 'Which real estate property type is most sensitive to economic cycles due to its high operational complexity?', 'Industrial warehouses', 'Hospitality (hotels)', 'Multifamily residential', 'Net-lease retail', 'B', 'Hospitality real estate has the highest operational complexity and most cyclical demand, as room rates and occupancy are repriced daily based on economic conditions.', 4),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate-q06', 'cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate', 'If cap rates in a market rise from 5% to 6% and the property''s NOI remains constant at $300,000, the property''s value will:', 'Increase from $5,000,000 to $6,000,000', 'Decrease from $5,000,000 to $4,545,455', 'Remain unchanged because NOI is constant', 'Decrease from $6,000,000 to $5,000,000', 'D', 'Value = NOI / Cap rate. At 5% the value is $6,000,000; at 6% it falls to $5,000,000. Rising cap rates compress property values when NOI is fixed.', 5),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate-q07', 'cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate', 'Which of the following best describes the Gross Income Multiplier (GIM)?', 'Property price divided by annual gross income', 'Net operating income divided by the property''s market value', 'Annual gross income minus operating expenses', 'Property value multiplied by the cap rate', 'A', 'GIM = Property price / Gross income. It is a quick valuation shortcut but ignores vacancy and operating expenses, unlike the cap rate approach.', 6),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate-q08', 'cfa-alternative-investments-real-estate', 'Industrial real estate has experienced strong secular demand growth primarily because of:', 'Declining interest rates reducing cap rates', 'Increased remote work reducing office demand', 'The expansion of e-commerce requiring logistics and warehouse space', 'Demographic shifts toward urban apartment living', 'C', 'E-commerce growth has driven sustained demand for distribution centers and last-mile logistics warehouses, benefiting the industrial property sector.', 7),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-commodities-q01', 'cfa-alternative-investments-commodities', 'A commodity futures market is in contango when:', 'The futures price exceeds the current spot price', 'Futures prices are below expected future spot prices', 'The spot price exceeds the futures price', 'Roll yield is positive for long futures holders', 'A', 'Contango exists when futures prices are higher than the current spot price. Long investors rolling futures forward incur a negative roll yield in contango.', 0),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-commodities-q02', 'cfa-alternative-investments-commodities', 'The total return of a long commodity futures position consists of which three components?', 'Spot return, roll yield, and collateral yield', 'Dividend yield, price return, and currency return', 'Convenience yield, storage costs, and risk-free rate', 'Income return, capital return, and inflation adjustment', 'A', 'The three components are: spot return (change in commodity price), roll yield (gain or loss from rolling futures contracts), and collateral yield (return on the margin collateral).', 1),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-commodities-q03', 'cfa-alternative-investments-commodities', 'Convenience yield is best described as:', 'The tax benefit of holding commodity futures rather than physical goods', 'The non-monetary benefit from holding physical inventory of a commodity', 'The yield earned on cash posted as futures margin collateral', 'The premium futures traders earn for providing liquidity to the market', 'B', 'Convenience yield reflects the benefit of having immediate access to physical inventory (e.g., uninterrupted production), which futures holders do not enjoy.', 2),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-commodities-q04', 'cfa-alternative-investments-commodities', 'A commodity market is in backwardation. What does this imply for a long futures investor rolling contracts forward?', 'The investor incurs a negative roll yield, reducing total return', 'The investor must pay the convenience yield to the seller', 'Roll yield is zero because the spot price equals the futures price', 'The investor earns a positive roll yield, enhancing total return', 'D', 'In backwardation, near-dated futures are priced above longer-dated ones. Rolling from an expiring contract into a cheaper forward contract generates positive roll yield.', 3),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-commodities-q05', 'cfa-alternative-investments-commodities', 'Which commodity index is most heavily weighted toward energy commodities?', 'Bloomberg Commodity Index', 'S&P GSCI', 'Rogers International Commodity Index', 'Deutsche Bank Liquid Commodity Index', 'B', 'The S&P GSCI weights commodities by world production, which makes it heavily concentrated in energy (often 60-70% or more), unlike the more diversified Bloomberg Commodity Index.', 4),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-commodities-q06', 'cfa-alternative-investments-commodities', 'The primary reason commodities are included in a diversified multi-asset portfolio is:', 'They provide high current income through dividends', 'They have historically offered a partial inflation hedge and low correlation with stocks and bonds', 'Commodity futures always outperform equities during bull markets', 'Physical commodities are easy to store and transport', 'B', 'Commodities provide diversification because their prices often rise with inflation and they have historically shown low correlation with traditional asset classes.', 5),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-commodities-q07', 'cfa-alternative-investments-commodities', 'Which of the following is the spot price of a commodity?', 'The price for delivery at a specified future date', 'The current market price for immediate delivery', 'The average price over the past 12 months', 'The price adjusted for storage costs and financing', 'B', 'The spot price is the price at which a commodity can be bought or sold for immediate delivery, as opposed to the futures price for future delivery.', 6),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-commodities-q08', 'cfa-alternative-investments-commodities', 'An investor holds a long position in crude oil futures. After one month, the near-month contract expires and the investor rolls into the next contract at a higher price. The roll yield in this transaction is:', 'Positive, because the investor moved to a higher-priced contract', 'Positive, because crude oil is always in backwardation', 'Zero, because the gain on the expiring contract offsets the cost of the new one', 'Negative, because buying the more expensive forward contract results in a loss', 'D', 'Rolling from an expiring contract into a more expensive forward contract (contango) generates negative roll yield, reducing total return for the long investor.', 7),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure-q01', 'cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure', 'Which of the following characteristics most distinguishes infrastructure from other real assets?', 'Regulated or contracted revenues providing predictable cash flows', 'High liquidity and ease of trading on secondary markets', 'Short economic lives requiring frequent asset replacement', 'High sensitivity to commodity price fluctuations', 'A', 'Infrastructure assets typically operate under regulatory frameworks or long-term contracts that provide predictable, often inflation-linked revenue streams, which is their defining characteristic.', 0),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure-q02', 'cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure', 'A greenfield infrastructure investment differs from a brownfield investment primarily in that:', 'Greenfield investments involve acquiring operating assets with established cash flows', 'Greenfield investments involve building new assets and bear construction and ramp-up risk', 'Greenfield investments are exclusively financed by governments', 'Greenfield investments have lower required returns due to lower risk', 'B', 'Greenfield projects involve new construction and face risks including cost overruns, delays, and uncertain demand during ramp-up, requiring higher return expectations than brownfield assets.', 1),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure-q03', 'cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure', 'Why are infrastructure investments particularly attractive to pension funds with defined-benefit liabilities?', 'Infrastructure offers the highest expected returns of all asset classes', 'Infrastructure has no correlation with interest rates, eliminating duration risk', 'Infrastructure assets are highly liquid and can be sold quickly when liabilities come due', 'Long-dated, often inflation-linked cash flows match the duration of long-term liabilities', 'D', 'Defined-benefit pension funds have long-duration liabilities; infrastructure''s long-life, inflation-linked cash flows provide natural asset-liability matching.', 2),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure-q04', 'cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure', 'In a Public-Private Partnership (PPP), risk is:', 'Borne entirely by the private sector operator', 'Borne entirely by the government entity', 'Transferred fully to the end-users through user fees', 'Shared between the government and the private operator', 'D', 'PPPs are structured to allocate each type of risk (construction, demand, political) to the party best able to manage it, creating a shared risk arrangement.', 3),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure-q05', 'cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure', 'Which statement best describes timberland as an alternative investment?', 'Timberland generates returns solely from land appreciation', 'Income comes from timber harvests and the asset benefits from biological growth of trees', 'Timberland is highly correlated with commodity futures markets', 'Returns are driven primarily by government subsidy programs', 'B', 'Timberland generates income from harvesting timber and benefits from biological growth (trees grow larger over time), giving investors flexibility to time harvests based on price conditions.', 4),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure-q06', 'cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure', 'Brownfield infrastructure assets are expected to earn lower returns than greenfield assets because:', 'Brownfield assets are smaller and less strategically important', 'Brownfield assets have established cash flows and lower construction risk', 'Brownfield assets require higher ongoing capital expenditure', 'Brownfield assets are subject to more regulatory oversight', 'B', 'The risk premium on brownfield assets is lower because they are already operational, have demonstrable cash flow histories, and do not carry construction or demand ramp-up risk.', 5),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure-q07', 'cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure', 'The demand for infrastructure services is best described as:', 'Highly elastic, as users can easily substitute alternative services', 'Relatively inelastic, because infrastructure provides essential services with few substitutes', 'Perfectly elastic, because prices are set by competitive markets', 'Pro-cyclical, with demand falling sharply during economic recessions', 'B', 'Infrastructure provides essential services such as water, electricity, and transportation, for which demand is relatively price-inelastic and less sensitive to economic cycles.', 6),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure-q08', 'cfa-alternative-investments-infrastructure', 'Farmland investments generate returns primarily from:', 'Crop production income and potential land appreciation', 'Government agricultural subsidies and tax credits', 'Rising commodity futures prices on organized exchanges', 'Biological growth similar to timberland investments', 'A', 'Farmland returns come from leasing or operating the land to produce crops (income return) and from appreciation in land values over time (capital return).', 7),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence-q01', 'cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence', 'Operational due diligence (ODD) in alternative investments primarily focuses on:', 'Assessing non-investment risks such as fund administration, custody, and valuation procedures', 'Evaluating the attractiveness of the manager''s investment strategy and return potential', 'Reviewing the manager''s historical return record relative to peers', 'Analyzing the portfolio''s factor exposures and concentration risk', 'A', 'ODD focuses on non-investment operational risks including back-office controls, custody arrangements, valuation processes, compliance, and IT systems.', 0),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence-q02', 'cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence', 'When evaluating an alternative investment manager, which factor represents key-person risk?', 'The manager charges fees above the industry median', 'The fund relies heavily on one or a few individuals whose departure could impair performance', 'The manager invests in geographically concentrated assets', 'The fund uses a complex valuation methodology for illiquid assets', 'B', 'Key-person risk arises when a fund''s performance depends critically on specific individuals; if they depart, the investment thesis and returns may be materially impaired.', 1),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence-q03', 'cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence', 'The TVPI (Total Value to Paid-In) multiple in private equity measures:', 'The ratio of distributions plus remaining net asset value to total capital invested', 'The annualized rate of return earned since the fund''s inception', 'The percentage of committed capital that has been called and invested', 'The excess return earned above a public market benchmark', 'A', 'TVPI = (Distributions + Residual NAV) / Paid-in capital. It captures total value created relative to capital deployed, combining realized and unrealized returns.', 2),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence-q04', 'cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence', 'An investor reviewing an alternative fund notices that the portfolio currently holds assets in strategies different from those described in the fund''s offering documents. This is an example of:', 'Operational risk, identified through back-office review', 'Benchmark misalignment, identified through performance attribution', 'Liquidity risk, identified through cash flow analysis', 'Style drift, identified through portfolio-level due diligence', 'D', 'Style drift occurs when a manager deviates from the stated investment strategy. It is identified by comparing current holdings to the strategy described in the fund documents.', 3),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence-q05', 'cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence', 'Which of the following is the most appropriate performance benchmark for a private equity buyout fund?', 'The S&P 500 total return index', 'The 90-day Treasury bill rate', 'A peer universe of comparable private equity funds with a similar vintage year and strategy', 'An equal-weighted basket of publicly traded financial companies', 'C', 'Private equity is best evaluated against a peer universe of funds with the same vintage year, geography, and strategy, as public benchmarks do not reflect the same risk profile or return timing.', 4),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence-q06', 'cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence', 'A strong historical track record is insufficient for manager selection because:', 'The same team, strategy, and risk level may not be in place going forward', 'Past returns are always higher than future returns due to mean reversion', 'Historical returns are never audited and therefore unreliable', 'Regulators prohibit using past performance in manager selection decisions', 'A', 'Past returns may reflect a different team, strategy, market environment, or leverage level. Investors must confirm the investment process generating past returns will continue unchanged.', 5),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence-q07', 'cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence', 'The DPI (Distributed to Paid-In) multiple is preferred over TVPI when an investor wants to assess:', 'Realized cash returned to investors relative to capital invested', 'The annualized return relative to a public market equivalent', 'Total paper gains including unrealized appreciation', 'The fund''s remaining investment capacity', 'A', 'DPI measures only realized distributions; unlike TVPI, it excludes unrealized NAV and therefore reflects cash actually returned to investors, making it a more conservative measure.', 6),
  ('cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence-q08', 'cfa-alternative-investments-due-diligence', 'Strategy fit in alternative manager selection means:', 'The manager''s strategy matches the investor''s portfolio objectives, risk budget, and liquidity needs', 'The manager''s fee structure aligns with industry norms', 'The manager''s returns have historically beaten the benchmark', 'The manager''s team has more than 10 years of experience', 'A', 'Strategy fit ensures that an alternative manager''s approach, risk level, liquidity terms, and expected return are consistent with the investor''s overall portfolio objectives and constraints.', 7),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning-q01', 'cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning', 'Which of the following best describes the purpose of an Investment Policy Statement (IPS)?', 'To specify the exact securities a portfolio manager must purchase', 'To translate a client''s situation and goals into guidelines governing portfolio management', 'To legally protect the investment manager from client lawsuits', 'To record the portfolio''s historical performance and benchmark comparisons', 'B', 'The IPS translates a client''s objectives and constraints into actionable investment guidelines, serving as the governing document for the entire investment process.', 0),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning-q02', 'cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning', 'A client expresses a strong desire to take on significant investment risk to achieve high returns, but her financial situation shows she cannot afford meaningful capital losses. How should the portfolio manager determine the appropriate risk level?', 'Use the higher of willingness and ability to take risk, to honor client preferences', 'Use the lower of willingness and ability to take risk, since that is the binding constraint', 'Average the willingness and ability to take risk', 'Focus only on the client''s stated willingness because the manager cannot assess ability', 'B', 'When willingness and ability to bear risk conflict, the more conservative (lower) tolerance governs. The manager should counsel the client on the gap while respecting the binding constraint.', 1),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning-q03', 'cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning', 'The TTLLU acronym in IPS construction stands for which five constraints?', 'Tax, Trend, Liquidity, Leverage, Uncertainty', 'Trading costs, Turnover, Leverage, Liquidity, Uncertainty', 'Time horizon, Tax, Liquidity, Legal & regulatory, Unique circumstances', 'Time horizon, Tracking error, Leverage, Liquidity, Upside', 'C', 'TTLLU covers the five standard IPS constraints: Time horizon, Tax concerns, Liquidity needs, Legal and regulatory requirements, and Unique circumstances such as ESG preferences.', 2),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning-q04', 'cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning', 'A 35-year-old investor saving for retirement at age 65 has a time horizon that is best described as:', 'Short-term, requiring a conservative fixed-income-heavy allocation', 'Medium-term, because markets are uncertain beyond 10 years', 'Multi-stage, because the investor also has near-term spending needs', 'Long-term, supporting a higher allocation to growth assets', 'D', 'A 30-year horizon until retirement is long-term, allowing the investor to tolerate short-term volatility in exchange for higher expected returns from equities and growth assets.', 3),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning-q05', 'cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning', 'Which institution typically has the longest time horizon and highest risk tolerance among institutional investors?', 'Life insurance companies', 'Defined-benefit pension funds in pay-out phase', 'Commercial banks', 'University endowment funds', 'D', 'University endowments have effectively perpetual time horizons and no fixed liabilities, allowing them to maintain high allocations to illiquid alternatives and equities.', 4),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning-q06', 'cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning', 'A client''s return objective states they need a 6% annual return to meet their goals. Their portfolio currently has a risk tolerance consistent with a maximum 12% standard deviation. This information should be:', 'Used independently; return and risk objectives need not be consistent with each other', 'Overridden by the manager''s own capital market assumptions', 'Reconciled so that the risk level can realistically support the return objective', 'Set aside until markets are more predictable', 'C', 'Return and risk objectives must be consistent. If the stated risk level cannot realistically generate the required return, the conflict must be resolved before portfolio construction begins.', 5),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning-q07', 'cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning', 'An investor specifies in her IPS that she will not hold tobacco or weapons manufacturers. This would be categorized under which IPS constraint?', 'Liquidity needs', 'Unique circumstances', 'Legal and regulatory', 'Time horizon', 'B', 'ESG restrictions, ethical preferences, and social screens are classified under unique circumstances, as they reflect individual values not captured by the other standard constraints.', 6),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning-q08', 'cfa-portfolio-management-ips-planning', 'After constructing a portfolio consistent with a client''s IPS, when should the IPS be reviewed and potentially updated?', 'Only when the portfolio significantly underperforms its benchmark', 'On a fixed schedule only, regardless of changes in the client''s circumstances', 'Whenever there is a material change in the client''s goals, financial situation, or constraints', 'Every 10 years to reflect long-run changes in capital markets', 'C', 'The IPS should be reviewed and updated whenever a significant life event or change in financial circumstances alters the client''s objectives or constraints, in addition to regular periodic reviews.', 7),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation-q01', 'cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation', 'Strategic asset allocation (SAA) is best defined as:', 'Short-term deviations from target weights to exploit market inefficiencies', 'The allocation to a single asset class that minimizes portfolio variance', 'Long-term target weights across asset classes consistent with the investor''s IPS', 'The process of selecting individual securities within each asset class', 'C', 'SAA establishes long-term target weights based on the investor''s objectives, constraints, and long-run capital market expectations, forming the baseline portfolio.', 0),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation-q02', 'cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation', 'Tactical asset allocation (TAA) differs from strategic asset allocation in that TAA:', 'Is based on long-run capital market expectations rather than short-term views', 'Focuses exclusively on rebalancing the portfolio back to its SAA targets', 'Eliminates all tracking error relative to the benchmark', 'Introduces deliberate short-term deviations from SAA based on market forecasts', 'D', 'TAA involves intentional deviations from SAA to exploit perceived short-term mispricings, adding active risk (tracking error) relative to the strategic benchmark.', 1),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation-q03', 'cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation', 'The minimum-variance portfolio on the efficient frontier is characterized by:', 'The highest expected return for any given risk level', 'Equal weighting across all asset classes to maximize diversification', 'The lowest possible portfolio standard deviation across all investable combinations', 'A portfolio consisting entirely of the risk-free asset', 'C', 'The minimum-variance portfolio is the leftmost point on the efficient frontier, representing the combination of risky assets with the lowest achievable standard deviation.', 2),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation-q04', 'cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation', 'A key advantage of the Black-Litterman model over standard mean-variance optimization (MVO) is that it:', 'Requires no input assumptions about expected returns or correlations', 'Guarantees the highest possible Sharpe ratio for any set of investor views', 'Starts from market equilibrium returns and blends in investor views, producing more diversified portfolios', 'Eliminates the need for rebalancing by automatically adjusting to market changes', 'C', 'Black-Litterman combines implied equilibrium returns (from market cap weights) with investor views, addressing MVO''s tendency to produce concentrated, input-sensitive portfolios.', 3),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation-q05', 'cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation', 'Calendar rebalancing differs from threshold (corridor) rebalancing in that calendar rebalancing:', 'Maintains tighter risk control because it responds immediately to significant price moves', 'Always results in lower trading costs than threshold rebalancing', 'Rebalances the portfolio on a fixed schedule regardless of how much weights have drifted', 'Is only appropriate for equity-only portfolios with no fixed income', 'C', 'Calendar rebalancing occurs at fixed intervals (monthly, quarterly) regardless of drift, while threshold rebalancing triggers only when weights deviate beyond a specified band from targets.', 4),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation-q06', 'cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation', 'Mean-variance optimization is most criticized for which of the following limitations?', 'It is highly sensitive to input assumptions and often produces concentrated portfolios', 'It requires real-time pricing, which is unavailable for most asset classes', 'It cannot model more than two asset classes simultaneously', 'It ignores the investor''s return objective and risk tolerance', 'A', 'Small changes in expected return assumptions can dramatically shift MVO weights, often yielding concentrated, unstable portfolios that are fragile to estimation errors.', 5),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation-q07', 'cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation', 'When an equity allocation grows from its 60% SAA target to 68% due to strong stock market performance, a portfolio manager practicing threshold rebalancing with a 5% corridor would:', 'Take no action, because only calendar rebalancing monitors weight drift', 'Widen the corridor to accommodate the higher equity weight', 'Wait until the next scheduled calendar date to rebalance', 'Immediately rebalance back to 60% because the weight has exceeded the 65% upper boundary', 'D', 'A 5% corridor around 60% sets upper and lower bounds of 65% and 55%. At 68%, the upper bound is breached, triggering a rebalance back to the 60% target.', 6),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation-q08', 'cfa-portfolio-management-asset-allocation', 'Research on asset allocation suggests that strategic asset allocation explains the majority of long-run portfolio return variability primarily because:', 'Individual security selection adds no value in efficient markets', 'Broad asset class exposures drive most of the variation in portfolio returns over time', 'Tactical allocation always destroys value and should be avoided entirely', 'Rebalancing automatically captures alpha from mean-reverting asset prices', 'B', 'The Brinson, Hood, and Beebower research showed that the policy mix across asset classes (SAA) explains the preponderance of the variability in total portfolio returns over time.', 7),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation-q01', 'cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation', 'The Sharpe ratio is most appropriate for evaluating performance when:', 'The portfolio represents only one component within a larger diversified fund', 'The portfolio is an investor''s entire investment portfolio', 'The benchmark has a different standard deviation than the portfolio', 'The portfolio holds only fixed income securities with low variance', 'B', 'The Sharpe ratio uses total risk (standard deviation) and is appropriate when the portfolio is the investor''s entire holding. For a sub-portfolio within a diversified fund, the Treynor ratio is preferred.', 0),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation-q02', 'cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation', 'A portfolio earns a return of 12%, the risk-free rate is 3%, and the portfolio beta is 1.2. The market return is 9%. What is Jensen''s alpha?', '1.8%', '3.0%', '0.6%', '2.4%', 'A', 'Jensen''s alpha = Rp - [Rf + beta(Rm - Rf)] = 12% - [3% + 1.2*(9% - 3%)] = 12% - [3% + 7.2%] = 12% - 10.2% = 1.8%.', 1),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation-q03', 'cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation', 'The Information Ratio (IR) measures:', 'The excess return over the benchmark per unit of tracking error', 'The excess return of the portfolio over the risk-free rate per unit of total risk', 'The portfolio''s alpha per unit of systematic risk (beta)', 'The ratio of positive return months to negative return months', 'A', 'IR = Active return / Tracking error = (Rp - Rb) / TE. A higher IR indicates the manager is generating more consistent active return per unit of active risk taken.', 2),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation-q04', 'cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation', 'In the Brinson, Hood, and Beebower (BHB) performance attribution model, the allocation effect measures:', 'Whether the manager selected better securities than the benchmark within each asset class', 'Whether the manager overweighted or underweighted asset classes that outperformed or underperformed', 'The combined impact of allocation and selection decisions in each segment', 'The total active return relative to the strategic benchmark', 'B', 'The allocation effect captures value added by over/underweighting asset classes: it is positive when the manager overweights (underweights) sectors that outperform (underperform) the overall benchmark.', 3),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation-q05', 'cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation', 'The Treynor ratio is preferred over the Sharpe ratio for evaluating a sub-portfolio within a larger diversified fund because:', 'Beta is more accurate than standard deviation for measuring total portfolio risk', 'The Treynor ratio does not require knowledge of the risk-free rate', 'When the portfolio is one of many holdings, idiosyncratic risk is diversified away, making systematic risk the relevant measure', 'The Sharpe ratio cannot be calculated for sub-portfolios with negative returns', 'C', 'In a diversified fund, unsystematic risk is eliminated at the total portfolio level; only systematic risk (beta) is relevant for evaluating a component, making the Treynor ratio appropriate.', 4),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation-q06', 'cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation', 'M-squared (M2) is calculated by:', 'Multiplying the portfolio''s Sharpe ratio by the benchmark standard deviation plus the risk-free rate', 'Subtracting Jensen''s alpha from the Treynor ratio', 'Dividing the portfolio''s excess return by beta minus the benchmark excess return', 'Adding the information ratio to the Sharpe ratio', 'A', 'M2 = (Sharpe_p - Sharpe_m) * sigma_m + Rf, or equivalently, it levers/de-levers the portfolio to the benchmark''s risk level and compares returns. It expresses risk-adjusted outperformance in return percentage terms.', 5),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation-q07', 'cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation', 'Which of the following is NOT a required characteristic of a valid benchmark?', 'Higher historical return than the portfolio', 'Specified in advance', 'Investable', 'Unambiguous and measurable', 'A', 'A valid benchmark does not need to outperform the portfolio; it must be investable, specified in advance, measurable, appropriate, reflective of investment opinion, accountable, and unambiguous.', 6),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation-q08', 'cfa-portfolio-management-performance-evaluation', 'A portfolio manager consistently generates positive Jensen''s alpha over a 5-year period. This most likely indicates:', 'The portfolio took on more total risk than the market portfolio', 'The portfolio''s Sharpe ratio exceeded the market Sharpe ratio', 'The manager earned returns exceeding what the CAPM predicts given the portfolio''s systematic risk', 'The portfolio is fully diversified with no idiosyncratic risk', 'C', 'Jensen''s alpha measures excess return above the CAPM-predicted return for the portfolio''s beta level. Positive alpha over multiple periods suggests manager skill or persistent factor exposures not captured by beta.', 7),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management-q01', 'cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management', 'Risk budgeting in portfolio management refers to:', 'Setting a maximum loss limit for each calendar year', 'Limiting each position to a fixed percentage of the total portfolio', 'Determining the budget required to hedge all portfolio risks using derivatives', 'Allocating a total risk budget across positions or asset classes to maximize return per unit of risk', 'D', 'Risk budgeting allocates a total risk allowance (expressed as volatility, VaR, or tracking error) across portfolio components, ensuring managers seek the highest return per unit of risk consumed.', 0),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management-q02', 'cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management', 'A portfolio has a daily 99% VaR of $2 million. This means:', 'The portfolio will lose exactly $2 million on 99% of trading days', 'The portfolio''s maximum possible loss is $2 million', 'Losses exceeding $2 million are expected on approximately 1% of trading days', 'The portfolio will lose at least $2 million on 1% of days with 99% confidence', 'C', 'A 99% VaR of $2 million means that on approximately 1% of trading days (about 2-3 days per year), losses are expected to exceed $2 million. VaR does not cap the loss magnitude.', 1),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management-q03', 'cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management', 'Conditional VaR (CVaR), also called Expected Shortfall, improves on VaR by:', 'Assuming a normal distribution, which reduces computation complexity', 'Eliminating the need to specify a confidence level', 'Measuring the average loss in the tail beyond the VaR threshold', 'Providing a guaranteed maximum loss figure for risk budgeting purposes', 'C', 'CVaR is the expected loss conditional on the loss exceeding the VaR level. It describes the severity of tail losses that VaR does not capture, addressing VaR''s key limitation.', 2),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management-q04', 'cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management', 'Which VaR estimation method requires no assumption about the shape of the return distribution?', 'Parametric (variance-covariance) method', 'Monte Carlo simulation', 'Analytical approximation using modified duration', 'Historical simulation', 'D', 'Historical simulation uses the actual distribution of past returns directly, making no normality assumption. It naturally captures fat tails and skewness present in actual market data.', 3),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management-q05', 'cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management', 'Maximum drawdown is best defined as:', 'The standard deviation of monthly portfolio returns over a given period', 'The VaR of the portfolio measured at the 95% confidence level', 'The average loss during months when the portfolio produces negative returns', 'The largest peak-to-trough decline in portfolio value over a specified period', 'D', 'Maximum drawdown measures the largest cumulative loss from a prior peak to a subsequent trough, capturing the worst sustained loss an investor could have experienced.', 4),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management-q06', 'cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management', 'A factor-based risk model decomposes portfolio risk into:', 'VaR contributions from each individual position', 'Market risk and credit risk components only', 'Systematic factor exposures and idiosyncratic (security-specific) risk', 'Historical and forward-looking risk components', 'C', 'Factor models explain portfolio returns and risk through exposures to systematic factors (market, size, value, momentum) plus residual idiosyncratic risk unique to individual securities.', 5),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management-q07', 'cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management', 'The parametric VaR method is least reliable for portfolios that:', 'Hold only investment-grade bonds with no embedded options', 'Are well-diversified across many asset classes with symmetric returns', 'Have a long track record of returns available for analysis', 'Contain options or other instruments with non-linear payoffs and fat-tailed return distributions', 'D', 'Parametric VaR assumes normally distributed, linear returns. Options introduce non-linearity and actual returns often have fat tails, making the parametric method unreliable for such portfolios.', 6),
  ('cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management-q08', 'cfa-portfolio-management-risk-management', 'An investment mandate specifies a maximum drawdown limit of 15%. Once this limit is breached, the most likely required action is:', 'Increase leverage to recover the loss more quickly', 'Report the breach only at the end of the fiscal year', 'Switch the entire portfolio to cash until the drawdown limit is reset', 'Reduce risk exposures to prevent further losses and notify stakeholders', 'D', 'A drawdown limit breach triggers risk reduction measures to prevent compounding losses and requires prompt disclosure to stakeholders; the appropriate response is de-risking, not increasing leverage.', 7),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-management-capm-q01', 'frm-foundations-risk-management-capm', 'Under the CAPM, which type of risk earns a return premium?', 'Idiosyncratic risk', 'Systematic (market) risk', 'Diversifiable risk', 'Firm-specific risk', 'B', 'Only non-diversifiable systematic risk, measured by beta, is rewarded; idiosyncratic risk can be diversified away.', 0),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-management-capm-q02', 'frm-foundations-risk-management-capm', 'In the CAPM equation, beta measures an asset''s:', 'Total return volatility', 'Sensitivity to overall market movements', 'Dividend yield', 'Default probability', 'B', 'Beta is the asset''s sensitivity to the market; it scales the market risk premium in CAPM.', 1),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-management-capm-q03', 'frm-foundations-risk-management-capm', 'The Sharpe ratio divides excess return by:', 'Beta', 'Market return', 'Total risk (standard deviation)', 'Tracking error', 'C', 'The Sharpe ratio uses total risk in the denominator, whereas the Treynor ratio uses beta.', 2),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-management-capm-q04', 'frm-foundations-risk-management-capm', 'Jensen''s alpha represents the portfolio return:', 'Equal to the risk-free rate', 'Below the benchmark', 'In excess of the CAPM prediction', 'Equal to the market return', 'C', 'Alpha is the return earned above what CAPM predicts, often used as a measure of manager skill.', 3),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-management-capm-q05', 'frm-foundations-risk-management-capm', 'An asset with a beta of 1.0 is expected to:', 'Outperform the market in every period', 'Have zero risk', 'Move with the overall market', 'Earn only the risk-free rate', 'C', 'A beta of 1.0 means the asset moves in line with the market on average.', 4),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-management-capm-q06', 'frm-foundations-risk-management-capm', 'Which risk can be reduced by holding a well-diversified portfolio?', 'Idiosyncratic risk', 'Systematic risk', 'Market risk', 'Undiversifiable risk', 'A', 'Idiosyncratic, firm-specific risk is diversifiable; systematic market risk remains regardless of diversification.', 5),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-management-capm-q07', 'frm-foundations-risk-management-capm', 'The market risk premium in the CAPM is defined as:', 'The risk-free rate alone', 'The expected market return minus the risk-free rate', 'Beta times the risk-free rate', 'The total volatility of the market', 'B', 'The market risk premium is the expected market return less the risk-free rate.', 6),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-management-capm-q08', 'frm-foundations-risk-management-capm', 'Credit risk is best described as the risk of loss from:', 'Movements in interest rates', 'Failed internal processes', 'An inability to sell at fair value', 'A counterparty failing to meet its obligations', 'D', 'Credit risk is the loss arising when a borrower or counterparty fails to pay as promised.', 7),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch-q01', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch', 'In the EWMA model, a higher decay factor lambda produces a volatility series that is:', 'More jagged and faster to react', 'Smoother and slower to react', 'Always constant', 'Equal to the long-run variance', 'B', 'A higher lambda gives recent returns relatively less extra weight, producing a smoother, slower-reacting estimate.', 0),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch-q02', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch', 'The RiskMetrics daily EWMA model uses a lambda of approximately:', '0.50', '0.72', '0.94', '1.20', 'C', 'RiskMetrics adopts lambda equal to 0.94 for daily volatility estimation.', 1),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch-q03', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch', 'In a GARCH(1,1) model, persistence is measured by:', 'omega only', 'omega divided by alpha', 'alpha minus beta', 'alpha plus beta', 'D', 'Persistence equals alpha plus beta; it must be below 1 for the model to be mean-reverting.', 2),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch-q04', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch', 'The long-run variance implied by a GARCH(1,1) model equals:', 'omega divided by (1 minus alpha minus beta)', 'omega times alpha', 'alpha divided by beta', 'alpha plus beta', 'A', 'The unconditional long-run variance is omega divided by (1 minus alpha minus beta).', 3),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch-q05', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch', 'EWMA is a special case of GARCH(1,1) in which:', 'omega is zero and alpha plus beta equals 1', 'alpha equals beta equals zero', 'omega equals 1', 'beta is greater than 1', 'A', 'Setting omega to zero and alpha plus beta to 1 reduces GARCH(1,1) to the EWMA recursion.', 4),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch-q06', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch', 'The tendency of large return moves to be followed by large moves is called:', 'Volatility clustering', 'Mean reversion', 'Heteroskedastic decay', 'Ghosting', 'A', 'Volatility clustering describes periods of high volatility persisting, a key motivation for EWMA and GARCH.', 5),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch-q07', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch', 'A drawback of the equally weighted variance estimate is the ghosting effect, which occurs when:', 'Recent returns are overweighted', 'Volatility reverts to its mean too quickly', 'The variance can never change', 'A large past return abruptly drops out of the window', 'D', 'Ghosting is the sudden jump in the estimate when a large observation leaves the equally weighted window.', 6),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch-q08', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-volatility-ewma-garch', 'Compared with EWMA, the GARCH(1,1) model additionally incorporates:', 'No weighting of past returns', 'Only the most recent squared return', 'A fixed lambda of 0.94', 'A long-run variance term that drives mean reversion', 'D', 'GARCH(1,1) adds the omega term tied to long-run variance, giving it mean reversion that EWMA lacks.', 7),
  ('frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging-q01', 'frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging', 'Which feature distinguishes futures from forward contracts?', 'Futures are customized over-the-counter deals', 'Futures are exchange-traded and marked-to-market daily', 'Futures carry more counterparty credit risk', 'Futures settle only at maturity', 'B', 'Futures are standardized, exchange-traded, and marked-to-market daily through a clearinghouse, unlike forwards.', 0),
  ('frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging-q02', 'frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging', 'For a non-dividend asset, the cost-of-carry forward price is:', 'S_0 minus r times T', 'S_0 divided by r', 'S_0 times e raised to (r times T)', 'S_0 times r times T', 'C', 'Under cost of carry with no income, the forward price equals spot compounded at the risk-free rate over T.', 1),
  ('frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging-q03', 'frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging', 'The minimum-variance hedge ratio is equal to:', 'The ratio of spot price to futures price', 'One minus the correlation', 'Futures volatility divided by spot volatility', 'Correlation times the ratio of spot volatility to futures volatility', 'D', 'The optimal hedge ratio is the correlation multiplied by the ratio of spot to futures return volatility.', 2),
  ('frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging-q04', 'frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging', 'A market is in backwardation when the futures price is:', 'Below the spot price', 'Above the spot price', 'Zero', 'Equal to the spot price', 'A', 'Backwardation describes a futures price below the spot price; contango is the opposite case.', 3),
  ('frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging-q05', 'frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging', 'Basis is defined as:', 'Futures price times the hedge ratio', 'Spot price minus futures price', 'The risk-free rate', 'The sum of spot and futures prices', 'B', 'Basis equals the spot price minus the futures price and converges to zero as delivery approaches.', 4),
  ('frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging-q06', 'frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging', 'An investor who already owns an asset and fears a price decline should use a:', 'Short hedge', 'Long hedge', 'Naked call', 'Cash-and-carry arbitrage', 'A', 'A short hedge (selling futures) protects the value of an asset already held against falling prices.', 5),
  ('frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging-q07', 'frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging', 'Basis risk in a hedge arises mainly when:', 'The hedge perfectly matches the exposure', 'The hedging instrument or maturity does not match the underlying', 'The contract is exchange-cleared', 'Futures are marked-to-market daily', 'B', 'Basis risk results from mismatches in asset, maturity, or quantity between the position and the hedging contract.', 6),
  ('frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging-q08', 'frm-financial-markets-futures-forwards-hedging', 'Compared with a forward, an exchange-traded future largely removes counterparty credit risk because of:', 'Daily news disclosure', 'The absence of margin', 'Customized contract terms', 'The clearinghouse acting as central counterparty', 'D', 'The clearinghouse interposes itself as central counterparty and collects margin, sharply reducing credit risk.', 7),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk-q01', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk', 'A one-day 99% VaR of 2 million means there is a:', '99% chance of losing exactly 2 million', 'Certainty of losing 2 million', '1% chance of losing more than 2 million in a day', '1% chance of gaining 2 million', 'C', 'A 99% one-day VaR of 2 million implies a 1% probability that the daily loss exceeds 2 million.', 0),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk-q02', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk', 'In the delta-normal VaR formula, the z-value used for 99% confidence is approximately:', '1.28', '1.65', '1.96', '2.33', 'D', 'The one-tailed standard-normal quantile for 99% confidence is about 2.33.', 1),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk-q03', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk', 'To scale a one-day VaR to a 10-day horizon under the square-root-of-time rule, you multiply by:', '10', 'The square root of 10', '100', '1', 'B', 'VaR scales with the square root of time, so the 10-day VaR is the one-day VaR times the square root of 10.', 2),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk-q04', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk', 'Expected Shortfall (Conditional VaR) measures the:', 'Most likely daily gain', 'Loss at exactly the VaR level only', 'Probability of any loss', 'Average loss in the tail beyond the VaR threshold', 'D', 'Expected Shortfall is the average of losses that exceed the VaR cutoff, capturing tail severity.', 3),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk-q05', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk', 'Portfolio VaR is generally less than the sum of component VaRs because of:', 'Diversification from imperfect correlation', 'Higher volatility', 'Leverage', 'Margin requirements', 'A', 'Imperfect correlation among assets produces a diversification benefit, lowering portfolio VaR below the sum of parts.', 4),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk-q06', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk', 'Which property of VaR makes Expected Shortfall preferred by regulators?', 'VaR always overstates risk', 'VaR ignores the confidence level', 'VaR cannot be computed parametrically', 'VaR can fail subadditivity for non-normal portfolios', 'D', 'VaR can violate subadditivity, so it is not always coherent; Expected Shortfall is coherent and captures the tail.', 5),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk-q07', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk', 'In the delta-normal approach, VaR is computed as z times sigma times the square root of t times:', 'The risk-free rate', 'The portfolio value', 'Beta', 'The correlation', 'B', 'Parametric VaR equals z times volatility times the square root of the horizon times the portfolio value.', 6),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk-q08', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-value-at-risk', 'Lowering the confidence level of a VaR estimate from 99% to 95% will, all else equal:', 'Increase the reported VaR', 'Decrease the reported VaR', 'Leave VaR unchanged', 'Make VaR negative', 'B', 'A lower confidence level uses a smaller z-value, producing a smaller VaR figure.', 7),
  ('frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting-q01', 'frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting', 'Which VaR method reuses actual historical returns without assuming a distribution?', 'Parametric (delta-normal)', 'Historical simulation', 'Monte Carlo simulation', 'Cornish-Fisher expansion', 'B', 'Historical simulation ranks observed past profit-and-loss and reads the percentile, making no distributional assumption.', 0),
  ('frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting-q02', 'frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting', 'Which VaR approach is best suited to nonlinear portfolios but is the most computationally intensive?', 'Parametric VaR', 'Historical simulation', 'Monte Carlo simulation', 'Delta-normal VaR', 'C', 'Monte Carlo simulation can capture nonlinear payoffs by simulating many paths, but it is the slowest method.', 1),
  ('frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting-q03', 'frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting', 'Over 250 trading days at 99% one-day VaR, the expected number of exceptions is about:', '0', '2.5', '25', '50', 'B', 'At 99% confidence, roughly 1% of 250 days, about 2.5 days, are expected to be exceptions.', 2),
  ('frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting-q04', 'frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting', 'In the Basel traffic-light backtest, 10 or more exceptions in 250 days places a model in the:', 'Red zone', 'Yellow zone', 'Blue zone', 'Green zone', 'A', 'Ten or more exceptions fall in the red zone, indicating the model is rejected as understating risk.', 3),
  ('frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting-q05', 'frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting', 'A backtest that finds far more exceptions than expected suggests the VaR model:', 'Uses too high a confidence level', 'Overstates the true risk', 'Is perfectly calibrated', 'Understates the true risk', 'D', 'Too many exceptions mean losses breach VaR more often than they should, so the model understates risk.', 4),
  ('frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting-q06', 'frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting', 'A conditional coverage backtest additionally checks that exceptions are:', 'Always clustered together', 'Greater than 10 per year', 'Independent and not clustered in time', 'Equal to the confidence level', 'C', 'Conditional coverage tests both the correct exception rate and that exceptions occur independently over time.', 5),
  ('frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting-q07', 'frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting', 'A key weakness of the parametric VaR method is that it:', 'Requires storing all past returns', 'Cannot scale across time horizons', 'Tends to understate fat-tailed losses', 'Is the slowest to compute', 'C', 'Assuming normality, parametric VaR underestimates losses when actual returns have fat tails.', 6),
  ('frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting-q08', 'frm-market-risk-var-methods-backtesting', 'The expected number of backtesting exceptions equals:', 'The confidence level times the number of days', 'The number of days divided by the z-value', 'One minus the confidence level, times the number of days', 'The VaR amount times volatility', 'C', 'Expected exceptions equal (1 minus confidence) multiplied by the number of observation days.', 7),
  ('frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var-q01', 'frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var', 'Expected Loss on a credit exposure is the product of:', 'PD, LGD and EAD', 'PD and the risk-free rate', 'LGD and volatility', 'EAD and beta', 'A', 'Expected Loss equals probability of default times loss given default times exposure at default.', 0),
  ('frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var-q02', 'frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var', 'Loss given default (LGD) is equal to:', 'The probability of default', 'Exposure at default times beta', 'One minus the recovery rate', 'The credit spread', 'C', 'LGD is the fraction of exposure lost in default, equal to one minus the recovery rate.', 1),
  ('frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var-q03', 'frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var', 'Economic capital for credit risk is sized to cover:', 'Expected loss only', 'The risk-free return', 'Operating expenses', 'Unexpected loss', 'D', 'Expected loss is provisioned in pricing; economic capital is held against unexpected loss volatility.', 2),
  ('frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var-q04', 'frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var', 'In the Merton model, a firm defaults when:', 'Its equity rises above its debt', 'The value of its assets falls below its debt', 'Its recovery rate hits 100%', 'Its credit spread reaches zero', 'B', 'The Merton model treats equity as a call option and defaults when asset value drops below the debt face value.', 3),
  ('frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var-q05', 'frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var', 'Credit VaR is most accurately described as:', 'The worst-case loss at a confidence level minus the expected loss', 'The expected loss plus the risk-free rate', 'The probability of default alone', 'The total exposure at default', 'A', 'Credit VaR is the unexpected loss: the worst-case loss at a confidence level less the expected loss.', 4),
  ('frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var-q06', 'frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var', 'All else equal, a higher default correlation across a loan portfolio:', 'Raises portfolio Credit VaR', 'Lowers portfolio Credit VaR', 'Eliminates unexpected loss', 'Has no effect on the loss distribution', 'A', 'Higher default correlation fattens the loss tail, increasing portfolio Credit VaR.', 5),
  ('frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var-q07', 'frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var', 'A bond''s credit spread over the risk-free rate approximately compensates for:', 'Expected credit loss (PD times LGD)', 'Liquidity gains', 'Inflation only', 'Currency movements', 'A', 'Credit spread broadly compensates investors for expected credit loss, roughly PD times LGD over the horizon.', 6),
  ('frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var-q08', 'frm-credit-risk-default-probability-credit-var', 'Exposure at default (EAD) represents:', 'The recovery rate on collateral', 'The amount outstanding and at risk when default occurs', 'The probability the borrower defaults', 'The fraction lost in default', 'B', 'EAD is the expected outstanding exposure subject to loss at the moment of default.', 7),
  ('frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc-q01', 'frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc', 'Operational risk is the risk of loss arising from:', 'Movements in market prices', 'Changes in interest rates', 'A counterparty defaulting on a loan', 'Failed internal processes, people, systems or external events', 'D', 'Operational risk covers losses from inadequate or failed processes, people, systems, or external events.', 0),
  ('frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc-q02', 'frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc', 'Which Basel Accord first introduced an explicit capital charge for operational risk?', 'Basel I', 'Basel III', 'Basel II', 'Basel IV', 'C', 'Basel II added operational risk capital alongside its three-pillar framework.', 1),
  ('frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc-q03', 'frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc', 'In the RAROC formula, the numerator subtracts which item from net revenue?', 'Economic capital', 'The hurdle rate', 'The risk-free rate', 'Expected loss', 'D', 'RAROC''s numerator nets revenue and costs and subtracts expected loss, then divides by economic capital.', 2),
  ('frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc-q04', 'frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc', 'A business line creates value when its RAROC is:', 'Equal to zero', 'Negative', 'Below the risk-free rate', 'Above the firm''s hurdle rate', 'D', 'A project adds value only when RAROC exceeds the hurdle rate (the cost of equity capital).', 3),
  ('frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc-q05', 'frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc', 'Under Basel II, Pillar 1 specifically addresses:', 'Market discipline and disclosure', 'Supervisory review', 'Minimum capital requirements', 'Liquidity coverage', 'C', 'Pillar 1 sets minimum regulatory capital; Pillar 2 is supervisory review and Pillar 3 is market discipline.', 4),
  ('frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc-q06', 'frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc', 'RAROC is primarily used by banks to:', 'Forecast interest rates', 'Measure inflation', 'Allocate capital and set risk-based pricing', 'Determine recovery rates', 'C', 'RAROC guides capital allocation, risk-based pricing, and like-for-like performance comparison across units.', 5),
  ('frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc-q07', 'frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc', 'Adjusted RAROC refines the basic measure by:', 'Subtracting the risk-free rate before comparison', 'Ignoring economic capital', 'Adding back expected loss', 'Multiplying by beta', 'A', 'Adjusted RAROC subtracts the risk-free rate so the result can be compared directly to the equity risk premium.', 6),
  ('frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc-q08', 'frm-operational-risk-basel-accords-raroc', 'Basel II maps operational loss data across business lines and:', 'Interest rate buckets', 'Loss event types', 'Currency pairs', 'Credit ratings', 'B', 'Operational loss data is classified by business line and by event type to drive capital estimation.', 7),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management-q01', 'frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management', 'Funding liquidity risk refers to the inability to:', 'Sell an asset near its fair value', 'Diversify a portfolio', 'Hedge interest rate exposure', 'Raise cash to meet cash-flow obligations', 'D', 'Funding liquidity risk is the risk of being unable to raise cash to meet obligations as they fall due.', 0),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management-q02', 'frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management', 'Market (trading) liquidity risk is the risk of:', 'A counterparty defaulting', 'Rising interest rates', 'An operational system failure', 'Being unable to sell an asset near its fair value', 'D', 'Market liquidity risk is the inability to transact an asset close to its fair value without moving the price.', 1),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management-q03', 'frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management', 'Liquidity-adjusted VaR (LVaR) adds a cost term based primarily on the:', 'Bid-ask spread', 'Risk-free rate', 'Beta of the asset', 'Dividend yield', 'A', 'LVaR augments standard VaR with a liquidation-cost term driven by the bid-ask spread.', 2),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management-q04', 'frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management', 'The Basel III Liquidity Coverage Ratio (LCR) is designed to ensure a bank can survive a stress period of:', '1 year', '90 days', '7 days', '30 days', 'D', 'The LCR requires enough high-quality liquid assets to cover net cash outflows over a 30-day stress horizon.', 3),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management-q05', 'frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management', 'The Net Stable Funding Ratio (NSFR) targets stable funding over a horizon of:', 'One year', '30 days', 'Ten days', 'One quarter', 'A', 'The NSFR promotes resilience by requiring stable funding to support assets over a one-year horizon.', 4),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management-q06', 'frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management', 'In the LCR, the numerator consists of:', 'Net cash outflows', 'Risk-weighted assets', 'Tier 1 capital', 'High-quality liquid assets (HQLA)', 'D', 'The LCR divides high-quality liquid assets by net cash outflows over 30 days, requiring at least 100%.', 5),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management-q07', 'frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management', 'Holding a buffer of high-quality liquid assets and diversifying funding sources is a way to:', 'Increase leverage', 'Raise credit correlation', 'Manage liquidity risk', 'Reduce diversification', 'C', 'A liquidity buffer and diversified, laddered funding reduce the chance of a cash-flow shortfall.', 6),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management-q08', 'frm-liquidity-risk-liquidity-risk-management', 'A liquidity spiral describes a crisis in which:', 'Spreads always narrow', 'Funding and market liquidity reinforce each other downward', 'VaR estimates fall to zero', 'Recovery rates rise sharply', 'B', 'In a liquidity spiral, falling funding and market liquidity feed on each other, deepening the stress.', 7),
  ('frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting-q01', 'frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting', 'In a two-asset portfolio, lowering the correlation between the assets will:', 'Reduce portfolio variance', 'Increase portfolio variance', 'Leave variance unchanged', 'Eliminate all risk', 'A', 'Lower correlation reduces the covariance term, decreasing portfolio variance through diversification.', 0),
  ('frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting-q02', 'frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting', 'Component VaR has the useful property that the components:', 'Are independent of position size', 'Always equal each other', 'Sum to the total portfolio VaR', 'Sum to zero', 'C', 'Component VaRs are constructed so that they add up exactly to the total portfolio VaR.', 1),
  ('frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting-q03', 'frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting', 'Marginal VaR measures the change in portfolio VaR from:', 'Removing the entire position', 'Doubling the portfolio', 'A small increase in a position', 'Changing the confidence level', 'C', 'Marginal VaR is the sensitivity of portfolio VaR to a small change in a given position.', 2),
  ('frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting-q04', 'frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting', 'Tracking error is defined as the volatility of:', 'The benchmark return', 'Active (portfolio minus benchmark) returns', 'Total portfolio return', 'The risk-free rate', 'B', 'Tracking error is the standard deviation of the difference between portfolio and benchmark returns.', 3),
  ('frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting-q05', 'frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting', 'The information ratio is computed as active return divided by:', 'The risk-free rate', 'Beta', 'Tracking error', 'Total volatility', 'C', 'The information ratio divides active return (over the benchmark) by the tracking error.', 4),
  ('frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting-q06', 'frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting', 'A risk-parity portfolio is constructed so that each asset contributes:', 'An equal amount of capital', 'An equal amount of expected return', 'Zero risk', 'An equal amount of risk', 'D', 'Risk parity equalizes each asset''s risk contribution rather than its capital weight.', 5),
  ('frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting-q07', 'frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting', 'Which measure captures the VaR change from adding an entirely new position to a portfolio?', 'Component VaR', 'Marginal VaR', 'Incremental VaR', 'Diversified VaR', 'C', 'Incremental VaR is the change in total VaR resulting from adding a complete new position.', 6),
  ('frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting-q08', 'frm-investment-risk-portfolio-risk-budgeting', 'In the two-asset portfolio variance formula, the cross term includes:', 'Twice the product of weights, volatilities and correlation', 'Only the weights', 'The risk-free rate', 'The sum of the variances only', 'A', 'The covariance term equals two times the product of the two weights, their volatilities, and the correlation.', 7),
  ('frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks-q01', 'frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks', 'Basel III strengthened capital quality by emphasizing which core component?', 'Subordinated debt', 'Common Equity Tier 1 (CET1)', 'Goodwill', 'Deferred tax assets', 'B', 'Basel III centers capital quality on Common Equity Tier 1, the most loss-absorbing form of capital.', 0),
  ('frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks-q02', 'frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks', 'The Basel III leverage ratio is a backstop because it is:', 'A non-risk-based measure of capital to total exposure', 'Risk-weighted by counterparty', 'Based only on credit ratings', 'Calculated solely from market risk', 'A', 'The leverage ratio compares Tier 1 capital to total exposure without risk weighting, acting as a backstop.', 1),
  ('frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks-q03', 'frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks', 'The Basel III/IV output floor limits internal-model capital relief to a percentage of the standardized approach of:', '50%', '90%', '72.5%', '100%', 'C', 'The output floor caps capital benefits from internal models at 72.5% of the standardized approach.', 2),
  ('frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks-q04', 'frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks', 'Under FRTB, the regulatory market-risk measure shifts from VaR to:', 'Expected Shortfall', 'Beta', 'Duration', 'Standard deviation', 'A', 'The Fundamental Review of the Trading Book replaces VaR with Expected Shortfall for regulatory market risk.', 3),
  ('frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks-q05', 'frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks', 'Climate risk is commonly divided into physical risk and:', 'Rollover risk', 'Settlement risk', 'Basis risk', 'Transition risk', 'D', 'Climate risk splits into physical risk (hazard damage) and transition risk (shifting to a low-carbon economy).', 4),
  ('frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks-q06', 'frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks', 'The capital conservation buffer introduced by Basel III is intended to:', 'Replace minimum capital entirely', 'Build a usable cushion above the minimum during good times', 'Lower required capital in downturns to zero', 'Increase leverage', 'B', 'The conservation buffer accumulates capital above the minimum that can be drawn down under stress.', 5),
  ('frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks-q07', 'frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks', 'Under FRTB, the Expected Shortfall measure is calibrated at a confidence level of:', '90%', '97.5%', '95%', '99.9%', 'B', 'FRTB sets the Expected Shortfall confidence level at 97.5% for regulatory market-risk capital.', 6),
  ('frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks-q08', 'frm-current-issues-basel-iii-iv-emerging-risks', 'Growing reliance on increasingly complex models has heightened the importance of managing:', 'Model risk and validation', 'Currency risk', 'Dividend risk', 'Settlement risk', 'A', 'Complex and AI-driven models raise model risk, demanding stronger validation and governance.', 7),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy-q01', 'frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy', 'A bank cannot exit a large equity position without moving the market price significantly against itself. This is best described as:', 'Funding liquidity risk', 'Credit spread risk', 'Operational risk', 'Market liquidity risk', 'D', 'Market liquidity risk is the inability to transact at or near the current market price due to insufficient market depth. Funding liquidity risk relates to meeting cash obligations, not position exit constraints.', 0),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy-q02', 'frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy', 'Which risk category encompasses losses arising from failed internal processes, people, systems, or external events?', 'Operational risk', 'Credit risk', 'Strategic risk', 'Market risk', 'A', 'Operational risk is explicitly defined in Basel III as losses from failed internal processes, people, systems, or external events. This is distinct from financial risks such as market or credit risk.', 1),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy-q03', 'frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy', 'A sovereign debt downgrade causes an investment-grade bond to fall to sub-investment-grade status, resulting in forced selling and losses for a fund. Which risk type is most directly illustrated?', 'Default risk', 'Reputational risk', 'Market liquidity risk', 'Migration risk', 'D', 'Migration risk is the loss from deterioration in credit quality (credit rating migration) rather than outright default. The downgrade itself, independent of default, creates the loss.', 2),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy-q04', 'frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy', 'Under Basel III, which of the following risk categories explicitly requires regulatory capital allocation?', 'Reputational risk', 'Strategic risk', 'Operational risk', 'Legal risk', 'C', 'Basel III''s Pillar 1 requires explicit capital charges for market, credit, and operational risk. Reputational and strategic risk are Pillar 2 considerations assessed under the ICAAP rather than through standardised capital formulae.', 3),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy-q05', 'frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy', 'An enterprise risk taxonomy is primarily designed to ensure which of the following?', 'That individual business units manage risk independently without central oversight', 'Consistent identification and classification of all material risks across the firm', 'Elimination of all credit and market risks from the balance sheet', 'Compliance with a single international regulatory standard', 'B', 'A risk taxonomy provides a common language and classification framework that enables consistent identification, measurement, and reporting of risks across all business lines and functions.', 4),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy-q06', 'frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy', 'A bank''s decision to exit a profitable business line due to persistent adverse media coverage is driven primarily by which risk?', 'Reputational risk', 'Operational risk', 'Credit risk', 'Funding liquidity risk', 'A', 'Reputational risk reflects the threat of damage to a firm''s standing in the eyes of customers, counterparties, and the public — the adverse media coverage and resulting business exit is a classic reputational risk manifestation.', 5),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy-q07', 'frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy', 'Which metric pair is most closely associated with measuring credit risk exposure?', 'VaR and Expected Shortfall', 'Duration and convexity', 'Liquidity Coverage Ratio and Net Stable Funding Ratio', 'Probability of Default and Loss Given Default', 'D', 'Probability of Default (PD) and Loss Given Default (LGD) are the fundamental building blocks of credit risk measurement, used together with Exposure at Default (EAD) to calculate Expected Loss.', 6),
  ('frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy-q08', 'frm-foundations-risk-types-taxonomy', 'When a credit event at one institution triggers a funding crisis at another due to interbank exposures, which risk interaction is most prominently illustrated?', 'Legal risk creating market risk', 'Market risk amplifying operational risk', 'Strategic risk converting to reputational risk', 'Credit risk triggering liquidity risk', 'D', 'The 2008 financial crisis demonstrated how credit events (counterparty defaults) can immediately cascade into funding liquidity stress, illustrating that risk categories are interdependent rather than isolated.', 7),
  ('frm-foundations-corporate-governance-q01', 'frm-foundations-corporate-governance', 'Under the three lines of defense model, which line is responsible for providing independent assurance over risk management and controls?', 'Second line (risk and compliance)', 'Third line (internal audit)', 'First line (business units)', 'External audit', 'B', 'Internal audit constitutes the third line of defense, providing independent assurance that the first and second lines are functioning effectively. External audit is separate from the three-lines model.', 0),
  ('frm-foundations-corporate-governance-q02', 'frm-foundations-corporate-governance', 'A Chief Risk Officer (CRO) reports exclusively to the CEO with no direct access to the board. What governance weakness does this create?', 'Excessive risk appetite', 'Insufficient separation between the CRO and business lines', 'Potential lack of independence, as commercial pressures could override risk assessments', 'Inadequate quantitative risk modelling capability', 'C', 'CRO independence requires direct reporting access to the board, not solely to the CEO. Without board access, the CRO''s risk assessments may be filtered or overridden by commercial considerations.', 1),
  ('frm-foundations-corporate-governance-q03', 'frm-foundations-corporate-governance', 'Which of the following is the BEST indicator of a strong risk culture within a financial institution?', 'Senior leaders visibly endorse prudent risk behaviour and welcome escalation of concerns', 'Employees consistently prioritise short-term revenue targets above limit compliance', 'Risk limits are set conservatively and never reviewed', 'Internal audit findings are addressed only when mandated by regulators', 'A', 'Tone from the top — senior leaders visibly modelling and rewarding prudent risk behaviour — is the primary driver of a strong risk culture, creating an environment where staff escalate concerns without fear.', 2),
  ('frm-foundations-corporate-governance-q04', 'frm-foundations-corporate-governance', 'The Board Risk Committee''s primary responsibility is best described as:', 'Executing day-to-day risk management decisions on behalf of the CEO', 'Conducting internal audits of the risk management function', 'Preparing regulatory filings and stress test submissions', 'Setting and approving the firm''s risk appetite and overseeing major risk exposures', 'D', 'The Board Risk Committee''s core mandate is to set risk appetite at a strategic level and provide oversight of whether management''s risk-taking remains within approved boundaries — it does not execute operational decisions.', 3),
  ('frm-foundations-corporate-governance-q05', 'frm-foundations-corporate-governance', 'A trading desk manager is responsible for both approving trades and reconciling back-office records. This arrangement violates which governance principle?', 'Tone from the top', 'Segregation of duties', 'Risk appetite alignment', 'The three lines of defense model', 'B', 'Segregation of duties requires that no single individual controls multiple stages of a transaction (execution, approval, recording). Combining trading and back-office reconciliation creates unchecked opportunity for fraud, as demonstrated by the Barings Bank collapse.', 4),
  ('frm-foundations-corporate-governance-q06', 'frm-foundations-corporate-governance', 'Which of the following is a characteristic of the SECOND line of defense?', 'Directly generates revenue through customer transactions', 'Provides independent assurance by auditing both the first and second lines', 'Establishes risk policies, frameworks, and oversight without owning business risk', 'Issues regulatory capital requirements to the firm', 'C', 'The second line (risk management and compliance) creates the framework within which the first line operates, providing oversight and challenge without bearing primary responsibility for revenue generation or independent audit.', 5),
  ('frm-foundations-corporate-governance-q07', 'frm-foundations-corporate-governance', 'Regulators increasingly assess risk culture as a standalone supervisory concern. Which observation would MOST likely trigger regulatory concern about a firm''s risk culture?', 'Staff who raise concerns about mis-selling practices face informal sanctions', 'Risk appetite is reviewed annually', 'The CRO attends all board meetings', 'Internal audit reports are shared with external auditors', 'A', 'Suppression of whistleblowing and retaliation against staff raising legitimate concerns are direct indicators of a dysfunctional risk culture where negative information does not flow to decision-makers.', 6),
  ('frm-foundations-corporate-governance-q08', 'frm-foundations-corporate-governance', 'Which governance structure best ensures that the risk management function remains independent from commercial pressures?', 'CRO reports to the head of the trading business to improve information flow', 'Risk staff are rotated through business units to build commercial knowledge', 'CRO has a direct reporting line to the board and independent authority to escalate risk concerns', 'Risk limits are set by trading desks and submitted to the board for information', 'C', 'CRO independence is preserved by direct board access and authority to escalate risk concerns without management filtering. Reporting into commercial units creates conflicts of interest that undermine the second line''s effectiveness.', 7),
  ('frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite-q01', 'frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite', 'Which statement best distinguishes risk appetite from risk tolerance?', 'Risk appetite defines the desired level of risk-taking; risk tolerance defines the acceptable deviation around that level', 'Risk appetite is quantitative; risk tolerance is always qualitative', 'Risk tolerance is set by regulators; risk appetite is set by the board', 'Risk appetite applies to operational risk only; risk tolerance applies to market risk', 'A', 'Risk appetite is the aggregate level of risk the firm is willing to accept in pursuit of strategy; risk tolerance is the allowable band of deviation around the appetite within which management operates day-to-day.', 0),
  ('frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite-q02', 'frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite', 'A bank observes that its derivative counterparty exposure is rising toward a pre-set threshold before a formal limit is breached. This threshold is best described as a:', 'Risk register entry', 'Stress test scenario', 'Key Risk Indicator (KRI)', 'Value-at-Risk estimate', 'C', 'Key Risk Indicators (KRIs) are forward-looking metrics that provide early warning when risk levels are approaching limits, enabling preventive action before a formal breach occurs.', 1),
  ('frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite-q03', 'frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite', 'The primary advantage of Enterprise Risk Management (ERM) over traditional silo-based risk management is:', 'ERM eliminates the need for quantitative risk models within business units', 'ERM recognises risk interdependencies and enables portfolio-level aggregation across all risk types', 'ERM transfers all risk management responsibility to the compliance department', 'ERM reduces regulatory capital requirements to zero', 'B', 'ERM''s key advantage is an integrated, firm-wide view that captures how risks interact and aggregate, whereas silo-based management can miss concentrations and correlations that only become visible at the enterprise level.', 2),
  ('frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite-q04', 'frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite', 'A risk register should be updated:', 'Only when a loss event occurs', 'Continuously, as a living document reflecting the current risk environment', 'Annually, immediately before the regulatory inspection', 'Only when new products are launched', 'B', 'A risk register is a living document that must be maintained continuously to reflect emerging risks, changes in the control environment, and resolved risk items — not treated as a static compliance exercise.', 3),
  ('frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite-q05', 'frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite', 'Which component of the risk appetite framework translates the broad appetite statement into actionable day-to-day constraints for business units?', 'Risk register', 'Stress test results', 'ICAAP document', 'Risk limits', 'D', 'Risk limits (e.g., VaR limits by desk, concentration limits by counterparty) cascade the board-level appetite statement into specific, enforceable constraints that guide operational decision-making.', 4),
  ('frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite-q06', 'frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite', 'Stress testing within an ERM framework primarily serves to:', 'Replace the need for day-to-day risk limit monitoring', 'Determine the probability of default for individual borrowers', 'Eliminate model risk from the risk measurement process', 'Validate whether the firm can withstand severe but plausible adverse scenarios', 'D', 'Stress testing assesses the firm''s resilience under extreme but plausible scenarios, complementing probabilistic measures like VaR by revealing vulnerabilities that tail probabilities alone may not capture.', 5),
  ('frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite-q07', 'frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite', 'Which of the following best describes the relationship between risk appetite and strategic objectives?', 'Risk appetite translates strategic objectives into the level and type of risk the firm is willing to accept in pursuing them', 'Risk appetite is set independently of strategy by the risk function', 'Strategic objectives are derived from the risk appetite statement', 'Risk appetite applies only to financial risks, not strategic decisions', 'A', 'The risk appetite framework operationalises strategy by defining what risks are acceptable in its pursuit — appetite cannot be set without reference to the firm''s strategic goals and business model.', 6),
  ('frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite-q08', 'frm-foundations-erp-risk-appetite', 'Under traditional silo-based risk management, which of the following problems is most likely to emerge?', 'Concentration risks that span multiple categories are missed because no single function has the full picture', 'Excessive regulatory capital requirements for market risk', 'KRIs are set too conservatively relative to risk appetite', 'Internal audit becomes too independent from business operations', 'A', 'Silo-based management optimises individual risk categories in isolation, creating blind spots for cross-category concentrations and correlated risks that only become visible when viewed at the enterprise level.', 7),
  ('frm-foundations-financial-disasters-q01', 'frm-foundations-financial-disasters', 'The collapse of Barings Bank in 1995 is primarily attributed to which risk management failure?', 'Excessive market risk from proprietary currency trading', 'Inadequate credit limits on sovereign bond exposures', 'A single trader controlling both trading and back-office settlement, with no independent oversight', 'Model risk from mispriced equity derivatives', 'C', 'Nick Leeson exploited the absence of segregation of duties by controlling both the trading function and the back-office account (88888) used to conceal losses, a fundamental operational control failure.', 0),
  ('frm-foundations-financial-disasters-q02', 'frm-foundations-financial-disasters', 'Metallgesellschaft''s 1993 losses were primarily caused by:', 'Credit defaults on long-dated energy supply contracts', 'Overconcentration in a single equity position', 'A rogue trader accumulating speculative foreign exchange positions', 'Ignoring funding liquidity risk when using short-dated futures to hedge long-dated oil commitments', 'D', 'MG''s hedging strategy was theoretically sound in terms of price risk, but the short-dated futures generated enormous mark-to-market margin calls when oil prices fell, creating a funding liquidity crisis that forced liquidation of the hedge.', 1),
  ('frm-foundations-financial-disasters-q03', 'frm-foundations-financial-disasters', 'LTCM''s failure in 1998 demonstrated that during a market crisis, correlations between assets tend to:', 'Converge toward 1, eliminating assumed diversification benefits', 'Remain stable as predicted by historical models', 'Decrease, providing unexpected diversification benefits', 'Become negative, amplifying portfolio gains', 'A', 'The Russian debt default triggered a flight to quality in which assets that were historically uncorrelated moved together, causing correlations to converge toward 1 and destroying the diversification assumptions underlying LTCM''s models.', 2),
  ('frm-foundations-financial-disasters-q04', 'frm-foundations-financial-disasters', 'The Gaussian copula model used to price CDOs before the 2008 financial crisis failed primarily because it:', 'Overestimated interest rate volatility', 'Assumed no tail dependency between defaults, underestimating the probability of simultaneous defaults in stress', 'Used an incorrect risk-free rate for discounting cash flows', 'Applied fat-tailed distributions that overstated expected losses', 'B', 'The Gaussian copula has zero tail dependency, meaning it severely underestimated the probability that many mortgages would default simultaneously in a stress scenario — the exact pattern observed in 2008.', 3),
  ('frm-foundations-financial-disasters-q05', 'frm-foundations-financial-disasters', 'Which risk concept describes the situation where counterparty default risk is positively correlated with the size of the exposure to that counterparty?', 'Credit migration risk', 'Funding liquidity risk', 'Wrong-way risk', 'Basis risk', 'C', 'Wrong-way risk exists when exposure to a counterparty increases at the same time as the counterparty''s creditworthiness deteriorates, making the credit loss larger precisely when the counterparty is most likely to default.', 4),
  ('frm-foundations-financial-disasters-q06', 'frm-foundations-financial-disasters', 'A common lesson from multiple financial disasters (Barings, LTCM, 2008 crisis) is that:', 'Quantitative models are inherently unreliable and should be abandoned', 'Regulatory capital requirements are always sufficient to absorb unexpected losses', 'Leverage and model risk amplify losses beyond what intuitive risk assessment anticipates', 'Operational risk is the dominant source of systemic financial crises', 'C', 'Across all major financial disasters, excessive leverage magnified losses while model risk — the failure of models to capture real-world behaviour in stress — left institutions unprepared for the magnitude of actual losses.', 5),
  ('frm-foundations-financial-disasters-q07', 'frm-foundations-financial-disasters', 'The 2008 financial crisis revealed a significant overreliance on which risk assessment tool for structured credit products?', 'Stress testing under regulatory scenarios', 'Duration-based interest rate sensitivity', 'Historical simulation VaR', 'External credit ratings from agencies', 'D', 'Investors and institutions heavily relied on AAA ratings assigned by credit rating agencies to CDO tranches without independently assessing the underlying collateral quality or model assumptions, a key contributor to the crisis.', 6),
  ('frm-foundations-financial-disasters-q08', 'frm-foundations-financial-disasters', 'Model risk is best defined as:', 'The risk that a quantitative model produces outputs with insufficient decimal precision', 'The risk that IT systems used to run models may fail unexpectedly', 'The risk that model documentation is not shared with regulators', 'The risk of adverse consequences from decisions based on incorrect or misused models', 'D', 'Model risk encompasses both errors in model specification or calibration (a model that is wrong) and the misapplication of a correctly specified model to situations outside its intended scope.', 7),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions-q01', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions', 'A risk manager uses a normal distribution to estimate 99% VaR for a trading portfolio. Compared to using a Student-t distribution with 5 degrees of freedom, the normal distribution will likely:', 'Produce a higher VaR estimate due to fatter tails', 'Produce a lower VaR estimate due to thinner tails', 'Produce the same VaR estimate since both are symmetric', 'Produce a higher VaR estimate due to greater skewness', 'B', 'The normal distribution has thinner tails than the Student-t, so at high confidence levels (99%) it assigns less probability mass to extreme losses and therefore produces a lower VaR estimate than the fat-tailed t-distribution.', 0),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions-q02', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions', 'The lognormal distribution is preferred over the normal distribution for modelling equity prices primarily because:', 'It has fatter tails that better capture equity market crashes', 'It ensures prices cannot fall below zero', 'It is easier to estimate parameters than the normal distribution', 'It is symmetric, matching observed equity return distributions', 'B', 'If a stock price followed a normal distribution, it could theoretically become negative. The lognormal distribution constrains prices to positive values, which is consistent with limited liability for equity holders.', 1),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions-q03', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions', 'As the degrees of freedom parameter (nu) in a Student-t distribution increases toward infinity, the distribution:', 'Becomes increasingly skewed to the right', 'Develops progressively fatter tails', 'Converges to the standard normal distribution', 'Converges to a Poisson distribution', 'C', 'The Student-t distribution converges to the standard normal as degrees of freedom approach infinity, because the additional uncertainty from estimating the variance (which drives the fat tails) disappears.', 2),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions-q04', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions', 'In operational risk modelling under the Loss Distribution Approach, the Poisson distribution is used to model:', 'The severity of individual loss events', 'The correlation between different loss event types', 'The frequency of loss events in a given period', 'The capital charge for market risk', 'C', 'The LDA separates frequency and severity: frequency (the number of loss events per period) is typically modelled with a Poisson distribution, while severity (the size of each loss) uses a heavy-tailed distribution such as lognormal or GPD.', 3),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions-q05', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions', 'A credit portfolio model assumes each obligor defaults independently with a probability of 2%. The number of defaults in a pool of 100 obligors is best modelled using which distribution?', 'Normal distribution', 'Lognormal distribution', 'Binomial distribution', 'Student-t distribution', 'C', 'With n independent Bernoulli trials (default/no-default) each with probability p, the total number of defaults follows a Binomial(n, p) distribution. The normal approximation may be used for large n, but the binomial is the exact model.', 4),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions-q06', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions', 'Which property of empirical financial return distributions does the normal distribution most significantly fail to capture?', 'Positive mean returns over long horizons', 'Excess kurtosis (fat tails) and negative skewness', 'The continuous nature of returns', 'Time-varying correlations between assets', 'B', 'Empirical studies consistently show that financial returns exhibit excess kurtosis (more probability mass in the tails than normal) and negative skewness, both of which the normal distribution cannot accommodate.', 5),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions-q07', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions', 'Using a normal distribution to estimate VaR at high confidence levels (e.g., 99.9%) in the presence of fat-tailed returns will most likely result in:', 'Overestimation of VaR, leading to excess capital held', 'Accurate VaR estimates since the CLT applies', 'Underestimation of VaR, leading to insufficient capital', 'No impact, as VaR is insensitive to tail assumptions', 'C', 'At very high confidence levels, the VaR is determined by the extreme tail of the distribution. If returns are fat-tailed but modelled as normal, the normal distribution assigns too little probability to large losses, systematically underestimating VaR.', 6),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions-q08', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-probability-distributions', 'Which distribution is most appropriate for modelling the number of rare operational loss events (e.g., cyber incidents) occurring in a one-year period?', 'Normal distribution', 'Binomial distribution with large n', 'Student-t distribution', 'Poisson distribution', 'D', 'The Poisson distribution is designed for modelling the count of rare, independent events occurring in a fixed time interval at a constant average rate — exactly the characterisation of infrequent operational loss events.', 7),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference-q01', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference', 'The Central Limit Theorem (CLT) states that as sample size increases, the sampling distribution of the sample mean:', 'Converges to a normal distribution regardless of the population distribution', 'Approaches the same distribution as the underlying population', 'Becomes more skewed to match the population''s skewness', 'Has a standard deviation equal to the population standard deviation', 'A', 'The CLT guarantees convergence of the sample mean''s distribution to normal as n grows, regardless of the underlying population distribution shape — this is why normal-based inference is so widely applicable.', 0),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference-q02', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference', 'A 95% confidence interval for a parameter theta means:', 'There is a 95% probability that theta lies within this specific interval', 'The parameter theta equals the midpoint of the interval with 95% certainty', 'In repeated sampling, 95% of such constructed intervals would contain the true theta', 'The sample estimate is within 5% of the true parameter value', 'C', 'A confidence interval is a frequentist concept: it means that if the experiment were repeated many times, 95% of the resulting intervals would contain the true parameter. The true parameter is fixed; it is the interval that is random.', 1),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference-q03', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference', 'Maximum Likelihood Estimation (MLE) selects parameter values that:', 'Minimise the sum of squared differences between observed and fitted values', 'Match the theoretical moments to the sample moments', 'Maximise the probability of observing the sample data given the parameters', 'Minimise the variance of the parameter estimates', 'C', 'MLE finds the parameter values under which the observed data are most likely — i.e., it maximises the likelihood function L(theta | data). This is distinct from OLS (minimises squared errors) and method of moments.', 2),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference-q04', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference', 'The Kupiec proportion-of-failures (POF) test is used in risk management to:', 'Estimate the parameters of a GARCH model', 'Backtest whether observed VaR exceptions are consistent with the stated confidence level', 'Test for heteroskedasticity in regression residuals', 'Determine whether credit ratings follow a Markov chain', 'B', 'The Kupiec POF test is a hypothesis test for VaR backtesting: it tests whether the observed frequency of exceptions (losses exceeding VaR) is statistically consistent with the confidence level claimed by the model.', 3),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference-q05', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference', 'Compared to Maximum Likelihood Estimation, the Method of Moments estimator is generally:', 'More computationally intensive and statistically efficient', 'Less efficient but simpler to compute, especially with closed-form solutions', 'More accurate in small samples due to lower bias', 'Preferred for heavy-tailed distributions such as the Pareto', 'B', 'Method of Moments is typically simpler than MLE (often yielding closed-form estimates) but is less statistically efficient, meaning it requires larger samples to achieve the same estimation precision as MLE.', 4),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference-q06', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference', 'A risk manager estimates a 99% VaR of $10 million with a 95% confidence interval of [$8 million, $12 million]. What does this confidence interval convey?', 'There is estimation uncertainty around the VaR point estimate; the interval quantifies the precision of the estimate', 'The true VaR is definitely between $8 million and $12 million', 'The VaR will be exceeded between $8 million and $12 million times per year', 'The 95% VaR is $10 million', 'A', 'The confidence interval around a VaR estimate reflects sampling uncertainty — with a finite historical sample, the VaR itself is estimated with error, and the interval conveys the range within which the true VaR plausibly lies.', 5),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference-q07', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference', 'For which purpose is Bayesian estimation most advantageous relative to MLE?', 'When computational resources are severely limited and closed-form estimates are required', 'When the distribution family is unknown and non-parametric methods are needed', 'When the sample size is very large and asymptotic efficiency dominates', 'When prior knowledge or expert judgment about parameters can be formally incorporated into the estimation', 'D', 'Bayesian estimation''s distinguishing feature is the ability to incorporate prior information (expert judgment, historical data from related entities) through a prior distribution, making it especially useful when sample data are scarce.', 6),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference-q08', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-statistical-inference', 'A risk model produces too many VaR exceptions over a backtesting period. A hypothesis test fails to reject the model at the 5% significance level. The risk manager should:', 'Recognise that failing to reject does not prove the model is correct; consider additional diagnostic tests', 'Conclude the model is definitely correct and no action is needed', 'Increase the VaR confidence level to reduce the number of exceptions', 'Replace the model immediately since any exceptions indicate failure', 'A', 'Failing to reject a null hypothesis does not prove it is true — the test may have low power with limited data. Risk managers should use multiple backtesting tests and qualitative judgment rather than relying solely on a single hypothesis test result.', 7),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-regression-q01', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-regression', 'The Gauss-Markov theorem guarantees that OLS is the Best Linear Unbiased Estimator (BLUE) when:', 'The dependent variable follows a normal distribution', 'All regressors are uncorrelated with each other', 'The sample size exceeds 100 observations', 'Errors are homoskedastic, uncorrelated, and have zero conditional mean', 'D', 'The Gauss-Markov theorem requires zero conditional mean of errors, homoskedasticity (constant error variance), and no autocorrelation. Normality of errors is not required for BLUE, though it is needed for exact inference in small samples.', 0),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-regression-q02', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-regression', 'A researcher regresses bond spreads on macroeconomic variables and finds that residual variance increases with the level of interest rates. This is a sign of:', 'Autocorrelation', 'Heteroskedasticity', 'Multicollinearity', 'Structural break', 'B', 'Heteroskedasticity is present when the variance of regression residuals is not constant but varies systematically with a regressor (or the fitted values). Here, the error variance changes with interest rate levels, violating the OLS homoskedasticity assumption.', 1),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-regression-q03', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-regression', 'The Durbin-Watson (DW) statistic is used to test for:', 'First-order autocorrelation in time-series regression residuals', 'Heteroskedasticity in cross-sectional regression', 'Multicollinearity among regressors', 'Non-linearity in the regression functional form', 'A', 'The Durbin-Watson test detects first-order serial correlation (autocorrelation) in OLS residuals. A DW value near 2 indicates no autocorrelation; values near 0 indicate positive autocorrelation and values near 4 indicate negative autocorrelation.', 2),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-regression-q04', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-regression', 'A Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) of 12 for a regressor indicates:', 'The regressor has 12 times the explanatory power of the dependent variable', 'The regressor is highly correlated with other regressors, inflating its standard error approximately 12-fold', 'The regression model has 12% of its variance explained by this regressor', 'The regressor should be multiplied by 12 before inclusion in the model', 'B', 'VIF measures how much the variance of a coefficient estimate is inflated by multicollinearity. A VIF of 12 means the standard error is approximately sqrt(12) times larger than it would be if the regressor were uncorrelated with all others; VIF > 10 is typically cause for concern.', 3),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-regression-q05', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-regression', 'In the GARCH(1,1) model sigma^2_t = omega + alpha * epsilon^2_(t-1) + beta * sigma^2_(t-1), the term alpha * epsilon^2_(t-1) captures:', 'The long-run average variance', 'The impact of the most recent squared return shock on today''s variance', 'The persistence of the conditional variance from yesterday', 'The correlation between return shocks and variance changes', 'B', 'The alpha term in GARCH(1,1) governs the reaction of conditional variance to the most recent squared return shock (the ARCH effect). A large alpha means variance responds quickly and sharply to new information.', 4),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-regression-q06', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-regression', 'When OLS residuals exhibit positive autocorrelation, which of the following consequences is most likely?', 'Standard errors are underestimated, making t-statistics appear more significant than they are', 'Coefficient estimates become biased and inconsistent', 'The R-squared statistic falls to zero', 'Coefficient estimates become inconsistent but standard errors remain valid', 'A', 'With positive autocorrelation, OLS standard errors are underestimated because the effective number of independent observations is overstated. This inflates t-statistics, causing spurious appearance of statistical significance. Coefficient estimates remain unbiased but are no longer efficient.', 5),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-regression-q07', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-regression', 'GARCH models are used in quantitative risk management primarily to:', 'Model time-varying (conditional) volatility, capturing volatility clustering', 'Correct for heteroskedasticity in cross-sectional equity regressions', 'Reduce multicollinearity in factor models', 'Estimate the unconditional mean of financial returns', 'A', 'GARCH captures the empirical observation that volatility clusters — periods of high volatility tend to persist, and periods of low volatility tend to persist. This makes GARCH models the foundation for dynamic VaR and options pricing with time-varying volatility.', 6),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-regression-q08', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-regression', 'When the OLS homoskedasticity assumption is violated, an appropriate remedy is to:', 'Remove all regressors with VIF greater than 5', 'Apply the Durbin-Watson correction to the coefficient estimates', 'Increase the sample size until residual variance stabilises', 'Use White''s heteroskedasticity-consistent standard errors or Weighted Least Squares', 'D', 'White''s robust standard errors correct the inference problem caused by heteroskedasticity without changing the coefficient estimates. WLS re-weights observations to restore efficiency when the variance pattern is known. Both are standard remedies in financial econometrics.', 7),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo-q01', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo', 'The first step in a Monte Carlo simulation of portfolio VaR is to:', 'Calculate the empirical VaR from historical data', 'Select the copula for dependency modelling', 'Specify the stochastic model governing the dynamics of the underlying risk factors', 'Generate pseudo-random numbers from a standard normal distribution', 'C', 'Before generating random numbers, the risk manager must specify the model (e.g., GBM, jump-diffusion) that governs how risk factors evolve. Random number generation is a later step in the simulation procedure.', 0),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo-q02', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo', 'The antithetic variates variance reduction technique works by:', 'Sampling more heavily from the tail region and reweighting results', 'Pairing each random draw u with (1-u) so that deviations above and below the mean partially cancel', 'Using a correlated variable with a known analytical price to adjust simulated values', 'Stratifying the sample space into equal-probability intervals', 'B', 'Antithetic variates pair each uniform draw u with its complement (1-u), creating negatively correlated simulation paths. This negative correlation causes overestimates on one path to be offset by underestimates on the paired path, reducing overall estimator variance.', 1),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo-q03', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo', 'Sklar''s theorem, which underpins copula theory, states that:', 'The sum of correlated normal random variables follows a normal distribution', 'Any joint distribution can be decomposed into its marginal distributions and a copula capturing the dependency structure', 'Copulas are only valid when the marginal distributions are normal', 'Tail dependency is always zero for elliptical copulas', 'B', 'Sklar''s theorem is the mathematical foundation of copula theory: any multivariate joint distribution can be expressed as a function of its marginals and a copula. This allows marginal distributions and dependency structure to be modelled separately.', 2),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo-q04', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo', 'The Gaussian copula was widely criticised after the 2008 financial crisis because it:', 'Is computationally too expensive for large credit portfolios', 'Requires marginal distributions to be normal, which is rarely true', 'Cannot accommodate asymmetric dependencies between assets', 'Assumes zero tail dependency, meaning it underestimates the probability of simultaneous large losses', 'D', 'The Gaussian copula has zero tail dependency — the probability of simultaneous extreme events converges to zero even as correlations increase. This caused systematic underestimation of joint default probabilities in CDO portfolios.', 3),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo-q05', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo', 'Importance sampling improves Monte Carlo efficiency for tail risk estimation by:', 'Reducing the number of model parameters that need to be estimated', 'Correlating simulation paths to reduce variance via negative covariance', 'Replacing random draws with deterministic low-discrepancy sequences', 'Oversampling the tail region of the distribution and reweighting the results to remove bias', 'D', 'Importance sampling concentrates simulation effort in the tail region that matters for VaR and ES estimation, then uses likelihood-ratio weights to correct for the biased sampling. This dramatically reduces the number of paths needed for accurate tail estimates.', 4),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo-q06', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo', 'The Student-t copula, compared to the Gaussian copula, is better suited to credit portfolio modelling primarily because:', 'It exhibits symmetric tail dependency, capturing the tendency for defaults to cluster in stress scenarios', 'It requires fewer parameters to estimate', 'It assumes independence between extreme events', 'It is equivalent to the Gaussian copula for all practical purposes', 'A', 'The Student-t copula has positive tail dependence (both upper and lower), meaning it assigns higher probability than the Gaussian copula to simultaneous extreme losses — making it more realistic for credit portfolio stress scenarios.', 5),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo-q07', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo', 'The probability integral transform is used in Monte Carlo simulation to:', 'Correlate random draws across simulation paths using the Cholesky decomposition', 'Convert normally distributed samples to uniform samples for variance reduction', 'Transform uniform random draws into draws from any target distribution using the inverse CDF', 'Construct antithetic pairs from pseudo-random uniform samples', 'C', 'The probability integral transform states that if U ~ Uniform(0,1), then F^{-1}(U) follows the distribution with CDF F. This allows simulation from any distribution by applying its inverse CDF to uniform random numbers.', 6),
  ('frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo-q08', 'frm-quantitative-analysis-monte-carlo', 'For modelling the joint default risk of a credit portfolio where defaults are more likely to cluster in economic downturns (lower tail dependency), which copula is most appropriate?', 'Clayton copula', 'Gaussian copula', 'Gumbel copula', 'Frank copula', 'A', 'The Clayton copula exhibits strong lower tail dependency and weak upper tail dependency, making it well-suited to credit default modelling where the key concern is clustering of defaults during economic stress (lower tail events).', 7),
  ('frm-financial-markets-options-pricing-q01', 'frm-financial-markets-options-pricing', 'The payoff of a European call option at expiry is:', 'max(S - K, 0)', 'max(K - S, 0)', 'S minus the premium paid', 'K times the risk-free rate', 'A', 'A call pays the excess of the asset price S over the strike K if positive, and zero otherwise.', 0),
  ('frm-financial-markets-options-pricing-q02', 'frm-financial-markets-options-pricing', 'Which of the following is NOT an input to the Black-Scholes option pricing model?', 'Current asset price', 'Historical dividend growth rate', 'Volatility of the underlying asset', 'Risk-free interest rate', 'B', 'Black-Scholes requires the current price, strike, time, risk-free rate, and volatility; historical dividend growth is not an input.', 1),
  ('frm-financial-markets-options-pricing-q03', 'frm-financial-markets-options-pricing', 'Implied volatility is best described as:', 'The historical standard deviation of past returns', 'The GARCH forecast of future volatility', 'The realized volatility over the option''s life', 'The volatility backed out of a market option price using the pricing model', 'D', 'Implied volatility is derived from the current market price of an option by inverting the pricing model.', 2),
  ('frm-financial-markets-options-pricing-q04', 'frm-financial-markets-options-pricing', 'A volatility smile in options markets indicates that:', 'Implied volatility is identical across all strikes', 'Historical and implied volatilities always match', 'Options are priced using the CAPM', 'Implied volatility varies with the strike price, violating strict Black-Scholes assumptions', 'D', 'The volatility smile shows that implied volatility changes across strikes, a pattern inconsistent with constant-volatility Black-Scholes.', 3),
  ('frm-financial-markets-options-pricing-q05', 'frm-financial-markets-options-pricing', 'The buyer of a call option has:', 'An obligation to buy the asset at the strike price', 'The right to sell the asset at the strike price', 'The right to buy the asset at the strike price', 'Unlimited liability if the asset price falls', 'C', 'A call option gives the holder the right, not the obligation, to purchase the underlying at the strike price.', 4),
  ('frm-financial-markets-options-pricing-q06', 'frm-financial-markets-options-pricing', 'Black-Scholes assumes which of the following about the underlying asset''s returns?', 'Returns follow a lognormal distribution with constant volatility', 'Returns follow a uniform distribution', 'Returns are mean-reverting with GARCH volatility', 'Returns are always positive', 'A', 'Black-Scholes assumes log-returns are normally distributed, implying prices are lognormal, with constant volatility throughout.', 5),
  ('frm-financial-markets-options-pricing-q07', 'frm-financial-markets-options-pricing', 'The maximum loss for the buyer of a put option is:', 'Unlimited, because the asset price can rise indefinitely', 'Equal to the strike price', 'The premium paid for the option', 'Zero, because puts always expire worthless', 'C', 'The put buyer''s maximum loss is limited to the premium paid; the option simply expires worthless if unexercised.', 6),
  ('frm-financial-markets-options-pricing-q08', 'frm-financial-markets-options-pricing', 'All else equal, increasing the time to expiry of an option will generally:', 'Decrease both call and put values', 'Increase both call and put values', 'Increase calls but decrease puts', 'Have no effect on option value', 'B', 'Longer time to expiry gives the option more opportunity to move in-the-money, raising the value of both calls and puts.', 7),
  ('frm-financial-markets-swaps-q01', 'frm-financial-markets-swaps', 'In a plain vanilla interest rate swap, the fixed-rate payer:', 'Pays floating and receives fixed', 'Receives fixed and pays no floating', 'Pays both fixed and floating rates', 'Pays fixed and receives floating', 'D', 'The fixed-rate payer in a vanilla swap pays the fixed swap rate and receives the floating reference rate.', 0),
  ('frm-financial-markets-swaps-q02', 'frm-financial-markets-swaps', 'At initiation, the swap rate in a plain vanilla interest rate swap is set so that the swap has:', 'A positive net present value to the fixed payer', 'A negative net present value', 'Zero value to both counterparties', 'A value equal to the notional principal', 'C', 'The swap rate is chosen so that the present value of fixed payments equals the present value of expected floating payments, giving zero initial value.', 1),
  ('frm-financial-markets-swaps-q03', 'frm-financial-markets-swaps', 'Following the 2008 financial crisis, the standard for discounting collateralized swap cash flows shifted to:', 'LIBOR flat', 'The overnight indexed swap (OIS) rate', 'The repo rate plus a spread', 'The federal funds target rate', 'B', 'Post-crisis best practice is to discount collateralized swaps using the OIS rate, which better reflects the risk-free rate.', 2),
  ('frm-financial-markets-swaps-q04', 'frm-financial-markets-swaps', 'SOFR (Secured Overnight Financing Rate) replaced LIBOR primarily because:', 'SOFR includes a credit-risk premium like LIBOR', 'SOFR is a forward-looking term rate like LIBOR', 'SOFR is published by commercial banks, not central banks', 'SOFR is based on actual overnight repo transactions, making it more robust', 'D', 'SOFR is grounded in real overnight repo transactions, eliminating the manipulation risk associated with LIBOR panel submissions.', 3),
  ('frm-financial-markets-swaps-q05', 'frm-financial-markets-swaps', 'A swap can be valued by treating it as the difference between:', 'Two equity positions', 'A forward contract and a futures contract', 'A fixed-rate bond and a floating-rate bond', 'Two options on interest rates', 'C', 'A swap is equivalent to a long position in one bond (fixed or floating) and a short position in the other, enabling bond-based valuation.', 4),
  ('frm-financial-markets-swaps-q06', 'frm-financial-markets-swaps', 'In an interest rate swap, which party benefits if floating rates rise significantly above the fixed swap rate?', 'Both parties equally', 'The fixed-rate payer', 'The floating-rate payer', 'The clearinghouse', 'B', 'When floating rates exceed the fixed rate, the fixed-rate payer receives more than it pays, gaining from the rate rise.', 5),
  ('frm-financial-markets-swaps-q07', 'frm-financial-markets-swaps', 'In a plain vanilla swap, only net cash flows are exchanged because:', 'Notional principal is always delivered at maturity', 'Both legs are denominated in the same currency and netting reduces credit exposure', 'The floating rate is fixed at initiation', 'Regulators require full gross settlement', 'B', 'Netting same-currency payment obligations reduces settlement risk and operational complexity.', 6),
  ('frm-financial-markets-swaps-q08', 'frm-financial-markets-swaps', 'A currency swap differs from an interest rate swap in that a currency swap:', 'Never involves any principal exchange', 'Cannot be used to hedge foreign exchange risk', 'Always uses the same reference rate on both legs', 'Involves exchange of principal in different currencies at maturity', 'D', 'Currency swaps typically involve exchanging notional principal in different currencies at inception and re-exchange at maturity.', 7),
  ('frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products-q01', 'frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products', 'A bond''s yield to maturity is best described as the discount rate that:', 'Equals the coupon rate in all cases', 'Is always equal to the risk-free rate', 'Measures only the credit spread over the risk-free rate', 'Equates the bond''s price to the present value of its future cash flows', 'D', 'YTM is the internal rate of return that sets the sum of discounted cash flows equal to the current bond price.', 0),
  ('frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products-q02', 'frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products', 'When market interest rates rise, the price of a fixed-coupon bond will:', 'Also rise proportionally', 'Fall', 'Remain unchanged', 'Equal the coupon rate', 'B', 'Bond prices and yields move inversely; when market rates rise, the present value of fixed cash flows falls.', 1),
  ('frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products-q03', 'frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products', 'Modified duration approximates the:', 'Percentage change in bond price per 1% change in yield', 'Dollar change in bond price for a 1% change in yield', 'Change in coupon payment when rates move', 'Credit spread of the bond', 'A', 'Modified duration gives the approximate percentage price change for a 100-basis-point shift in yield.', 2),
  ('frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products-q04', 'frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products', 'Convexity improves the duration approximation by capturing:', 'The credit risk component of yield', 'The linear sensitivity to rate moves', 'The curvature in the price-yield relationship', 'The time value of coupon payments', 'C', 'Convexity is the second-order term that corrects for the nonlinear (curved) price response to yield changes.', 3),
  ('frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products-q05', 'frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products', 'In a repurchase agreement (repo), the haircut represents:', 'The interest rate charged on the repo', 'The duration of the collateral', 'The coupon rate of the collateral bond', 'The discount applied to collateral value to protect the cash lender', 'D', 'The haircut is the difference between the market value of collateral and the cash lent, protecting the lender against collateral price falls.', 4),
  ('frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products-q06', 'frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products', 'Which yield measure assumes all coupon payments are reinvested at the same rate as the YTM?', 'Current yield', 'Coupon rate', 'Spot rate', 'Yield to maturity', 'D', 'YTM implicitly assumes coupon reinvestment at the YTM rate, which is a key limitation of the measure.', 5),
  ('frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products-q07', 'frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products', 'A bond with higher convexity, compared to a lower-convexity bond with the same duration, will:', 'Lose more value when yields fall', 'Gain less value when yields fall and lose more when yields rise', 'Gain more value when yields fall and lose less when yields rise', 'Have identical price behavior to the lower-convexity bond', 'C', 'Higher convexity means the price-yield curve is more curved, so the bond outperforms in both yield-up and yield-down scenarios.', 6),
  ('frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products-q08', 'frm-financial-markets-fixed-income-products', 'Repos are primarily used by fixed-income dealers to:', 'Issue new equity capital', 'Hedge equity market risk', 'Fund their bond holdings with short-term borrowing', 'Calculate yield to maturity', 'C', 'Dealers use the repo market to finance bond inventories by temporarily selling securities and agreeing to repurchase them.', 7),
  ('frm-financial-markets-credit-products-q01', 'frm-financial-markets-credit-products', 'In a credit default swap, the protection buyer:', 'Pays a periodic spread and receives compensation on a credit event', 'Receives a periodic spread and pays on a credit event', 'Holds the reference bonds directly', 'Receives no payment if the reference entity defaults', 'A', 'The protection buyer pays the CDS spread and receives a loss payment from the seller if a credit event occurs.', 0),
  ('frm-financial-markets-credit-products-q02', 'frm-financial-markets-credit-products', 'A wider CDS spread for a reference entity generally reflects:', 'Higher perceived default risk or lower recovery expectations', 'A higher recovery rate', 'Lower perceived default risk', 'A stronger credit rating', 'A', 'CDS spreads widen when markets perceive higher default probability or lower expected recovery, as the protection seller bears greater expected loss.', 1),
  ('frm-financial-markets-credit-products-q03', 'frm-financial-markets-credit-products', 'In a CDO, which tranche absorbs the first losses from the collateral pool?', 'Senior tranche', 'Equity (first-loss) tranche', 'Mezzanine tranche', 'Super-senior tranche', 'B', 'The equity tranche absorbs losses first, protecting the mezzanine and senior tranches.', 2),
  ('frm-financial-markets-credit-products-q04', 'frm-financial-markets-credit-products', 'A synthetic CDO differs from a cash CDO primarily because a synthetic CDO:', 'Gains credit exposure through CDS rather than actual bond holdings', 'Always holds physical bonds as collateral', 'Is always rated AAA', 'Cannot be tranched into senior and junior notes', 'A', 'Synthetic CDOs use CDS contracts to obtain credit exposure without purchasing the underlying bonds.', 3),
  ('frm-financial-markets-credit-products-q05', 'frm-financial-markets-credit-products', 'In a CDO structure, the senior tranche offers the lowest yield because it:', 'Absorbs the first losses', 'Has the highest priority claim and the lowest default risk', 'Has the highest correlation risk', 'Is always unrated', 'B', 'Senior tranches bear losses only after all subordinate tranches are wiped out, so they carry the lowest risk and yield.', 4),
  ('frm-financial-markets-credit-products-q06', 'frm-financial-markets-credit-products', 'A CDS credit event that triggers a payment from the protection seller includes:', 'A rise in interest rates', 'An equity market decline', 'A decline in commodity prices', 'Default or restructuring of the reference entity', 'D', 'CDS credit events are defined in the contract and typically include bankruptcy, failure to pay, and restructuring of the reference entity.', 5),
  ('frm-financial-markets-credit-products-q07', 'frm-financial-markets-credit-products', 'Higher default correlation among CDO reference entities benefits which tranche the most?', 'Senior tranche', 'Equity tranche', 'Mezzanine tranche', 'All tranches equally', 'B', 'Higher correlation makes defaults cluster, increasing the chance of total portfolio loss but also increasing the chance of no losses at all, which benefits equity holders.', 6),
  ('frm-financial-markets-credit-products-q08', 'frm-financial-markets-credit-products', 'The CDS spread at inception is set so that:', 'The present value of premium payments equals the present value of expected loss payments', 'The protection buyer pays more than the expected loss', 'The swap always has positive value for the protection seller', 'The spread equals the risk-free rate', 'A', 'Like any swap, the CDS spread is set at initiation so that the instrument has zero net present value to both parties.', 7),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation-q01', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation', 'DV01 measures the change in bond price for a:', '1% change in yield', '1-basis-point (0.01%) decrease in yield', '1% change in the credit spread', '1-day change in time to maturity', 'B', 'DV01 (dollar value of a basis point) is the price change for a 1-basis-point downward shift in yield.', 0),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation-q02', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation', 'Key rate durations are most useful for hedging:', 'Parallel shifts in the yield curve only', 'Currency risk in foreign bonds', 'Credit spread movements', 'Yield curve shape risk arising from non-parallel shifts', 'D', 'Key rate durations isolate sensitivity at each maturity point, enabling hedges against twists and steepening of the yield curve.', 1),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation-q03', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation', 'Spread duration measures a bond''s price sensitivity to changes in its:', 'Coupon rate', 'Time to maturity', 'Credit spread', 'Recovery rate', 'C', 'Spread duration captures how much the bond price changes when its credit spread over the risk-free rate widens or narrows.', 2),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation-q04', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation', 'The option-adjusted spread (OAS) of a callable bond strips out the option effect in order to:', 'Enable fair comparison with bullet bonds', 'Increase the bond''s yield above its YTM', 'Remove credit risk from the spread', 'Calculate the bond''s modified duration', 'A', 'OAS removes the value of the embedded option, allowing like-for-like yield comparison between callable and non-callable bonds.', 3),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation-q05', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation', 'A portfolio''s total DV01 is computed as:', 'The sum of DV01 across all positions', 'The average DV01 across all positions', 'The DV01 of the largest position only', 'The DV01 of the longest-maturity bond', 'A', 'DV01 is linear and additive, so portfolio DV01 is the sum of individual position DV01s.', 4),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation-q06', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation', 'For a callable bond, a lower OAS relative to a similar non-callable bond reflects:', 'Greater credit risk', 'A steeper yield curve', 'Higher liquidity of the callable bond', 'The cost of the call option embedded in the bond', 'D', 'The callable bond''s OAS is lower than its nominal spread because part of the spread compensates for the call option value retained by the issuer.', 5),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation-q07', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation', 'Which statement about key rate durations is correct?', 'Key rate durations across all maturities sum to zero', 'Key rate durations are independent of position size', 'Key rate durations sum to the total modified duration', 'Key rate durations measure only credit spread risk', 'C', 'The sum of all key rate durations equals the bond''s total modified duration, as they decompose the same overall interest rate sensitivity.', 6),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation-q08', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-bond-valuation', 'A widening of credit spreads will cause the price of a credit-risky bond to:', 'Rise, because the bond becomes cheaper to issue', 'Remain unchanged if duration is constant', 'Rise proportionally to the spread widening', 'Fall, because the discount rate applied to the bond''s cash flows increases', 'D', 'A wider credit spread raises the total yield used to discount cash flows, lowering the present value and hence the bond price.', 7),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation-q01', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation', 'Delta for a long call option is:', 'Between 0 and 1', 'Always negative', 'Between -1 and 0', 'Always greater than 1', 'A', 'Call delta is positive and bounded between 0 (deep out-of-the-money) and 1 (deep in-the-money).', 0),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation-q02', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation', 'Gamma is highest for options that are:', 'Deep in-the-money with long time to expiry', 'Deep out-of-the-money with any time to expiry', 'In-the-money with long time to expiry', 'At-the-money and near expiry', 'D', 'Gamma peaks for at-the-money options close to expiry, because small price changes can shift the option from in- to out-of-the-money.', 1),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation-q03', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation', 'Vega measures the sensitivity of an option''s price to:', 'The risk-free interest rate', 'The passage of time', 'Changes in implied volatility', 'Changes in the underlying asset price', 'C', 'Vega is the partial derivative of the option price with respect to implied volatility; long options have positive vega.', 2),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation-q04', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation', 'Theta for a long option position is generally:', 'Positive, because the option gains value over time', 'Negative, reflecting time decay as expiry approaches', 'Zero for all options', 'Positive only for deep in-the-money options', 'B', 'Long option positions suffer time decay (theta is negative), losing value as expiry approaches with all else constant.', 3),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation-q05', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation', 'A delta-neutral portfolio must be rebalanced frequently because:', 'Delta changes as the underlying price moves, driven by gamma', 'Vega increases as options approach expiry', 'Rho changes with the risk-free rate daily', 'Theta becomes positive after hedging', 'A', 'Gamma causes delta to change as the underlying moves, so a delta-neutral hedge drifts and must be rebalanced continuously.', 4),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation-q06', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation', 'A trader who is long gamma benefits from:', 'Large moves in the underlying asset in either direction', 'Low realized volatility and stable markets', 'Declining implied volatility', 'Slow passage of time', 'A', 'Long gamma positions profit from large price swings because gains accelerate in either direction while losses from rebalancing are limited.', 5),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation-q07', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation', 'Rho for a long call option is:', 'Negative, because higher rates reduce call value', 'Zero for all standard options', 'Positive, because higher rates increase call value', 'Equal to delta', 'C', 'A higher risk-free rate lowers the present value of the strike price paid at expiry, increasing the call option''s value.', 6),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation-q08', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-option-valuation', 'A key limitation of dynamic delta hedging in practice is that:', 'It requires no monitoring after establishment', 'It eliminates all gamma and vega risk simultaneously', 'Discrete rebalancing, transaction costs, and price jumps leave residual risk', 'It can only be applied to at-the-money options', 'C', 'Continuous rebalancing is impossible in practice; gaps between trades, transaction costs, and sudden jumps all create imperfect hedges.', 7),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing-q01', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing', 'The primary purpose of stress testing is to:', 'Replace VaR as the sole risk measure', 'Set individual trader position limits', 'Calculate expected losses under average market conditions', 'Examine portfolio performance under severe scenarios that statistical models may miss', 'D', 'Stress testing evaluates tail scenarios — typically severe, correlated dislocations — that VaR underestimates or excludes.', 0),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing-q02', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing', 'DFAST stands for:', 'Dodd-Frank Act Stress Test', 'Diversified Fixed-Asset Stress Test', 'Dynamic Funding and Stability Test', 'Default Frequency Assessment and Stress Test', 'A', 'DFAST is the Dodd-Frank Act Stress Test, an annual U.S. regulatory requirement for large bank holding companies.', 1),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing-q03', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing', 'Reverse stress testing differs from conventional stress testing in that it:', 'Uses only historical scenarios', 'Works backward from a failure outcome to identify what scenarios could cause it', 'Applies only to market risk, not credit or liquidity risk', 'Is voluntary and not required by any regulator', 'B', 'Reverse stress testing starts with the outcome (failure or capital breach) and works backward to identify plausible triggering scenarios.', 2),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing-q04', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing', 'A historical scenario stress test using the 2008 financial crisis as a template is limited because it:', 'Only captures risks that materialized in the past, missing novel scenarios', 'Requires Monte Carlo simulation', 'Cannot project capital adequacy', 'Is too expensive to implement', 'A', 'Historical scenarios are anchored to past events and cannot anticipate entirely new risk drivers or unprecedented market structures.', 3),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing-q05', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing', 'CCAR (Comprehensive Capital Analysis and Review) is primarily used by U.S. regulators to assess banks'':', 'Capital planning processes and capital adequacy under stress', 'Market liquidity of trading books', 'Operational risk event counts', 'Counterparty credit exposure only', 'A', 'CCAR evaluates whether large bank holding companies have sufficient capital and sound capital planning processes under adverse scenarios.', 4),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing-q06', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing', 'A hypothetical (narrative) stress scenario differs from a historical scenario in that it:', 'Uses only quantitative data without expert judgment', 'Replays observed market moves directly', 'Is forward-looking and can incorporate unprecedented shocks', 'Cannot be used for regulatory reporting', 'C', 'Hypothetical scenarios are constructed around plausible but previously unseen events, allowing assessment of novel systemic risks.', 5),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing-q07', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing', 'The severely adverse scenario in a DFAST stress test is designed to represent:', 'Expected base-case economic conditions', 'A mild recession with moderate unemployment', 'A severe global recession with sharp asset price declines', 'Only interest rate risk, not credit or market risk', 'C', 'The severely adverse scenario represents a deep recession, typically with large unemployment increases and significant asset price falls.', 6),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing-q08', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-stress-testing', 'Stress testing is best viewed as a complement to VaR rather than a replacement because:', 'Stress tests are always more conservative than VaR', 'Stress tests explore specific extreme scenarios while VaR summarizes typical loss distributions', 'VaR captures tail severity while stress testing captures frequency', 'Regulators prohibit using stress tests and VaR together', 'B', 'VaR characterizes the loss distribution statistically; stress tests explore particular severe scenarios, together giving a fuller risk picture.', 7),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk-q01', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk', 'The Federal Reserve''s primary supervisory guidance on model risk management is:', 'SR 11-7', 'Basel III Pillar 2', 'Dodd-Frank Section 165', 'FRTB Article 325', 'A', 'SR 11-7 is the Fed''s Supervisory Guidance on Model Risk Management, setting out the framework for model development, validation, and governance.', 0),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk-q02', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk', 'Under SR 11-7, which of the following is required of the model validation function?', 'Validation must be performed by the model''s own developers', 'Validation need not assess model conceptual soundness', 'Validation is only required for market risk models', 'Validation must be independent of model development', 'D', 'SR 11-7 requires that validation be conducted independently of the teams that build and use models to ensure objectivity.', 1),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk-q03', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk', 'Backtesting a VaR model involves:', 'Simulating future scenarios and comparing them to theoretical values', 'Comparing model-predicted VaR breaches to actual realized losses', 'Rerunning the model with different random seeds', 'Replacing the model with a challenger model', 'B', 'Backtesting counts how often actual losses exceed the VaR estimate, testing whether the model''s predictions match realized outcomes.', 2),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk-q04', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk', 'A challenger model in the context of model validation is:', 'A model that is always inferior to the primary model', 'An independently built alternative used to benchmark or validate the primary model', 'A regulatory-prescribed model mandated by SR 11-7', 'A model used exclusively for stress testing', 'B', 'Challenger models are independent alternatives that help validate the primary model and reduce reliance on a single approach.', 3),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk-q05', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk', 'Model misuse occurs when a model is:', 'Used within its intended range and assumptions', 'Subjected to sensitivity analysis', 'Applied outside the scope or conditions it was designed for', 'Validated by an independent team', 'C', 'Model misuse is applying a model beyond its intended use case or assumptions, which can produce materially misleading outputs.', 4),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk-q06', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk', 'Sensitivity analysis in model validation is used to:', 'Replace backtesting entirely', 'Test how model outputs change under varied input assumptions', 'Determine the model''s historical loss record', 'Set the model''s capital charge directly', 'B', 'Sensitivity analysis probes the stability of model outputs by varying key assumptions, revealing dependence on uncertain inputs.', 5),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk-q07', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk', 'According to SR 11-7, a model consists of three components: an information input, a processing component, and:', 'A regulatory approval step', 'A stress testing module', 'A reporting (output) component', 'A benchmarking database', 'C', 'SR 11-7 defines a model as having an input component, a processing component, and a reporting or output component.', 6),
  ('frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk-q08', 'frm-valuation-risk-models-model-risk', 'Benchmarking during model validation involves:', 'Setting minimum capital requirements for the model', 'Documenting the model''s assumptions for regulators', 'Counting VaR exceptions over a historical period', 'Comparing the model''s output to those of alternative or industry-standard models', 'D', 'Benchmarking assesses a model by comparing its results to those produced by independent or industry-accepted alternative models.', 7),
  ('frm-market-risk-parametric-var-q01', 'frm-market-risk-parametric-var', 'A portfolio has a daily volatility of 1.2% and a market value of $10 million. What is the 1-day 99% VaR under the parametric method?', '$198,000', '$233,000', '$279,600', '$165,000', 'C', 'The 99% z-score is 2.33, so VaR = $10,000,000 x 2.33 x 0.012 = $279,600. The 95% z-score of 1.65 would give $198,000, which is the most common distractor.', 0),
  ('frm-market-risk-parametric-var-q02', 'frm-market-risk-parametric-var', 'Which z-score corresponds to a 95% one-tailed confidence level in parametric VaR?', '1.65', '2.33', '1.28', '2.58', 'A', 'The 95% one-tailed z-score is 1.65. A z-score of 1.28 corresponds to 90%, 2.33 to 99%, and 2.58 to 99.5% confidence levels.', 1),
  ('frm-market-risk-parametric-var-q03', 'frm-market-risk-parametric-var', 'Portfolio A has a 1-day VaR of $500,000 and Portfolio B has a 1-day VaR of $300,000. The correlation between the two is 0. What is the combined portfolio VaR?', '$800,000', '$200,000', '$400,000', '$583,095', 'D', 'With zero correlation, portfolio VaR = sqrt(500,000^2 + 300,000^2) = sqrt(250,000,000,000 + 90,000,000,000) = sqrt(340,000,000,000) = approximately $583,095. The sum of $800,000 ignores diversification.', 2),
  ('frm-market-risk-parametric-var-q04', 'frm-market-risk-parametric-var', 'Under the square root of time rule, a 1-day 99% VaR of $1 million scales to a 10-day VaR of approximately:', '$2,330,000', '$10,000,000', '$1,000,000', '$3,162,278', 'D', 'The 10-day VaR is obtained by multiplying the 1-day VaR by sqrt(10) = 3.1623, giving approximately $3,162,278. Multiplying by 10 ignores the square root scaling assumption.', 3),
  ('frm-market-risk-parametric-var-q05', 'frm-market-risk-parametric-var', 'The primary distributional assumption underlying parametric VaR is that portfolio returns are:', 'Fat-tailed with positive skewness', 'Uniformly distributed', 'Normally distributed', 'Log-normally distributed with mean zero', 'C', 'Parametric VaR assumes normally distributed returns, which allows the use of z-scores to map confidence levels to loss quantiles. This assumption understates tail risk when actual returns have fat tails.', 4),
  ('frm-market-risk-parametric-var-q06', 'frm-market-risk-parametric-var', 'When the correlation between two assets in a portfolio increases from 0 to 1, the portfolio VaR will:', 'Decrease, reflecting greater diversification', 'Remain unchanged', 'Decrease to zero', 'Increase, reaching the sum of individual VaRs', 'D', 'As correlation approaches 1, the diversification benefit disappears and portfolio VaR approaches the simple sum of individual VaRs. A correlation of -1 would minimise portfolio risk.', 5),
  ('frm-market-risk-parametric-var-q07', 'frm-market-risk-parametric-var', 'Which of the following is a key limitation of the parametric VaR method for options portfolios?', 'It requires an excessively long historical data window', 'It cannot accommodate correlation inputs between assets', 'It relies on a linear approximation that fails to capture gamma and vega exposures', 'It systematically overstates tail risk due to the fat-tailed assumption', 'C', 'Parametric VaR uses a delta (linear) approximation of portfolio value changes, which misses the nonlinear effects of gamma and vega in options. Full valuation methods such as historical simulation handle these better.', 6),
  ('frm-market-risk-parametric-var-q08', 'frm-market-risk-parametric-var', 'The diversification benefit in a two-asset portfolio is largest when the correlation between the assets is:', '1.0', '0.5', '0.0', '-1.0', 'D', 'The diversification benefit is maximised at a correlation of -1.0, where the assets perfectly offset each other and portfolio VaR can theoretically be reduced to zero. The benefit decreases as correlation increases toward 1.', 7),
  ('frm-market-risk-historical-simulation-q01', 'frm-market-risk-historical-simulation', 'In standard historical simulation, VaR is estimated by applying which of the following to the current portfolio?', 'Randomly generated return scenarios from a fitted distribution', 'Monte Carlo paths generated using current market parameters', 'Stressed volatility inputs calibrated to a crisis period', 'Actual historical risk factor changes from a past observation window', 'D', 'Historical simulation replays actual past risk factor changes against today''s portfolio holdings to generate a P&L distribution, without assuming any specific return distribution.', 0),
  ('frm-market-risk-historical-simulation-q02', 'frm-market-risk-historical-simulation', 'A bank uses a 500-day historical simulation window to estimate 99% VaR. The 99% VaR corresponds to which observation in the ranked P&L distribution?', 'The 1st worst loss', 'The 5th worst loss', 'The 10th worst loss', 'The 25th worst loss', 'B', 'At 99% confidence with 500 observations, the worst 1% corresponds to 5 observations (500 x 0.01 = 5). The 99% VaR is typically read at the 5th worst loss.', 1),
  ('frm-market-risk-historical-simulation-q03', 'frm-market-risk-historical-simulation', 'Which feature of historical simulation makes it better suited than parametric VaR for portfolios containing options?', 'It employs full valuation, capturing nonlinear payoffs from gamma and vega', 'It uses a lower confidence level, reducing sensitivity to tail events', 'It assumes a fat-tailed distribution that matches option payoffs', 'It uses implied volatility rather than historical volatility', 'A', 'Historical simulation values the portfolio under each scenario using full pricing models, naturally capturing nonlinear exposures such as options gamma without relying on a linear delta approximation.', 2),
  ('frm-market-risk-historical-simulation-q04', 'frm-market-risk-historical-simulation', 'Age-weighted historical simulation addresses which limitation of standard historical simulation?', 'It assigns lower weight to older observations, improving responsiveness to recent conditions', 'It assumes normality for the central portion of the distribution', 'It gives equal weight to all past observations regardless of age', 'It eliminates the need for a historical data window by using risk factor proxies', 'A', 'Age-weighting uses exponential decay so that more recent observations have greater influence on the VaR estimate, making the model more responsive to current market volatility regimes.', 3),
  ('frm-market-risk-historical-simulation-q05', 'frm-market-risk-historical-simulation', 'Filtered historical simulation (FHS) improves on standard historical simulation primarily by:', 'Standardising historical returns by current GARCH volatility estimates before resampling', 'Extending the lookback window to capture a wider range of market conditions', 'Replacing historical scenarios with Monte Carlo simulations', 'Restricting the scenario set to stress periods only, removing benign market days', 'A', 'FHS scales historical returns by the ratio of current to past volatility (estimated via GARCH), so the resulting scenarios reflect both historical distributional shape and current volatility levels.', 4),
  ('frm-market-risk-historical-simulation-q06', 'frm-market-risk-historical-simulation', 'A key disadvantage of historical simulation compared to Monte Carlo simulation is that historical simulation:', 'Requires a distributional assumption about asset returns', 'Cannot capture fat tails or skewness in the return distribution', 'Is entirely backward-looking and cannot capture risks not present in the historical window', 'Overstates VaR because it uses stressed rather than normal market periods', 'C', 'Historical simulation is constrained by the scenarios in its lookback window. Risk from unprecedented events or structural breaks in market relationships will not appear in the P&L distribution.', 5),
  ('frm-market-risk-historical-simulation-q07', 'frm-market-risk-historical-simulation', 'Which of the following best describes the ''ghost feature'' problem in historical simulation?', 'Synthetic scenarios that appear in the distribution but never happened in reality', 'Overfitting of the GARCH model to recent volatility, inflating current VaR', 'A large historical loss that abruptly drops out of the VaR window after 250 days, causing a sudden VaR decrease', 'Correlation instability during market stress that is not captured in the historical window', 'C', 'The ghost feature refers to the mechanical jump in VaR when a large loss scenario from exactly one window-length ago rolls out of the observation window, causing an abrupt artificial drop in estimated VaR.', 6),
  ('frm-market-risk-historical-simulation-q08', 'frm-market-risk-historical-simulation', 'Compared to parametric VaR, historical simulation generally produces VaR estimates that:', 'Are always lower because they eliminate distributional assumptions', 'Better capture fat tails and non-normal return distributions observed in actual markets', 'Require more restrictive assumptions about the correlation structure of returns', 'Are less sensitive to extreme market events in the historical window', 'B', 'Because historical simulation uses actual past return data without a normality constraint, it naturally reflects the fat tails, skewness, and correlation patterns observed in real markets, which parametric VaR understates.', 7),
  ('frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall-q01', 'frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall', 'Expected Shortfall at the 95% confidence level is best defined as:', 'The 95th percentile of the loss distribution', 'The maximum loss observed in the worst 5% of scenarios', 'The probability-weighted loss across all scenarios in the distribution', 'The average loss given that the loss exceeds the 95% VaR', 'D', 'Expected Shortfall (ES) is the conditional expected loss, averaging across all outcomes that fall in the tail beyond the VaR threshold. It provides more information about the severity of tail losses than VaR alone.', 0),
  ('frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall-q02', 'frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall', 'Which of the four coherence axioms does VaR violate for non-normal distributions?', 'Monotonicity', 'Positive homogeneity', 'Translation invariance', 'Subadditivity', 'D', 'VaR fails subadditivity for non-normal distributions, meaning the VaR of a combined portfolio can exceed the sum of the individual VaRs. Expected Shortfall satisfies subadditivity and all other coherence axioms.', 1),
  ('frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall-q03', 'frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall', 'Under the Basel FRTB framework, the confidence level used for Expected Shortfall in the Internal Models Approach is:', '95% one-tailed', '99.9% one-tailed', '99% one-tailed', '97.5% one-tailed', 'D', 'FRTB replaced the pre-existing 99% VaR with a 97.5% ES measure. This captures more tail information than 99% VaR while maintaining a practically estimable confidence level.', 2),
  ('frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall-q04', 'frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall', 'An analyst computes a 99% VaR of $2 million and a 99% ES of $3.5 million for a portfolio. Which statement is correct?', 'VaR and ES should always be equal at the same confidence level', 'The ES being higher than VaR indicates the model has been mis-calibrated', 'ES understates tail risk because it ignores the shape of the tail', 'ES of $3.5 million represents the average loss in the worst 1% of scenarios', 'D', 'ES at 99% is the expected (average) loss conditional on losses exceeding the 99% VaR threshold. ES is always greater than or equal to VaR at the same confidence level because it averages losses that exceed VaR.', 3),
  ('frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall-q05', 'frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall', 'The subadditivity property of Expected Shortfall implies that for two portfolios A and B:', 'ES(A+B) = ES(A) + ES(B) in all cases', 'ES(A+B) is independent of the correlation between A and B', 'ES(A+B) >= ES(A) + ES(B)', 'ES(A+B) <= ES(A) + ES(B)', 'D', 'Subadditivity means the risk of a combined position cannot exceed the sum of individual risks, reflecting the principle that diversification should not be penalised. ES satisfies ES(A+B) <= ES(A) + ES(B).', 4),
  ('frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall-q06', 'frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall', 'A practical challenge with using Expected Shortfall for regulatory backtesting is that:', 'ES conditions on rare tail events, making it statistically difficult to backtest', 'ES is always equal to VaR at the same confidence level, making it redundant', 'ES cannot be computed from historical simulation, requiring Monte Carlo methods', 'ES violates translation invariance, making capital floor calculations unreliable', 'A', 'Backtesting ES is statistically challenging because it requires observing sufficient tail events (which are rare by definition) to determine whether the model correctly estimates the average loss beyond VaR.', 5),
  ('frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall-q07', 'frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall', 'Which of the following risk measures is coherent according to the Artzner et al. framework?', 'Standard deviation of portfolio returns', 'Maximum loss (worst-case scenario)', 'VaR under a normal distribution assumption', 'Expected Shortfall', 'D', 'Expected Shortfall satisfies all four coherence axioms: monotonicity, subadditivity, positive homogeneity, and translation invariance. VaR fails subadditivity for non-elliptical distributions and is therefore not coherent.', 6),
  ('frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall-q08', 'frm-market-risk-expected-shortfall', 'For a portfolio with a symmetric normal return distribution, how does 99% Expected Shortfall compare to 99% VaR?', 'ES equals VaR under normality', 'ES is higher than VaR because it averages losses beyond the VaR threshold', 'ES is lower than VaR because the tail is symmetric', 'The relationship depends entirely on portfolio size, not distribution shape', 'B', 'Even under normality, ES exceeds VaR at the same confidence level because ES averages all losses in the tail beyond the VaR cutoff, which are larger than the cutoff itself.', 7),
  ('frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital-q01', 'frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital', 'Under the FRTB Standardised Approach, the sensitivities-based method (SBM) captures which three types of risk sensitivity?', 'DV01, CS01, and FX delta', 'Delta, gamma, and rho', 'Duration, convexity, and vega', 'Delta, vega, and curvature', 'D', 'The FRTB SBM aggregates delta (linear sensitivity), vega (volatility sensitivity for options), and curvature (second-order risk not captured by delta, analogous to gamma) across prescribed risk classes.', 0),
  ('frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital-q02', 'frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital', 'Under FRTB backtesting, a bank''s VaR model receives 11 exceptions over a 250-day window. What consequence does this trigger?', 'The model is placed in the amber zone with a higher capital multiplier', 'Regulatory approval for the Internal Models Approach is revoked for that desk', 'The bank must immediately switch to the Standardised Approach', 'The bank must resubmit its model for approval with a 90-day remediation period', 'B', 'Ten or more exceptions in a 250-day window places the model in the red zone under FRTB backtesting rules, leading to revocation of IMA approval. The desk must then use the Standardised Approach.', 1),
  ('frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital-q03', 'frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital', 'Which of the following best describes a Non-Modellable Risk Factor (NMRF) under FRTB?', 'A risk factor that is excluded from the Internal Models Approach because it is too correlated with other factors', 'A risk factor for which the bank has insufficient verified price observations to calibrate a model', 'Any risk factor assigned to the trading book that is also present in the banking book', 'A risk factor that the regulator has designated as requiring a fixed capital charge', 'B', 'Under FRTB, a risk factor is modellable only if the bank can demonstrate sufficient real price observations over the preceding 12 months. Risk factors failing this test are NMRFs and must be capitalised using stress scenarios.', 2),
  ('frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital-q04', 'frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital', 'The liquidity horizon used for major currency pairs under FRTB Internal Models is:', '60 trading days', '20 trading days', '10 trading days', '120 trading days', 'C', 'FRTB assigns a 10-day liquidity horizon to large-cap equity and major FX risk factors, reflecting the assumption that these positions can be liquidated quickly. Less liquid risk factors receive longer horizons up to 120 days.', 3),
  ('frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital-q05', 'frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital', 'What is the primary regulatory purpose of backtesting a bank''s VaR model?', 'To confirm that the frequency of actual losses exceeding VaR is consistent with the model''s confidence level', 'To verify that the model produces the correct VaR at a 97.5% confidence level for ES calculation', 'To compare the bank''s VaR estimates against industry benchmarks from peer institutions', 'To ensure that the VaR model is calibrated to a stress period rather than normal market conditions', 'A', 'Backtesting checks whether the observed rate of VaR breaches in actual daily P&L is statistically consistent with the model''s stated confidence level. For a 99% model, exceptions should occur roughly 1% of the time.', 4),
  ('frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital-q06', 'frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital', 'Under pre-FRTB Basel 2.5, the market risk capital charge combined stressed VaR with which other component?', 'The Incremental Risk Charge and Comprehensive Risk Measure', 'Expected Shortfall at 97.5% confidence', 'The Standardised Approach output floor', 'A floor of three times the 10-day 99% VaR with a multiplier of 4', 'A', 'Basel 2.5 required banks to hold capital against Stressed VaR (SVaR) plus, for relevant portfolios, the Incremental Risk Charge (IRC) and the Comprehensive Risk Measure (CRM). FRTB replaced this patchwork with the unified ES-based framework.', 5),
  ('frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital-q07', 'frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital', 'A bank receives 7 VaR backtesting exceptions over a 250-day window. Under FRTB, this places the model in which zone?', 'Green zone — no additional capital required', 'Red zone — IMA approval is revoked', 'Amber zone — a scaling capital multiplier applies', 'Amber zone — the model must be rebuilt within 30 days', 'C', 'Five to nine exceptions fall in the amber zone under the FRTB traffic light system. The capital multiplier increases progressively from 1.5 toward 2.0, but IMA approval is retained. Red zone begins at 10 exceptions.', 6),
  ('frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital-q08', 'frm-market-risk-regulatory-capital', 'The FRTB Internal Models Approach requires Expected Shortfall to be computed at which confidence level to replace the pre-FRTB 99% VaR?', '99%', '95%', '97.5%', '99.9%', 'C', 'FRTB mandates ES at 97.5% one-tailed confidence, which regulators determined provides a broadly equivalent but more risk-sensitive capital charge compared to 99% VaR, while better capturing tail loss severity.', 7),
  ('frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives-q01', 'frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives', 'In a credit default swap, the protection buyer''s obligation is to:', 'Deliver the defaulted bond to the protection seller upon a credit event', 'Pay a periodic premium (CDS spread) to the protection seller', 'Compensate the protection seller for losses exceeding the notional amount', 'Post collateral equal to the notional amount of the contract', 'B', 'The protection buyer pays a periodic premium (the CDS spread, expressed in basis points per annum on the notional) to the protection seller in exchange for credit protection. The buyer stops paying upon a credit event or contract maturity.', 0),
  ('frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives-q02', 'frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives', 'If the recovery rate on a defaulted bond is 40%, the protection payment in a physically settled CDS is:', '40% of notional', '100% of notional minus accrued interest', '60% of notional', 'The full notional regardless of recovery', 'C', 'In a cash-settled CDS, the protection payment equals (1 - Recovery Rate) x Notional = (1 - 0.40) x Notional = 60% of notional. In physical settlement, the seller pays par and receives the defaulted bond worth approximately 40 cents.', 1),
  ('frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives-q03', 'frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives', 'Which of the following is NOT a standard ISDA credit event for a corporate CDS?', 'Failure to pay', 'Bankruptcy', 'Rating downgrade below investment grade', 'Restructuring', 'C', 'A credit rating downgrade is not an ISDA credit event. Standard corporate CDS credit events include failure to pay, bankruptcy, and restructuring. Some CDS contracts exclude restructuring, leading to ''no restructuring'' (NR) contracts common in North America.', 2),
  ('frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives-q04', 'frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives', 'The CDS spread on a 5-year contract for a company is 200 basis points. Assuming a recovery rate of 40%, the implied annual probability of default is approximately:', '2.0%', '5.0%', '3.3%', '12.0%', 'C', 'Using the approximation PD = CDS Spread / LGD, where LGD = 1 - 0.40 = 0.60: PD = 0.0200 / 0.60 = 3.33% per year. This is the annual risk-neutral default probability implied by the CDS market.', 3),
  ('frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives-q05', 'frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives', 'A portfolio manager holds $50 million of corporate bonds and buys $50 million notional of CDS protection on the same issuer. This position:', 'Creates a leveraged long credit exposure to the issuer', 'Generates a risk-free profit if the bond yield exceeds the CDS spread', 'Hedges the credit risk, leaving mainly interest rate risk on the bond', 'Is prohibited under Basel III as it creates circular credit risk exposures', 'C', 'Buying CDS protection on a bond held offsets the credit default risk. The residual exposure is primarily interest rate duration risk on the bond, since the CDS spread compensates for the credit component of the bond yield.', 4),
  ('frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives-q06', 'frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives', 'The ''premium leg'' of a CDS refers to:', 'The stream of periodic payments made by the protection buyer to the protection seller', 'The contingent payment made by the protection seller upon a credit event', 'The upfront payment made at initiation to reflect the difference between the contract spread and par spread', 'The accrued interest on the reference bond at the time of default', 'A', 'The premium leg consists of the periodic payments (the CDS spread multiplied by the notional and day count fraction) made by the protection buyer on scheduled payment dates until default or maturity.', 5),
  ('frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives-q07', 'frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives', 'CDX.NA.IG is best described as:', 'A CDS index referencing a standardised basket of North American investment-grade credits', 'A single-name CDS on the largest North American investment-grade issuer', 'A total return swap on a portfolio of North American high-yield bonds', 'A structured note that pays a coupon linked to North American credit spreads', 'A', 'CDX.NA.IG is a credit default swap index referencing 125 North American investment-grade entities. It allows investors to gain or hedge broad credit market exposure efficiently and is the North American equivalent of the European iTraxx Main index.', 6),
  ('frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives-q08', 'frm-credit-risk-credit-derivatives', 'If a protection seller in a CDS wants to close out their position before maturity without an assignment, they would most likely:', 'Novate the contract directly to the reference entity', 'Deliver the reference obligation to the protection buyer', 'Request early termination through a mandatory credit event trigger', 'Buy protection in an identical CDS contract, creating an offsetting position', 'D', 'A protection seller can offset their exposure by entering a new CDS as protection buyer on the same reference entity, maturity, and notional. This creates a matched book that offsets market risk, though it leaves residual counterparty credit risk.', 7),
  ('frm-credit-risk-securitisation-q01', 'frm-credit-risk-securitisation', 'In a securitisation waterfall, which tranche absorbs losses first?', 'Senior tranche', 'Mezzanine tranche', 'Equity (first-loss) tranche', 'Super-senior tranche', 'C', 'The equity tranche sits at the bottom of the capital structure and absorbs the first losses from the asset pool. This protects higher-rated tranches and is why the equity tranche commands the highest yield but carries the greatest risk.', 0),
  ('frm-credit-risk-securitisation-q02', 'frm-credit-risk-securitisation', 'The originate-to-distribute model is associated with which risk in securitisation?', 'Moral hazard, as originators may reduce underwriting standards when transferring credit risk to investors', 'Liquidity risk from holding long-dated assets funded with short-term liabilities', 'Market risk from changes in interest rates affecting the asset pool value', 'Operational risk from servicing a large number of individual loan accounts', 'A', 'When originators know they will sell the loans rather than hold them, incentives to maintain tight underwriting standards are weakened. This moral hazard problem was a key contributing factor to the deterioration of mortgage quality prior to the 2007-2009 crisis.', 1),
  ('frm-credit-risk-securitisation-q03', 'frm-credit-risk-securitisation', 'In a Collateralised Debt Obligation (CDO), the equity tranche value increases when asset default correlation increases because:', 'Higher correlation concentrates outcomes: either most assets survive (equity profits) or all default (equity is wiped out anyway)', 'Higher correlation means fewer total defaults, benefiting all tranches equally', 'Higher correlation reduces the variance of the pool''s loss distribution, benefiting the equity tranche''s expected return', 'The equity tranche receives priority distribution of interest income when correlations are high', 'A', 'At high correlation, defaults tend to cluster — either a few assets default (equity may survive) or many default simultaneously (equity is already wiped out). The equity tranche''s option-like payoff increases in value with the bimodal nature of high-correlation loss distributions.', 2),
  ('frm-credit-risk-securitisation-q04', 'frm-credit-risk-securitisation', 'In a synthetic CDO, exposure to the reference portfolio is obtained through:', 'Physical purchase of bonds and loans from the reference entities', 'Credit default swaps referencing the underlying assets', 'Total return swaps exchanging bond coupons for LIBOR payments', 'Repurchase agreements using the reference bonds as collateral', 'B', 'A synthetic CDO uses CDS contracts to gain credit exposure to a reference portfolio rather than physically purchasing the underlying bonds or loans, allowing rapid assembly of large and diversified reference pools.', 3),
  ('frm-credit-risk-securitisation-q05', 'frm-credit-risk-securitisation', 'A senior tranche in a securitisation achieves a AAA rating even when the underlying collateral is sub-investment grade primarily because of:', 'Government guarantees provided to protect senior bondholders from loss', 'The use of interest rate swaps to eliminate duration risk from the pool', 'Credit enhancement from subordinate tranches that absorb losses first', 'Diversification benefits from holding a large number of uncorrelated loans', 'C', 'Credit enhancement through subordination means the senior tranche is protected by all losses being absorbed by mezzanine and equity tranches before the senior is impaired. The thickness of this buffer, relative to expected pool losses, drives the senior tranche''s high credit rating.', 4),
  ('frm-credit-risk-securitisation-q06', 'frm-credit-risk-securitisation', 'Post-financial-crisis regulations require securitisation originators to retain a minimum economic interest in the securitised pool primarily to:', 'Reduce regulatory capital requirements for the originating bank', 'Align originator incentives with investor interests by keeping skin in the game', 'Ensure the originator maintains control over the servicing of the underlying loans', 'Comply with accounting rules requiring consolidation of the securitisation vehicle', 'B', 'Risk retention rules (requiring a minimum 5% economic interest in most jurisdictions) are designed to reduce the moral hazard of originate-to-distribute by ensuring originators share in the credit risk they create.', 5),
  ('frm-credit-risk-securitisation-q07', 'frm-credit-risk-securitisation', 'A CDO-squared is a securitisation that:', 'References tranches of existing CDOs rather than individual bonds or loans', 'Securitises two separate asset pools simultaneously under one structure', 'Doubles the coupon on a standard CDO through leverage', 'Provides two levels of subordination for the senior tranche', 'A', 'A CDO-squared holds tranches (typically mezzanine tranches) of other CDOs as its collateral. This creates a highly complex structure where the correlation assumptions and loss distributions compound across two layers of securitisation.', 6),
  ('frm-credit-risk-securitisation-q08', 'frm-credit-risk-securitisation', 'Which securitisation tranche is most adversely affected by an increase in asset default correlation?', 'Equity tranche', 'Mezzanine tranche', 'Senior tranche', 'All tranches are equally affected by correlation changes', 'C', 'The senior tranche suffers most from increasing default correlation because higher correlation raises the probability that many assets default simultaneously, potentially exhausting all subordinate tranches and reaching the senior. At low correlation, diversification protects the senior.', 7),
  ('frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk-q01', 'frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk', 'Potential Future Exposure (PFE) in counterparty credit risk is best defined as:', 'The current mark-to-market value of all derivative positions with a counterparty', 'The maximum exposure at a specified confidence level over a future time horizon', 'The probability-weighted average exposure across all future time steps', 'The total notional amount of derivative contracts outstanding with a counterparty', 'B', 'PFE is a high-percentile (often 95%) forward-looking measure of exposure, capturing the worst-case exposure at a given future date with a specified level of confidence. It is used for credit limit monitoring and capital calculations.', 0),
  ('frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk-q02', 'frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk', 'CVA is best described as:', 'The market value of the credit risk embedded in a derivative due to possible counterparty default', 'The regulatory capital charge for counterparty credit risk under Basel III', 'The collateral posted by a counterparty to reduce replacement cost exposure', 'The adjustment to VaR for bilateral netting agreements', 'A', 'Credit Valuation Adjustment (CVA) is the difference between the risk-free value of a derivative and its fair value accounting for counterparty default risk. It is the price the market assigns to the possibility that the counterparty defaults before maturity.', 1),
  ('frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk-q03', 'frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk', 'A bank has a portfolio of interest rate swaps with a counterparty. Current market values are: Swap A = +$5m, Swap B = -$2m, Swap C = +$1m. Under a bilateral netting agreement, the bank''s net current exposure is:', '$8 million (sum of positive values)', '$4 million (net positive exposure after netting)', '$3 million (only Swap A and C count)', '$6 million (sum of all absolute values minus netting)', 'B', 'Under netting, the net replacement cost is max(0, sum of all MTM values) = max(0, 5 - 2 + 1) = $4 million. Without netting, the bank could only claim the positive contracts ($6m total), while owing the $2m on Swap B.', 2),
  ('frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk-q04', 'frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk', 'Expected Positive Exposure (EPE) is used in the Basel regulatory capital calculation for counterparty credit risk because it:', 'Represents the worst-case exposure at a 99% confidence level over the trade life', 'Captures the time-averaged expected exposure, reflecting the average credit cost over the transaction', 'Equals the current exposure plus the potential future exposure at a 95% confidence level', 'Represents the exposure conditional on the counterparty defaulting at the peak exposure date', 'B', 'EPE is the time-weighted average of Expected Exposure (EE) profiles over the life of the transaction. Basel uses EPE as the basis for the effective expected exposure (Effective EPE) in the Internal Models Method capital calculation for CCR.', 3),
  ('frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk-q05', 'frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk', 'Wrong-way risk in counterparty credit risk occurs when:', 'The exposure to a counterparty decreases as the counterparty''s credit quality deteriorates', 'The exposure to a counterparty increases as the counterparty''s credit quality deteriorates', 'Collateral value declines independently of the counterparty''s credit standing', 'Netting sets produce a higher exposure than gross exposure due to correlation', 'B', 'Wrong-way risk exists when exposure and counterparty creditworthiness are adversely correlated — the bank''s exposure grows precisely when the counterparty is more likely to default, amplifying the expected loss. A classic example is buying protection from a counterparty correlated with the reference entity.', 4),
  ('frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk-q06', 'frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk', 'Under a Credit Support Annex (CSA), variation margin is exchanged to:', 'Cover the initial cost of entering into derivative contracts at inception', 'Satisfy regulatory requirements for central clearing of standardised derivatives', 'Provide a buffer against potential future losses in the event of counterparty default', 'Continuously reduce net counterparty exposure to reflect current market values', 'D', 'Variation margin under a CSA is exchanged daily (or at agreed intervals) to offset the current mark-to-market change in the derivative''s value, keeping net exposure close to zero and reducing counterparty credit risk.', 5),
  ('frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk-q07', 'frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk', 'Bilateral CVA (BCVA) extends unilateral CVA by also accounting for:', 'The credit risk of the reference entity in a CDS contract', 'The bank''s own default risk (DVA — Debt Valuation Adjustment)', 'The potential future exposure of the entire netting set', 'Market volatility contributions to expected exposure profiles', 'B', 'Bilateral CVA incorporates both CVA (expected loss if counterparty defaults) and DVA (gain to the bank if the bank itself defaults while the contract has negative value). DVA reflects the bank''s own credit risk embedded in its derivative liabilities.', 6),
  ('frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk-q08', 'frm-credit-risk-counterparty-credit-risk', 'Central clearing of OTC derivatives primarily reduces systemic counterparty credit risk by:', 'Eliminating all credit exposure between bilateral counterparties by requiring cash settlement', 'Mutualising and netting exposures through a central counterparty (CCP) with robust default management', 'Requiring the central counterparty to post initial margin equal to the full notional', 'Transferring credit risk to the government, which guarantees CCP obligations', 'B', 'A CCP interposes itself between buyer and seller, becoming the counterparty to both sides. By multilaterally netting exposures and requiring initial and variation margin, CCPs dramatically reduce bilateral CCR and the interconnectedness that causes systemic risk.', 7),
  ('frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital-q01', 'frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital', 'Under the Basel IRB approach, which parameter represents the fraction of the exposure that the bank expects to lose if a default occurs?', 'LGD (Loss Given Default)', 'M (Effective Maturity)', 'EAD (Exposure at Default)', 'PD (Probability of Default)', 'A', 'LGD is the percentage of the exposure expected to be lost after accounting for recoveries, collateral, and guarantee arrangements. It is expressed as (1 - Recovery Rate) and is central to computing expected and unexpected credit losses.', 0),
  ('frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital-q02', 'frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital', 'Under the Foundation IRB (F-IRB) approach, which credit risk parameter do banks estimate internally?', 'LGD only', 'EAD only', 'PD only', 'PD, LGD, and EAD', 'C', 'Under F-IRB, banks provide their own internal estimates of PD for each obligor grade, while LGD and EAD are set by supervisory rules. Under Advanced IRB, banks estimate all four parameters (PD, LGD, EAD, and M) internally.', 1),
  ('frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital-q03', 'frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital', 'The Basel III output floor for IRB approaches requires that IRB-based risk-weighted assets cannot fall below what percentage of Standardised Approach RWA?', '72.5%', '65%', '50%', '80%', 'A', 'The Basel IV output floor sets a floor of 72.5% of the Standardised Approach RWA for banks using internal models. This prevents excessive RWA reduction from internal models and is being phased in between 2025 and 2028.', 2),
  ('frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital-q04', 'frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital', 'Under the Basel Standardised Approach for credit risk, a corporate exposure rated AA- receives a risk weight of:', '20%', '0%', '50%', '100%', 'A', 'Under the Basel Standardised Approach, corporate exposures rated AAA to AA- receive a 20% risk weight, reflecting their high credit quality. Unrated corporates receive a 100% risk weight as the default treatment.', 3),
  ('frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital-q05', 'frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital', 'The IRB formula is based on the Vasicek single-factor model, which models credit losses assuming:', 'All obligors default independently with no common systematic risk factor', 'Default is driven by one common systematic risk factor plus idiosyncratic risk', 'Default correlation is fixed at a regulatory constant across all asset classes', 'LGD is perfectly correlated with PD across the economic cycle', 'B', 'The Vasicek model assumes each obligor''s asset value is driven by a single systematic factor (representing the state of the economy) and an idiosyncratic component. The IRB formula calibrates the supervisory correlation (rho) to reflect each asset class''s sensitivity to the systematic factor.', 4),
  ('frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital-q06', 'frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital', 'Exposure at Default (EAD) for an undrawn revolving credit facility is calculated as:', 'The currently drawn balance only, since the undrawn portion is at the borrower''s discretion', 'The full committed facility limit, regardless of current utilisation', 'Zero, as undrawn commitments carry no credit risk until drawn', 'The drawn balance plus a credit conversion factor (CCF) applied to the undrawn commitment', 'D', 'EAD for revolving facilities includes the current drawn balance plus the undrawn commitment multiplied by a Credit Conversion Factor (CCF), which estimates the proportion of undrawn commitments likely to be drawn by the time of default.', 5),
  ('frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital-q07', 'frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital', 'Under the Basel IRB approach, a longer effective maturity (M) for a credit exposure results in:', 'A lower risk weight, as longer maturity implies a more established borrower', 'A lower risk weight due to discounting of distant future cash flows', 'No change to the risk weight, as maturity is not a parameter in the IRB formula', 'A higher risk weight, reflecting greater uncertainty and migration risk over time', 'D', 'The IRB maturity adjustment increases the risk weight for longer-maturity exposures to reflect the greater probability of credit quality migration (downgrade or default) over the exposure''s life. The adjustment is applied as a multiplier to the base capital requirement.', 6),
  ('frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital-q08', 'frm-credit-risk-regulatory-capital', 'The minimum Pillar 1 capital ratio under Basel III requires banks to hold Common Equity Tier 1 (CET1) capital of at least what percentage of risk-weighted assets?', '2%', '4.5%', '6%', '8%', 'B', 'Basel III requires a minimum CET1 ratio of 4.5% of RWA. The total Tier 1 minimum is 6% and total capital (Tier 1 + Tier 2) is 8%. Including the capital conservation buffer of 2.5%, the effective CET1 target is 7%.', 7),
  ('frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution-q01', 'frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution', 'In the Loss Distribution Approach, which distribution is most commonly used to model the frequency of operational loss events?', 'Normal distribution', 'Exponential distribution', 'Poisson distribution', 'Beta distribution', 'C', 'The Poisson distribution is the standard choice for event frequency in LDA because it models count data with a single parameter (lambda) representing the expected number of events per period.', 0),
  ('frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution-q02', 'frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution', 'Which severity distribution is preferred in LDA primarily because it accommodates a heavy right tail and is defined only for positive values?', 'Normal distribution', 'Uniform distribution', 'Student-t distribution', 'Lognormal distribution', 'D', 'The lognormal distribution is favoured for operational loss severities because it has positive support and its heavy right tail captures the rare catastrophic losses that dominate capital requirements.', 1),
  ('frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution-q03', 'frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution', 'The process of combining a frequency distribution and a severity distribution to derive the aggregate loss distribution is known as:', 'Calibration', 'Convolution', 'Bootstrapping', 'Deconvolution', 'B', 'Convolution (typically implemented via Monte Carlo simulation) combines the frequency and severity distributions to produce the aggregate annual loss distribution from which capital is measured.', 2),
  ('frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution-q04', 'frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution', 'Under the Basel II Advanced Measurement Approach, the regulatory operational risk capital charge is set at which percentile of the aggregate loss distribution?', '95th percentile', '97.5th percentile', '99th percentile', '99.9th percentile', 'D', 'The AMA requires banks to hold capital equal to the 99.9th percentile (one-year) aggregate loss, consistent with the Basel II target solvency standard for operational risk.', 3),
  ('frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution-q05', 'frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution', 'A bank finds that the variance of its annual loss event count exceeds the mean. Which frequency distribution is more appropriate than the Poisson?', 'Negative binomial distribution', 'Binomial distribution', 'Geometric distribution', 'Hypergeometric distribution', 'A', 'The negative binomial distribution relaxes the Poisson assumption of equal mean and variance, accommodating overdispersion (variance greater than mean) seen in many operational loss datasets.', 4),
  ('frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution-q06', 'frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution', 'Under LDA data requirements, scenario analysis is used primarily to:', 'Capture low-frequency, high-impact tail events', 'Estimate expected loss for routine events', 'Replace internal loss data entirely', 'Determine the frequency parameter for the Poisson model', 'A', 'Scenario analysis supplements internal data by providing expert judgment on extreme but plausible events that rarely appear in historical records, ensuring the tail of the severity distribution is adequately calibrated.', 5),
  ('frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution-q07', 'frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution', 'Basel III/IV replaced the Advanced Measurement Approach with which standardised method for operational risk capital?', 'Basic Indicator Approach', 'Standardised Approach (SA)', 'Standardised Measurement Approach (SMA)', 'Internal Ratings-Based Approach', 'C', 'The Standardised Measurement Approach (SMA) replaced all earlier operational risk approaches under Basel IV, combining a business indicator component with a bank''s own loss history in a prescribed formula.', 6),
  ('frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution-q08', 'frm-operational-risk-loss-distribution', 'External loss data is incorporated into LDA mainly to:', 'Reduce the need for internal data collection', 'Enrich the tail of the severity distribution with industry events', 'Satisfy regulatory disclosure requirements', 'Determine the mean of the frequency distribution', 'B', 'External loss data from industry consortia (e.g., ORX) provide observations of large-scale losses that are too rare to appear in a single bank''s own history, improving tail calibration.', 7),
  ('frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators-q01', 'frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators', 'Which of the following best describes a Risk Control Self-Assessment (RCSA)?', 'A process where business units identify risks and evaluate control effectiveness', 'A statistical model that forecasts future losses from historical data', 'A regulatory capital calculation method replacing internal models', 'An audit of financial statements for compliance purposes', 'A', 'RCSA is a forward-looking process in which business lines systematically identify their risks, rate their controls, and determine residual exposure, feeding into the broader operational risk framework.', 0),
  ('frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators-q02', 'frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators', 'A KRI that measures the number of failed trade settlements per month is most directly linked to which risk category?', 'People risk', 'Process risk', 'Legal risk', 'Strategic risk', 'B', 'Failed settlements typically result from breakdowns in operational processes such as trade capture, matching, or instruction transmission, making this a process risk indicator.', 1),
  ('frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators-q03', 'frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators', 'In an RCSA heat map, which cell combination would typically be assigned a Red rating?', 'Low likelihood, low impact', 'Low likelihood, medium impact', 'High likelihood, low impact', 'High likelihood, high impact', 'D', 'A heat map assigns the highest risk rating (Red) to scenarios with both high likelihood and high impact, indicating an unacceptable residual risk that demands immediate mitigation.', 2),
  ('frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators-q04', 'frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators', 'Which of the following is NOT a characteristic of a well-designed KRI?', 'Backward-looking, based only on past losses', 'Predictive of future risk events', 'Measurable and quantifiable', 'Timely and reported at an appropriate frequency', 'A', 'Effective KRIs are designed to be forward-looking and predictive; purely backward-looking loss measures are lagging indicators, not true key risk indicators.', 3),
  ('frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators-q05', 'frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators', 'When a KRI breaches its amber threshold, the appropriate response is to:', 'Immediately halt all related business activities', 'No action is required until red threshold is breached', 'Escalate directly to the board without management involvement', 'Notify management and monitor the situation closely', 'D', 'An amber breach signals elevated risk requiring management attention and closer monitoring; a red breach triggers escalation to senior risk committees, while amber allows time to investigate and respond before escalation.', 4),
  ('frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators-q06', 'frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators', 'The RCSA process scores ''inherent risk'' before considering controls. This represents:', 'The risk remaining after all controls are applied', 'The regulatory capital charge for operational risk', 'The risk transferred to insurance or third parties', 'The risk that exists in the absence of any mitigating controls', 'D', 'Inherent risk is the gross risk level that would exist if no controls were in place; subtracting the effect of controls gives the residual risk that management must accept or further mitigate.', 5),
  ('frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators-q07', 'frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators', 'High staff turnover in a key control function is an example of which type of operational risk KRI?', 'System availability KRI', 'People risk KRI', 'External fraud KRI', 'Legal and compliance KRI', 'B', 'Staff turnover directly affects the quality of control execution and institutional knowledge, making it a leading indicator of people risk within operational risk management.', 6),
  ('frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators-q08', 'frm-operational-risk-key-risk-indicators', 'Which statement best explains why KRIs and RCSA complement loss data in an operational risk framework?', 'They replace internal loss data when the AMA is used', 'They are required only for Pillar 3 disclosure purposes', 'They provide a forward-looking view, capturing risk before losses occur', 'They measure market risk exposures that feed into op risk capital', 'C', 'Loss data is inherently backward-looking; KRIs and RCSA add a prospective dimension by flagging deteriorating controls and rising risk environments before actual losses materialise.', 7),
  ('frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk-q01', 'frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk', 'Which type of cyber attack encrypts a victim''s data and demands payment for the decryption key?', 'Ransomware', 'Phishing', 'DDoS', 'SQL injection', 'A', 'Ransomware is malicious software that encrypts files or systems and extorts payment for restoration, posing severe operational and reputational risk to financial institutions.', 0),
  ('frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk-q02', 'frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk', 'A Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attack primarily aims to:', 'Steal sensitive customer data', 'Install spyware on employee devices', 'Overwhelm systems with traffic to cause service outages', 'Intercept communications between counterparties', 'C', 'DDoS attacks flood target systems with massive volumes of requests, exhausting capacity and making services unavailable to legitimate users, disrupting critical banking operations.', 1),
  ('frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk-q03', 'frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk', 'The NIST Cybersecurity Framework organises cyber risk management into five functions. Which of the following is NOT one of them?', 'Identify', 'Protect', 'Recover', 'Transfer', 'D', 'The five NIST CSF functions are Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, and Recover. Transfer is a risk treatment option but not one of the framework''s core functions.', 2),
  ('frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk-q04', 'frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk', 'Which probabilistic framework is commonly used to quantify cyber risk in monetary terms?', 'GARCH model', 'Black-Scholes model', 'FAIR (Factor Analysis of Information Risk)', 'Vasicek credit model', 'C', 'The FAIR model provides a structured, probabilistic method for estimating cyber loss exposure in monetary terms, enabling comparison with other operational risks and informing cyber insurance decisions.', 3),
  ('frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk-q05', 'frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk', 'A supply chain cyber attack differs from a direct attack in that it:', 'Exploits compromised third-party software or vendors to reach the target', 'Targets the bank''s trading systems exclusively', 'Requires physical access to the target''s data centre', 'Only affects publicly listed companies', 'A', 'Supply chain attacks compromise a trusted vendor or software provider as an entry point, allowing attackers to reach target organisations that may have strong direct defences but insufficient third-party controls.', 4),
  ('frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk-q06', 'frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk', 'Spear-phishing differs from generic phishing primarily because it:', 'Targets only external customers rather than employees', 'Is highly personalised and targeted at specific individuals', 'Uses malware rather than deceptive communications', 'Requires the attacker to be physically present at the institution', 'B', 'Spear-phishing uses personalised information about the target (name, role, colleagues) to make deceptive communications more convincing, significantly increasing success rates compared to mass phishing campaigns.', 5),
  ('frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk-q07', 'frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk', 'A primary regulatory expectation regarding cyber risk at the board level is that boards should:', 'Oversee cyber risk as part of the overall risk governance framework', 'Outsource all cyber risk management to specialist firms', 'Personally conduct penetration testing of systems', 'Limit cyber disclosures to avoid market sensitivity', 'A', 'Regulators require boards to provide oversight and governance of cyber risk, ensuring it is embedded in the risk management framework rather than treated solely as a technical IT matter.', 6),
  ('frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk-q08', 'frm-operational-risk-cyber-technology-risk', 'Why is cyber risk particularly difficult to quantify using standard statistical methods?', 'Cyber losses are always below reporting thresholds', 'Loss data are sparse and cyber events tend to be correlated across institutions', 'Regulators prohibit the use of statistical models for cyber risk', 'Cyber risk only affects reputational value, which cannot be measured', 'B', 'The scarcity of historical cyber loss data and the potential for simultaneous correlated losses across institutions (e.g., from a widespread infrastructure attack) make standard statistical calibration unreliable.', 7),
  ('frm-operational-risk-business-continuity-q01', 'frm-operational-risk-business-continuity', 'What is the primary distinction between a Business Continuity Plan (BCP) and a Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)?', 'BCP focuses on sustaining critical business functions; DRP focuses on restoring IT systems', 'BCP applies only to natural disasters, while DRP applies to cyber incidents', 'DRP is a broader plan that encompasses all elements of BCP', 'BCP is required by regulation, while DRP is voluntary', 'A', 'BCP covers all critical business operations and their continuity during disruptions, while DRP is a subset focused specifically on recovering IT infrastructure and data.', 0),
  ('frm-operational-risk-business-continuity-q02', 'frm-operational-risk-business-continuity', 'A bank''s payment processing system has an RTO of 4 hours. This means the system must be:', 'Fully restored and operational within 4 hours of a disruption', 'Backed up every 4 hours', 'Tested for failures no more than 4 times per year', 'Available 4 hours per day during a crisis', 'A', 'The Recovery Time Objective (RTO) defines the maximum acceptable downtime; an RTO of 4 hours means business continuity plans must restore the system within that window.', 1),
  ('frm-operational-risk-business-continuity-q03', 'frm-operational-risk-business-continuity', 'Recovery Point Objective (RPO) measures:', 'The maximum tolerable data loss expressed in time', 'The time required to restore normal operations', 'The cost of implementing backup systems', 'The frequency of BCP testing exercises', 'A', 'RPO defines how much data (in terms of time elapsed since the last backup) the organisation can afford to lose; a 2-hour RPO means backups must be taken at least every 2 hours.', 2),
  ('frm-operational-risk-business-continuity-q04', 'frm-operational-risk-business-continuity', 'Under the concept of operational resilience, regulators require institutions to define:', 'The maximum profit target during a crisis period', 'Impact tolerances for important business services', 'Minimum capital buffers for technology failures', 'Insurance coverage levels for operational losses', 'B', 'Operational resilience regulation requires firms to identify their important business services and set impact tolerances - the maximum level of disruption they can accept before harm to customers or financial stability occurs.', 3),
  ('frm-operational-risk-business-continuity-q05', 'frm-operational-risk-business-continuity', 'Which type of BCP test involves a live switchover to backup systems without simulating a real event?', 'Tabletop exercise', 'Simulation exercise', 'Full failover test', 'Document review', 'C', 'A full failover test actually switches production operations to backup systems, providing the most realistic validation that recovery capabilities work as planned under genuine operational conditions.', 4),
  ('frm-operational-risk-business-continuity-q06', 'frm-operational-risk-business-continuity', 'A Crisis Management Team (CMT) in a financial institution typically includes representatives from:', 'Only the IT department and risk management', 'Business, IT, legal, communications, and risk functions', 'Regulators and external auditors', 'Front-office trading desks exclusively', 'B', 'Effective crisis management requires cross-functional representation, as a major operational disruption demands coordinated responses across business operations, technology recovery, legal obligations, regulatory communication, and public relations.', 5),
  ('frm-operational-risk-business-continuity-q07', 'frm-operational-risk-business-continuity', 'Tabletop exercises in BCP testing are best described as:', 'Discussion-based walkthroughs of crisis scenarios with key personnel', 'Physical rehearsals that simulate actual system failures', 'Automated software tests of backup system recovery times', 'Annual reviews of the written BCP document', 'A', 'Tabletop exercises are structured discussions where participants talk through responses to hypothetical crisis scenarios, identifying gaps in plans without disrupting operations or switching to backup systems.', 6),
  ('frm-operational-risk-business-continuity-q08', 'frm-operational-risk-business-continuity', 'The operational resilience approach differs from traditional BCP primarily because it:', 'Focuses only on technology recovery rather than business functions', 'Is voluntary and not subject to regulatory oversight', 'Replaces the need for disaster recovery planning', 'Emphasises the ability to adapt and recover, including from events not specifically anticipated', 'D', 'Operational resilience goes beyond traditional BCP by requiring firms to absorb and adapt to a wide range of disruptions - including unanticipated ones - rather than just executing predefined recovery scripts.', 7),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity-q01', 'frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity', 'The Liquidity Coverage Ratio (LCR) requires banks to hold sufficient HQLA to survive a stress scenario lasting how long?', '7 days', '14 days', '90 days', '30 days', 'D', 'The LCR is calibrated to a 30-day stress scenario; banks must hold HQLA equal to or exceeding net cash outflows over that period, with a minimum ratio of 100%.', 0),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity-q02', 'frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity', 'Which of the following is classified as Level 1 HQLA under the LCR framework?', 'Investment-grade corporate bonds with a 15% haircut', 'Cash and central bank reserves', 'Covered bonds rated AA or above', 'Equities included in major indices', 'B', 'Level 1 HQLA includes cash, central bank reserves, and sovereign bonds of zero risk-weight, all recognised at 100% of value with no haircut applied.', 1),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity-q03', 'frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity', 'The Net Stable Funding Ratio (NSFR) is designed to address which dimension of liquidity risk?', 'Intraday settlement risk in payment systems', 'Short-term market liquidity for trading positions', 'Structural funding mismatches over a one-year horizon', 'Credit risk in the loan book', 'C', 'The NSFR addresses structural funding stability over a one-year horizon, requiring the amount of stable funding to meet or exceed required stable funding across all asset categories.', 2),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity-q04', 'frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity', 'In the NSFR formula, which funding source would typically receive the highest Available Stable Funding (ASF) weight?', 'Overnight interbank borrowing', 'Equity capital and long-term debt (maturity > 1 year)', 'Retail deposits with maturities under 1 year', 'Secured short-term borrowing backed by non-HQLA', 'B', 'Equity and long-term debt (maturity exceeding one year) receive an ASF factor of 100%, reflecting their stability as permanent or long-dated funding sources that will not need refinancing within the stress horizon.', 3),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity-q05', 'frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity', 'Intraday liquidity refers to funds needed to:', 'Fund the bank''s overnight repo book', 'Cover margin calls on derivative positions over 30 days', 'Meet payment and securities settlement obligations during the business day', 'Satisfy the NSFR requirement on a same-day basis', 'C', 'Intraday liquidity is the cash required to settle payment obligations in real-time gross settlement systems throughout the trading day, and peaks can differ substantially from end-of-day positions.', 4),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity-q06', 'frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity', 'A bank''s LCR is calculated as 85%. This means the bank:', 'Holds 15% more HQLA than required', 'Has met the NSFR minimum requirement', 'Has a 15% surplus over net cash outflows', 'Fails to meet the minimum 100% LCR requirement', 'D', 'An LCR below 100% indicates the bank''s HQLA is insufficient to cover projected net cash outflows over the 30-day stress period, representing a shortfall requiring corrective action.', 5),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity-q07', 'frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity', 'Central bank standing facilities serve which primary role in a bank''s liquidity management?', 'A primary source of day-to-day funding to minimise HQLA holdings', 'A backstop source of liquidity when market funding is unavailable', 'A mechanism to transfer liquidity risk to the public sector', 'A tool for generating income from idle reserve balances', 'B', 'Central bank facilities act as a lender-of-last-resort backstop; while available, regulators expect banks to maintain adequate liquidity buffers independently rather than relying on central bank access as a primary funding source.', 6),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity-q08', 'frm-liquidity-risk-funding-liquidity', 'Which statement about LCR net cash outflows is correct?', 'Different deposit types are assigned different regulatory run-off rates', 'Committed credit lines are excluded from outflow calculations', 'All deposits are assumed to run off at 100% in the 30-day stress', 'Inflows and outflows are measured at nominal value without any caps', 'A', 'The LCR framework prescribes specific run-off rates by deposit type (e.g., stable retail deposits at 3%, less stable at 10%, unsecured wholesale at higher rates) reflecting their likelihood of withdrawal under stress.', 7),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity-q01', 'frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity', 'The bid-ask spread in a financial market represents:', 'The annual fee charged by brokers for holding positions', 'The minimum margin required to hold a leveraged position', 'The difference between the highest buy price and lowest sell price offered by market-makers', 'The difference between the opening and closing price of an asset', 'C', 'The bid-ask spread is the gap between the market-maker''s bid (buying price) and ask (selling price), representing the immediate round-trip transaction cost and a primary measure of market liquidity.', 0),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity-q02', 'frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity', 'Liquidity-Adjusted VaR (LVaR) differs from standard VaR because it:', 'Uses a shorter confidence interval to be more conservative', 'Replaces historical simulation with Monte Carlo methods', 'Adds the estimated cost of unwinding positions to the standard VaR', 'Measures funding liquidity risk rather than market risk', 'C', 'LVaR augments standard VaR by incorporating the bid-ask spread cost (and price impact for large positions), reflecting that liquidating a portfolio in stress costs more than simply marking to mid-market prices.', 1),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity-q03', 'frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity', 'A deep market is characterised by:', 'Large volume of orders at multiple price levels absorbing trades with minimal impact', 'Thin order books with few resting orders at each price', 'A wide bid-ask spread reflecting high transaction costs', 'High short-term price volatility and frequent price gaps', 'A', 'Market depth refers to the ability to absorb large orders without significant price movement; deep markets have substantial order volume at each price level, minimising the price impact of any individual trade.', 2),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity-q04', 'frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity', 'The Amihud illiquidity ratio is calculated as:', 'Bid-ask spread divided by asset price', 'Absolute daily return divided by daily dollar trading volume', 'Daily volume divided by market capitalisation', 'Price impact multiplied by position size', 'B', 'The Amihud ratio equals the absolute return divided by dollar volume, capturing how much prices move per dollar of trading volume - a higher ratio signals greater illiquidity and price impact.', 3),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity-q05', 'frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity', 'During a market stress event, the liquidity risk premium typically:', 'Narrows as investors seek safe assets', 'Stays constant because it is calibrated over long periods', 'Spikes, driving illiquid asset prices down and amplifying losses', 'Becomes irrelevant as central banks provide unlimited liquidity', 'C', 'In stress, investors demand much higher compensation for holding illiquid assets, causing their prices to fall sharply - a liquidity risk premium spike that amplifies losses beyond what fundamental value changes would imply.', 4),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity-q06', 'frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity', 'For a large position, the liquidity cost in LVaR must account for price impact because:', 'Large positions always involve structured products requiring specialist valuation', 'Regulators require a fixed price impact add-on for positions above a threshold', 'Unwinding a large order moves the market against the seller, worsening execution prices', 'Price impact only affects the bid but not the ask price', 'C', 'Selling a large block of securities into the market absorbs available bids, pushing the price down before the full position is liquidated; this adverse price impact must be included in the liquidity cost estimate.', 5),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity-q07', 'frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity', 'Which asset would typically have the narrowest bid-ask spread?', 'A small-cap emerging market equity', 'A structured credit product with limited secondary market', 'An on-the-run US Treasury bond', 'A real estate investment with infrequent appraisals', 'C', 'On-the-run US Treasury bonds are among the most actively traded and liquid securities in the world, with very narrow bid-ask spreads due to high volume, standardised structure, and broad market participation.', 6),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity-q08', 'frm-liquidity-risk-market-liquidity', 'The standard VaR formula assumes positions can be liquidated at mid-market prices. This assumption is most problematic when:', 'Markets are highly liquid and trading volumes are elevated', 'Positions are small relative to average daily trading volume', 'The holding period used in VaR exceeds 10 days', 'Positions are large relative to market depth and markets are stressed', 'D', 'The mid-market pricing assumption breaks down most severely when positions are large relative to available liquidity, particularly during stress when market depth shrinks; in such cases LVaR is essential.', 7),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing-q01', 'frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing', 'The survival horizon in a liquidity stress test is defined as:', 'The maximum holding period for HQLA before they must be sold', 'The period over which the bank can meet all obligations using available liquid assets under stress', 'The time required to restore normal funding conditions after a crisis', 'The duration of the historical stress period used to calibrate the test', 'B', 'The survival horizon is the forward-looking period during which the bank projects it can remain solvent and liquid using its buffer, even if wholesale funding markets are closed and deposits are running off at stressed rates.', 0),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing-q02', 'frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing', 'A combined stress scenario in liquidity stress testing is designed to capture:', 'Only market-wide funding freezes similar to the 2008 financial crisis', 'Only bank-specific events such as rating downgrades', 'Normal business conditions with a 10% haircut on all assets', 'Both idiosyncratic and market-wide stresses occurring simultaneously', 'D', 'The combined scenario - the most severe in liquidity stress testing - overlaps a bank-specific crisis with a market-wide funding disruption, testing whether the buffer is adequate when multiple stresses occur together.', 1),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing-q03', 'frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing', 'Which of the following would be a stressed cash outflow item in a liquidity stress test?', 'Contractual loan repayments received from borrowers', 'Maturing securities held in the HQLA portfolio', 'Additional collateral required on derivative contracts due to a rating downgrade', 'Dividend income from equity investments', 'C', 'A rating downgrade triggers contractual collateral top-up clauses on derivative transactions, representing a contingent cash outflow that must be captured in the stressed outflow projection.', 2),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing-q04', 'frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing', 'The liquidity buffer in stress testing must consist of:', 'Unencumbered HQLA that can be monetised rapidly without significant haircut in stress', 'Any assets on the balance sheet including illiquid loans', 'Committed credit lines from other financial institutions', 'Regulatory capital in excess of minimum requirements', 'A', 'The liquidity buffer must comprise unencumbered HQLA - assets that are free from legal or contractual restrictions and can be converted to cash quickly even under stressed market conditions.', 3),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing-q05', 'frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing', 'ILAAP stands for Internal Liquidity Adequacy Assessment Process and is part of which Basel pillar?', 'Pillar 2 - Supervisory Review Process', 'Pillar 1 - Minimum Capital Requirements', 'Pillar 3 - Market Discipline', 'Pillar 4 - Macroprudential Overlay', 'A', 'ILAAP is a Pillar 2 requirement under Basel III; banks conduct their own internal assessment of liquidity adequacy, and supervisors review and challenge it, potentially imposing additional liquidity requirements.', 4),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing-q06', 'frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing', 'An idiosyncratic liquidity stress scenario would typically include which assumption?', 'All banks simultaneously losing access to interbank markets', 'Central bank withdrawal of emergency liquidity facilities', 'A sovereign debt crisis affecting multiple country markets', 'A bank-specific reputational event causing retail deposit withdrawals', 'D', 'An idiosyncratic scenario models stresses unique to the individual institution - such as a rating downgrade, fraud announcement, or loss event - that damage its reputation and trigger deposit outflows or funding withdrawal.', 5),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing-q07', 'frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing', 'Net cumulative outflow profiling in a liquidity stress test helps management identify:', 'The regulatory capital charge for operational risk', 'The point in time when the liquidity buffer would be exhausted under stress', 'The optimal mix of funding instruments for the balance sheet', 'The credit rating sensitivity of wholesale funding costs', 'B', 'By projecting cumulative net outflows over the survival horizon, management can identify when (and if) the buffer runs out, enabling targeted action to extend the survival horizon above the regulatory minimum.', 6),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing-q08', 'frm-liquidity-risk-stress-testing', 'If a supervisor finds a bank''s internal stress scenarios insufficiently severe, what action can the supervisor take?', 'Issue a public fine but cannot change the bank''s internal model', 'Require immediate closure of the bank', 'Impose a Pillar 2 liquidity add-on to the minimum requirement', 'Transfer the bank''s HQLA to a ring-fenced fund', 'C', 'Under the ILAAP Pillar 2 framework, supervisors can impose institution-specific liquidity add-ons if internal stress test scenarios or buffers are deemed inadequate relative to the bank''s actual risk profile.', 7),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-alm-q01', 'frm-liquidity-risk-alm', 'In gap analysis, a positive repricing gap indicates that:', 'More assets than liabilities reprice in a given time bucket, benefiting from rising rates', 'Liabilities reprice faster than assets, benefiting from rising rates', 'The bank''s net interest margin is negative', 'The bank has more fixed-rate liabilities than variable-rate assets', 'A', 'A positive gap (rate-sensitive assets exceed rate-sensitive liabilities) means net interest income rises when interest rates increase, as more assets are re-priced upward than liabilities.', 0),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-alm-q02', 'frm-liquidity-risk-alm', 'The duration gap is defined as:', 'Duration of assets minus duration of liabilities', 'Duration of liabilities minus duration of assets', 'Duration of assets minus (Liabilities/Assets) multiplied by duration of liabilities', 'The weighted average maturity of the asset portfolio', 'C', 'Duration gap = Duration(A) - (L/A) x Duration(L), where the liabilities-to-assets ratio scales the liability duration to reflect the leverage of equity, capturing the net interest rate sensitivity of economic value.', 1),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-alm-q03', 'frm-liquidity-risk-alm', 'A positive duration gap means that when interest rates rise, the economic value of equity will:', 'Increase, because asset values rise faster than liability values', 'Decrease, because asset values fall more than liability values', 'Remain unchanged, because duration gap is immunised', 'Increase, because liabilities reprice faster than assets', 'B', 'With a positive duration gap, assets have longer duration than liabilities; rising rates reduce asset prices more than liability prices in present-value terms, causing the economic value of equity to fall.', 2),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-alm-q04', 'frm-liquidity-risk-alm', 'Net Interest Income (NII) sensitivity analysis is considered a short-term ALM measure because:', 'It is only relevant for banks with overnight deposit funding', 'It only captures floating-rate instruments, ignoring fixed-rate positions', 'Regulatory rules prohibit its use beyond a quarterly reporting period', 'It measures the earnings impact over a 1-2 year horizon, missing long-term present-value effects', 'D', 'NII sensitivity captures the near-term earnings impact of rate changes on currently repricing instruments, but it misses the long-term present-value effects on fixed-rate positions that EVE analysis captures.', 3),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-alm-q05', 'frm-liquidity-risk-alm', 'Under Basel IRRBB standards, banks are required to disclose EVE sensitivity to a standard interest rate shock of:', '50 basis points parallel shift', '100 basis points parallel shift', '500 basis points parallel shift', '200 basis points parallel shift', 'D', 'Basel IRRBB guidelines require disclosure of EVE change under a standard 200bp parallel interest rate shift, providing a consistent basis for supervisory comparison across institutions.', 4),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-alm-q06', 'frm-liquidity-risk-alm', 'Duration matching as an immunisation strategy aims to:', 'Maximise net interest income regardless of rate movements', 'Make the present value of assets and liabilities equally sensitive to interest rate changes', 'Eliminate all repricing gaps across every time bucket', 'Ensure all assets and liabilities mature on the same date', 'B', 'Duration matching sets the duration gap to zero, so that a change in interest rates has equal present-value effects on assets and liabilities, leaving equity value unchanged - the classic immunisation condition.', 5),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-alm-q07', 'frm-liquidity-risk-alm', 'A bank with predominantly long-term fixed-rate mortgage assets funded by short-term deposits can use interest rate swaps to reduce duration gap by:', 'Buying put options on interest rates to cap borrowing costs', 'Paying fixed and receiving floating on a swap, further extending asset duration', 'Entering a currency swap to convert foreign currency exposures', 'Receiving fixed and paying floating on a swap, shortening the effective asset duration', 'D', 'By receiving fixed on a swap, the bank synthetically converts its fixed-rate mortgage income into floating, reducing the effective duration of the asset side and narrowing the positive duration gap.', 6),
  ('frm-liquidity-risk-alm-q08', 'frm-liquidity-risk-alm', 'The Asset-Liability Committee (ALCO) is primarily responsible for:', 'Setting individual credit limits for corporate loan customers', 'Conducting internal audits of trading desk compliance', 'Approving new financial products for retail customers', 'Overseeing the management of interest rate risk and liquidity risk on the balance sheet', 'D', 'ALCO oversees the structural interest rate risk and liquidity risk inherent in the balance sheet, setting policies, reviewing ALM metrics (NII, EVE, LCR, NSFR), and directing hedging or funding strategies.', 7),
  ('frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk-q01', 'frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk', 'A hedge fund holds illiquid distressed debt positions but offers investors monthly redemptions. This situation is best described as which type of risk?', 'Liquidity mismatch risk', 'Leverage risk', 'Manager risk', 'Operational risk', 'A', 'Liquidity mismatch risk arises when a fund''s asset liquidity is shorter than its redemption terms, potentially forcing fire sales of illiquid positions during stress. This structural mismatch is a defining vulnerability for certain hedge fund strategies.', 0),
  ('frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk-q02', 'frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk', 'Which hedge fund strategy is most directly exposed to the simultaneous risk of credit spread widening and a decline in equity volatility?', 'Global macro', 'Long/short equity', 'Convertible arbitrage', 'Statistical arbitrage', 'C', 'Convertible arbitrage profits from mispricing between convertible bonds and the underlying equity, making it sensitive to both credit spreads (which affect the bond component) and equity volatility (which affects the embedded option value).', 1),
  ('frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk-q03', 'frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk', 'During operational due diligence, an investor discovers that the hedge fund manager''s back office also performs position valuation. This raises which primary concern?', 'Strategy capacity constraints', 'Excessive gross leverage', 'Conflict of interest in valuation', 'Prime broker counterparty risk', 'C', 'When portfolio managers or their affiliated staff perform valuations, there is an inherent conflict of interest because incentive fees are tied to reported performance. Independent valuation by a third-party administrator is a best practice to mitigate this risk.', 2),
  ('frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk-q04', 'frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk', 'A prime broker raises margin requirements for a hedge fund during a period of market stress. The most likely immediate consequence is:', 'Reduced strategy capacity', 'Forced deleveraging at adverse prices', 'Increased key-person risk', 'Imposition of a redemption gate', 'B', 'When prime brokers increase margin requirements, hedge funds must either post additional collateral or liquidate positions to meet calls. In stressed markets, this forced deleveraging typically occurs at unfavorable prices, amplifying losses.', 3),
  ('frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk-q05', 'frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk', 'Which of the following best describes a ''side pocket'' in hedge fund operations?', 'A segregated sub-account isolating illiquid or hard-to-value assets', 'A reserve account held by the prime broker as collateral', 'A fee mechanism that defers performance fees until a hurdle rate is met', 'A leverage facility provided by the fund administrator', 'A', 'A side pocket is a separate account within a hedge fund used to hold illiquid or hard-to-value assets, preventing investors who redeem from receiving these assets at potentially arbitrary values and protecting remaining investors from liquidity-driven forced sales.', 4),
  ('frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk-q06', 'frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk', 'Key-person risk in hedge funds is most directly mitigated by which measure?', 'Requiring daily liquidity for all fund positions', 'Ensuring robust team depth and documented investment processes', 'Reducing gross leverage to below 2x', 'Engaging an independent fund administrator', 'B', 'Key-person risk arises from over-reliance on specific individuals. Mitigation involves building team depth, institutionalizing the investment process through documentation, and ensuring multiple team members can execute the strategy.', 5),
  ('frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk-q07', 'frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk', 'Statistical arbitrage strategies are exposed to the risk that mean-reversion assumptions break down. This is an example of which category of risk?', 'Operational risk', 'Liquidity risk', 'Model risk', 'Counterparty risk', 'C', 'Statistical arbitrage relies on quantitative models that assume historical price relationships will revert to historical norms. When these assumptions fail — as during regime changes or market stress — the strategy suffers model risk losses.', 6),
  ('frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk-q08', 'frm-investment-risk-hedge-fund-risk', 'An investor conducting due diligence on a hedge fund observes a 10-year track record that began in 2008. Which bias is most important to consider when evaluating this record?', 'Anchoring bias', 'Look-ahead bias', 'Confirmation bias', 'Survivorship bias', 'D', 'Survivorship bias arises because only funds that have survived and continued to report are included in most databases. Funds that launched around 2008 and subsequently closed due to poor performance are excluded, making average performance look better than it actually was.', 7),
  ('frm-investment-risk-pension-risk-q01', 'frm-investment-risk-pension-risk', 'A defined benefit pension plan has assets with duration of 8 years and liabilities with duration of 14 years. If interest rates rise by 100 basis points, what happens to the plan''s funded status?', 'Funded status deteriorates because asset losses exceed liability gains', 'Funded status improves because liability present value falls more than asset value', 'Funded status is unchanged because both assets and liabilities fall equally', 'Funded status improves because rising rates increase asset yields', 'B', 'When asset duration (8 years) is less than liability duration (14 years), the present value of liabilities falls more than asset values when rates rise. This positive duration gap means rising rates improve funded status.', 0),
  ('frm-investment-risk-pension-risk-q02', 'frm-investment-risk-pension-risk', 'In a defined contribution pension plan, who bears the primary investment risk?', 'The plan participant (employee)', 'The plan trustee', 'The plan sponsor (employer)', 'The Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation', 'A', 'In a defined contribution plan, the employer contributes a fixed amount and the employee directs investments. The participant bears all investment risk; their retirement income depends entirely on investment performance.', 1),
  ('frm-investment-risk-pension-risk-q03', 'frm-investment-risk-pension-risk', 'A pension fund adopts a liability-driven investing (LDI) strategy. Which instrument is most directly used to hedge the fund''s interest rate duration mismatch?', 'Long-duration government bonds or interest rate swaps', 'Equity index futures', 'Short-term money market instruments', 'Commodity futures', 'A', 'LDI strategies use long-duration bonds or receive-fixed interest rate swaps to increase asset duration and match it to the long duration of pension liabilities, thereby hedging funded status against interest rate movements.', 2),
  ('frm-investment-risk-pension-risk-q04', 'frm-investment-risk-pension-risk', 'Longevity risk for a defined benefit pension plan refers to which of the following?', 'The risk that beneficiaries live longer than actuarial assumptions, increasing total payout obligations', 'The risk that the plan''s assets decline in value due to equity market losses', 'The risk that inflation erodes the real value of fixed pension payments', 'The risk that the plan sponsor becomes insolvent before funding obligations are met', 'A', 'Longevity risk is the risk that plan members live longer than the mortality tables used in actuarial valuations, requiring the plan to make benefit payments for longer periods than anticipated and increasing the present value of liabilities.', 3),
  ('frm-investment-risk-pension-risk-q05', 'frm-investment-risk-pension-risk', 'Which transaction transfers the longevity and investment risk of a defined benefit plan''s liabilities entirely to an insurance company?', 'A longevity swap', 'A pension buy-out', 'A pension buy-in', 'A liability-driven investment overlay', 'B', 'In a pension buy-out, the plan sponsor transfers both the assets and the pension obligations to an insurance company, which then becomes directly liable to plan members. A buy-in is an investment held by the plan; a buy-out extinguishes the plan sponsor''s liability entirely.', 4),
  ('frm-investment-risk-pension-risk-q06', 'frm-investment-risk-pension-risk', 'A pension plan reports a funded ratio of 85%. This means:', 'The plan holds assets equal to 85% of contributions made by employees', 'The plan has earned returns equal to 85% of its benchmark over the past year', 'Plan assets cover only 85% of the present value of future benefit obligations', 'The plan has invested 85% of its assets in fixed income securities', 'C', 'A funded ratio of 85% indicates the plan is underfunded: plan assets equal 85% of the present value of accrued liabilities, leaving a 15% funding shortfall that may require additional sponsor contributions or benefit adjustments.', 5),
  ('frm-investment-risk-pension-risk-q07', 'frm-investment-risk-pension-risk', 'Which actuarial assumption, if changed to a lower value, would increase the reported present value of a defined benefit pension plan''s liabilities?', 'Expected salary growth rate', 'Expected portfolio return', 'Discount rate', 'Assumed employee turnover rate', 'C', 'The discount rate is used to convert future benefit payments to present value. A lower discount rate increases the present value of future obligations, worsening the funded status. This is why low interest rate environments create pension funding challenges.', 6),
  ('frm-investment-risk-pension-risk-q08', 'frm-investment-risk-pension-risk', 'A longevity swap entered into by a pension plan involves the plan receiving payments from the counterparty when:', 'Portfolio assets underperform the benchmark', 'Inflation exceeds a predetermined threshold', 'Interest rates fall below a specified floor', 'Actual mortality rates are lower than expected (i.e., members live longer)', 'D', 'In a longevity swap, the pension plan pays fixed payments based on expected mortality and receives variable payments based on actual survival rates. When actual longevity exceeds expectations (members live longer), the plan receives net payments that offset the additional benefit costs.', 7),
  ('frm-investment-risk-factor-models-q01', 'frm-investment-risk-factor-models', 'In the Fama-French three-factor model, the HML factor captures returns attributable to which characteristic?', 'High momentum stocks versus low momentum stocks', 'High beta stocks versus low beta stocks', 'High market capitalization stocks versus low market capitalization stocks', 'High book-to-market (value) stocks versus low book-to-market (growth) stocks', 'D', 'HML stands for High Minus Low, referring to the book-to-market ratio. It captures the historical premium earned by value stocks (high book-to-market) over growth stocks (low book-to-market), one of the most studied anomalies in asset pricing.', 0),
  ('frm-investment-risk-factor-models-q02', 'frm-investment-risk-factor-models', 'The Carhart four-factor model extends the Fama-French three-factor model by adding which factor?', 'Profitability (robust minus weak)', 'Investment (conservative minus aggressive)', 'Low volatility (low minus high beta)', 'Momentum (winners minus losers)', 'D', 'Carhart added the momentum factor (UMD: Up Minus Down, or winners minus losers over the past 12 months excluding the most recent month) to capture the tendency of recent outperformers to continue outperforming over subsequent months.', 1),
  ('frm-investment-risk-factor-models-q03', 'frm-investment-risk-factor-models', 'A portfolio manager generates a positive regression intercept after controlling for market, size, value, and momentum factors. This intercept is best interpreted as:', 'Alpha — return in excess of all identified factor exposures', 'Evidence of positive factor timing ability', 'Compensation for systematic risk exposures', 'Tracking error relative to the benchmark', 'A', 'The regression intercept (alpha) in a factor model represents the return that cannot be explained by exposure to the included systematic factors. A positive alpha suggests genuine outperformance beyond factor compensation, though it may also reflect an omitted factor.', 2),
  ('frm-investment-risk-factor-models-q04', 'frm-investment-risk-factor-models', 'The information ratio (IR) of an active manager is defined as:', 'Alpha divided by total portfolio volatility', 'Excess return divided by beta', 'Alpha divided by tracking error', 'Sharpe ratio minus the benchmark Sharpe ratio', 'C', 'The information ratio equals alpha (active return relative to the benchmark) divided by tracking error (the standard deviation of active returns). It measures how consistently a manager generates alpha per unit of active risk taken.', 3),
  ('frm-investment-risk-factor-models-q05', 'frm-investment-risk-factor-models', 'A smart beta strategy systematically tilts toward small-cap and value stocks. Compared to a traditional active fund, this approach primarily offers:', 'Higher alpha through discretionary stock selection', 'Rules-based factor exposure at lower cost than active management', 'Protection against factor crowding through daily rebalancing', 'Guaranteed outperformance over full market cycles', 'B', 'Smart beta strategies offer systematic, transparent exposure to historically rewarded factors (value, size, momentum, quality) using rules-based indices, typically at lower costs than actively managed funds that seek similar factor tilts through discretionary stock selection.', 4),
  ('frm-investment-risk-factor-models-q06', 'frm-investment-risk-factor-models', 'A fund with a loading of 0.8 on the SMB factor is most likely to:', 'Outperform in environments where large-cap stocks dominate', 'Benefit when growth stocks outperform value stocks', 'Exhibit higher returns during periods of strong small-cap performance', 'Show negative correlation with the market factor', 'C', 'A positive loading on SMB (Small Minus Big) indicates the fund has a tilt toward smaller-capitalization stocks. The fund will outperform when small-cap stocks outperform large-cap stocks, and underperform in the opposite regime.', 5),
  ('frm-investment-risk-factor-models-q07', 'frm-investment-risk-factor-models', 'Factor crowding risk in quantitative equity strategies refers to:', 'The risk that factor exposures exceed regulatory concentration limits', 'The risk that a single factor dominates total portfolio variance', 'The risk that many managers hold similar factor exposures, leading to correlated drawdowns during unwinding', 'The risk that factor premiums erode as more capital is allocated to them', 'C', 'Factor crowding occurs when many quantitative strategies target the same factors, creating highly correlated positions. During market stress, simultaneous de-risking by these strategies amplifies price moves and causes correlated drawdowns across funds that appear diversified.', 6),
  ('frm-investment-risk-factor-models-q08', 'frm-investment-risk-factor-models', 'Which statement best describes the difference between systematic (beta) risk and idiosyncratic (alpha) risk in the context of factor models?', 'Systematic risk can be eliminated through diversification; idiosyncratic risk cannot', 'Idiosyncratic risk is shared across all stocks; systematic risk is stock-specific', 'Systematic risk is compensated by factor premiums; idiosyncratic risk is not compensated on average', 'Beta risk increases with portfolio concentration; alpha risk decreases with diversification', 'C', 'In factor models, systematic (beta) risk reflects exposure to rewarded risk factors for which investors receive a risk premium. Idiosyncratic risk is stock-specific and diversifiable; in a large portfolio, it averages to zero and is not compensated by the market.', 7),
  ('frm-investment-risk-esg-q01', 'frm-investment-risk-esg', 'Which of the following is an example of a governance (G) risk factor in ESG analysis?', 'Board independence and executive compensation structures', 'Supply chain labor standards in emerging markets', 'A company''s water consumption relative to industry peers', 'Carbon emissions intensity per unit of revenue', 'A', 'Governance factors relate to how a company is directed and controlled, including board composition, independence, diversity, executive pay alignment with shareholder interests, and shareholder rights. These are distinct from environmental (E) and social (S) factors.', 0),
  ('frm-investment-risk-esg-q02', 'frm-investment-risk-esg', 'Greenwashing in the context of ESG investing most directly refers to:', 'Overstating or misrepresenting ESG credentials of a fund or company', 'The underperformance of ESG-screened portfolios during bull markets', 'The exclusion of fossil fuel companies from an investment universe', 'The difficulty of measuring the social impact of investments', 'A', 'Greenwashing refers to making misleading claims about the environmental or social sustainability credentials of an investment product or company. It creates reputational and regulatory risk for asset managers as regulators increase scrutiny of ESG disclosures.', 1),
  ('frm-investment-risk-esg-q03', 'frm-investment-risk-esg', 'Under the EU Sustainable Finance Disclosure Regulation (SFDR), which article classification applies to funds that have sustainable investment as their objective?', 'Article 9', 'Article 7', 'Article 8', 'Article 6', 'A', 'SFDR Article 9 applies to funds with a specific sustainable investment objective, requiring the highest level of ESG disclosure. Article 8 funds promote ESG characteristics. Article 6 funds make no sustainability claims.', 2),
  ('frm-investment-risk-esg-q04', 'frm-investment-risk-esg', 'An investment fund excludes all tobacco companies from its portfolio regardless of their ESG scores within the sector. This approach is best described as:', 'Negative screening', 'Positive screening (best-in-class)', 'ESG integration', 'Impact investing', 'A', 'Negative screening involves excluding specific sectors, companies, or activities from the investment universe based on ethical or ESG criteria. Tobacco exclusion is one of the most common negative screens, applied without consideration of relative ESG performance within the sector.', 3),
  ('frm-investment-risk-esg-q05', 'frm-investment-risk-esg', 'The concept of ''double materiality'' in ESG reporting requires companies to disclose:', 'Both quantitative metrics and qualitative narratives for all ESG factors', 'Both backward-looking historical data and forward-looking ESG targets', 'ESG data at both the parent company and subsidiary level', 'Both how ESG factors affect the company financially and how the company affects society and the environment', 'D', 'Double materiality holds that companies should report from two perspectives: the financial materiality of ESG factors on the company (outside-in), and the impact materiality of the company''s activities on people and the planet (inside-out). The EU''s Corporate Sustainability Reporting Directive (CSRD) mandates double materiality.', 4),
  ('frm-investment-risk-esg-q06', 'frm-investment-risk-esg', 'Which of the following represents a social (S) risk factor that could be material to an investor''s analysis of a technology company?', 'The company''s Scope 1 and Scope 2 carbon emissions', 'Board gender diversity and independent director representation', 'The company''s use of renewable energy in its data centers', 'Data privacy practices and potential regulatory fines for data breaches', 'D', 'Data privacy is a social risk factor because it relates to the company''s relationship with individuals whose data it processes. Regulatory fines, reputational damage, and litigation costs from data breaches can be financially material, making this a legitimate ESG investment risk.', 5),
  ('frm-investment-risk-esg-q07', 'frm-investment-risk-esg', 'An investor integrates ESG scores into their fundamental analysis as one input among several financial and non-financial factors. This approach is best described as:', 'Negative screening', 'Thematic investing', 'Shareholder engagement', 'ESG integration', 'D', 'ESG integration involves systematically incorporating ESG information alongside traditional financial analysis to identify risks and opportunities that may not be captured by conventional metrics, without necessarily excluding companies based on their ESG scores.', 6),
  ('frm-investment-risk-esg-q08', 'frm-investment-risk-esg', 'A major challenge in comparing ESG ratings across different rating providers is:', 'Excessive regulatory standardization of ESG methodologies', 'The tendency of ESG ratings to be identical to credit ratings', 'The low correlation between ratings from different providers due to differing methodologies and data sources', 'The requirement for all ESG ratings to use audited financial statement data only', 'C', 'Research has consistently found low correlation (often below 0.5) between ESG scores from different rating agencies such as MSCI, Sustainalytics, and S&P, due to differences in scope, measurement, and weighting of individual ESG factors. This divergence complicates portfolio construction and performance attribution.', 7),
  ('frm-current-issues-climate-risk-q01', 'frm-current-issues-climate-risk', 'A coastal property that loses value due to gradual sea-level rise over 30 years is an example of which category of climate risk?', 'Chronic physical risk', 'Acute physical risk', 'Policy transition risk', 'Reputational transition risk', 'A', 'Chronic physical risk refers to gradual, long-term shifts in climate patterns such as rising sea levels, increasing average temperatures, and changing precipitation. These risks erode asset values over time, in contrast to acute physical risks from sudden extreme weather events.', 0),
  ('frm-current-issues-climate-risk-q02', 'frm-current-issues-climate-risk', 'The TCFD (Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures) framework recommends disclosure across four pillars. Which of the following is NOT one of them?', 'Governance', 'Strategy', 'Metrics & Targets', 'Compensation', 'D', 'The four TCFD pillars are Governance (how climate risks are overseen), Strategy (actual and potential impacts on business), Risk Management (processes for identifying and managing climate risks), and Metrics & Targets (measures used to assess climate risks). Compensation is not a standalone TCFD pillar.', 1),
  ('frm-current-issues-climate-risk-q03', 'frm-current-issues-climate-risk', 'A coal mining company''s reserves become economically unviable due to rising carbon taxes and falling renewable energy costs. This is an example of:', 'Acute physical risk', 'Reputational transition risk', 'Chronic physical risk', 'Stranded assets', 'D', 'Stranded assets are assets that lose their economic value earlier than expected due to changes in regulation, market conditions, or technology. Carbon-intensive assets such as coal reserves, oil fields, and fossil fuel infrastructure face stranding risk as the energy transition accelerates.', 2),
  ('frm-current-issues-climate-risk-q04', 'frm-current-issues-climate-risk', 'An emissions trading scheme (ETS) differs from a carbon tax primarily in that:', 'An ETS applies only to financial institutions, while a carbon tax applies to all sectors', 'An ETS sets a cap on total emissions and allows trading of allowances; a carbon tax sets a fixed price per tonne', 'A carbon tax generates no government revenue, while an ETS does', 'An ETS covers Scope 3 emissions while a carbon tax covers only Scope 1', 'B', 'An emissions trading scheme establishes a cap on aggregate emissions and distributes or auctions allowances that can be traded between participants, letting the market determine the carbon price. A carbon tax fixes the price per tonne of CO2 while leaving the quantity of emissions uncertain.', 3),
  ('frm-current-issues-climate-risk-q05', 'frm-current-issues-climate-risk', 'Which feature makes climate stress tests conducted by central banks fundamentally different from traditional bank stress tests?', 'Climate stress tests are voluntary while traditional stress tests are mandatory', 'Climate stress tests rely on macroeconomic models while traditional tests use balance sheet data', 'Climate stress tests assess only insurance companies, not banks', 'Climate stress tests span multi-decade horizons and require novel scenario analysis covering both physical and transition pathways', 'D', 'Traditional bank stress tests typically cover 2-3 year horizons using established macrofinancial models. Climate stress tests require 10-30+ year horizons, novel climate-economic scenario models, and assessment of both physical and transition risk channels simultaneously, posing significant methodological challenges.', 4),
  ('frm-current-issues-climate-risk-q06', 'frm-current-issues-climate-risk', 'A manufacturing firm faces higher input costs because a new carbon tax increases the price of energy. This is an example of which type of climate risk?', 'Acute physical risk', 'Chronic physical risk', 'Technology transition risk', 'Policy transition risk', 'D', 'Policy transition risk arises from government actions to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, including carbon taxes, cap-and-trade schemes, efficiency standards, and disclosure requirements. Higher energy costs resulting from a carbon tax are a direct manifestation of policy transition risk.', 5),
  ('frm-current-issues-climate-risk-q07', 'frm-current-issues-climate-risk', 'A bank lends against real estate in a flood-prone coastal area without factoring in changing flood probabilities over the loan''s 25-year term. This best illustrates which risk?', 'Transition risk from carbon pricing', 'Stranded asset risk from changing technology', 'Greenwashing risk', 'Acute physical risk that is not captured in current credit models', 'D', 'The failure to incorporate increasing flood risk into loan underwriting is a direct example of acute physical climate risk not being captured in credit models. As flood frequency and severity increase with climate change, collateral values and borrower creditworthiness may deteriorate, creating unexpected credit losses.', 6),
  ('frm-current-issues-climate-risk-q08', 'frm-current-issues-climate-risk', 'TCFD scenario analysis for a financial institution should include at minimum a scenario aligned with which international climate target?', 'A 4 degree Celsius warming pathway (business as usual)', 'A 1.5 to 2 degree Celsius warming pathway consistent with the Paris Agreement', 'A carbon-neutral scenario by 2050 specific to the financial sector only', 'A scenario based on current national policy commitments only', 'B', 'The TCFD recommends that institutions analyze scenarios including one consistent with the Paris Agreement goal of limiting warming to well below 2 degrees Celsius, ideally 1.5 degrees Celsius. This scenario typically features aggressive carbon pricing and rapid technology transition and is used to stress test business strategies.', 7),
  ('frm-current-issues-digital-assets-q01', 'frm-current-issues-digital-assets', 'In 2022, the TerraUSD (UST) stablecoin collapsed to near zero. This event primarily illustrated which type of digital asset risk?', 'Custody risk from exchange insolvency', 'Smart contract exploit resulting in unauthorized withdrawals', 'Regulatory reclassification of the asset as a security', 'Algorithmic stablecoin design failure and the risk of a death spiral', 'D', 'TerraUSD maintained its dollar peg through an algorithmic mechanism involving its sister token LUNA rather than fiat collateral. When confidence in the peg broke, a self-reinforcing death spiral occurred as UST redemptions minted LUNA, flooding supply and destroying value in both tokens.', 0),
  ('frm-current-issues-digital-assets-q02', 'frm-current-issues-digital-assets', 'Which risk category is most directly associated with the collapse of the FTX crypto exchange in 2022?', 'Custody risk from commingling of customer assets', 'Oracle manipulation risk', 'Smart contract risk', 'Blockchain consensus failure', 'A', 'The FTX collapse illustrated custody risk: customer assets deposited with the exchange were allegedly commingled with and used by FTX''s affiliated trading firm, Alameda Research. When Alameda''s losses became apparent and withdrawals surged, FTX lacked sufficient assets to meet redemptions.', 1),
  ('frm-current-issues-digital-assets-q03', 'frm-current-issues-digital-assets', 'Oracle risk in DeFi protocols refers to the risk that:', 'The blockchain''s consensus mechanism fails to validate transactions correctly', 'The private key controlling the protocol''s treasury is compromised', 'Price feeds used by smart contracts are manipulated or provide inaccurate data', 'Regulatory authorities classify the protocol''s governance token as an unregistered security', 'C', 'DeFi protocols typically rely on oracles — external data feeds — to obtain price information for assets. If oracle prices are manipulated or inaccurate, smart contracts may execute at wrong prices, enabling attackers to drain protocol funds or distort outcomes for borrowers and lenders.', 2),
  ('frm-current-issues-digital-assets-q04', 'frm-current-issues-digital-assets', 'Which characteristic of crypto markets most directly contributes to extreme price volatility compared to traditional equity markets?', 'The use of blockchain technology for settlement', 'The global regulatory fragmentation across jurisdictions', 'The pseudonymous nature of blockchain transactions', '24/7 trading with thinner liquidity and absence of circuit breakers', 'D', 'Crypto markets operate continuously without the circuit breakers that pause trading in equity markets during extreme moves. Combined with relatively thin liquidity compared to major equity markets and the high proportion of leveraged participants, this contributes to extreme intraday and interday volatility.', 3),
  ('frm-current-issues-digital-assets-q05', 'frm-current-issues-digital-assets', 'A smart contract vulnerability that allows an attacker to repeatedly withdraw funds before the contract updates its internal balance is known as:', 'A 51% attack', 'A flash loan attack', 'A reentrancy attack', 'A Sybil attack', 'C', 'A reentrancy attack exploits a vulnerability where a smart contract makes an external call before updating its state. The attacker can repeatedly call back into the contract during the external call, draining funds before the balance is decremented. The DAO hack of 2016 is the most famous example.', 4),
  ('frm-current-issues-digital-assets-q06', 'frm-current-issues-digital-assets', 'From a regulatory risk perspective, why is the classification of a digital asset as a ''security'' significant for its issuer?', 'It exempts the asset from anti-money laundering requirements', 'It subjects the issuer to securities registration, disclosure, and investor protection regulations', 'It automatically grants the asset commodity status for tax purposes', 'It requires the asset to maintain a 1:1 peg to the US dollar', 'B', 'If a digital asset is classified as a security under the Howey test, its issuance and trading become subject to securities law, requiring registration with regulators, prospectus disclosure, and compliance with investor protection rules. Non-compliance exposes issuers to enforcement actions and significant legal liability.', 5),
  ('frm-current-issues-digital-assets-q07', 'frm-current-issues-digital-assets', 'A fiat-backed stablecoin that holds US Treasury bills as reserves faces which primary residual risk?', 'Algorithmic failure and death spiral dynamics', 'Counterparty and redemption risk on the stablecoin issuer', 'Smart contract exploit allowing unauthorized minting', 'Blockchain consensus failure invalidating token balances', 'B', 'Even with high-quality reserves such as Treasury bills, holders of fiat-backed stablecoins bear counterparty risk on the issuer: the risk that the issuer is insolvent, has misrepresented reserves, faces regulatory shutdown, or cannot process redemptions in a timely manner during periods of stress.', 6),
  ('frm-current-issues-digital-assets-q08', 'frm-current-issues-digital-assets', 'Governance risk in DeFi protocols most directly refers to:', 'The risk that regulators impose governance requirements on decentralized protocols', 'The risk that the development team abandons the protocol (rug pull)', 'The risk that large token holders capture voting power and make decisions that benefit themselves at the expense of other users', 'The risk that governance tokens lose market value due to declining protocol usage', 'C', 'Token-based governance in DeFi grants voting power proportional to token holdings. This creates governance risk when large holders (whales or founding teams) control sufficient voting power to pass proposals that redirect protocol funds, change fee structures, or otherwise extract value from smaller token holders.', 7),
  ('frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning-q01', 'frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning', 'A bank uses a gradient-boosted tree model to make credit decisions. Regulators ask the bank to explain why a specific applicant was denied credit. The primary challenge this creates is:', 'The model''s black-box nature makes it difficult to provide interpretable explanations', 'The model cannot be run on individual observations', 'The model requires proprietary data that cannot be disclosed to regulators', 'The model was trained on aggregate population data and cannot produce individual outputs', 'A', 'Complex ML models such as gradient-boosted trees and neural networks are black-box models whose internal mechanics cannot be easily articulated. Regulatory requirements for adverse action notices in credit decisions require explainable reasons, creating tension with the use of black-box models.', 0),
  ('frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning-q02', 'frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning', 'Survivorship bias in a machine learning model''s training dataset for credit risk would most likely result in:', 'The model overestimating default probabilities because it includes only failed borrowers', 'The model underestimating credit risk because it is trained only on borrowers who were approved and survived', 'The model producing inconsistent predictions across demographic groups', 'The model overfitting to recent economic conditions', 'B', 'Survivorship bias in credit modeling occurs when the training data includes only applicants who received credit and were observed through repayment or default. Rejected applicants — who may have been riskier — are excluded, causing the model to underestimate risk for similar future applicants.', 1),
  ('frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning-q03', 'frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning', 'Model drift in an ML-based risk model most directly refers to:', 'Intentional changes made to model parameters by authorized users', 'Deterioration in model performance due to changes in the statistical properties of input data over time', 'Differences in predictions between a model and its validation benchmark', 'Unauthorized modifications to the model''s source code', 'B', 'Model drift (also called concept drift or data drift) occurs when the relationships the model learned during training no longer hold in the current environment. For example, a fraud detection model trained pre-pandemic may perform poorly post-pandemic because spending patterns changed significantly.', 2),
  ('frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning-q04', 'frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning', 'SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) values are used in the context of ML risk models primarily to:', 'Measure the statistical significance of individual model features', 'Validate that a model''s predictions are calibrated to observed default rates', 'Explain the contribution of each input feature to a specific model prediction', 'Detect adversarial inputs designed to manipulate model outputs', 'C', 'SHAP values, derived from cooperative game theory, decompose a model''s prediction for a specific observation into contributions from each input feature. This provides local explainability, allowing risk managers and regulators to understand why the model produced a particular output for an individual case.', 3),
  ('frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning-q05', 'frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning', 'Flash crashes in equity markets have been linked to algorithmic trading. The mechanism most often cited involves:', 'Manually entered erroneous orders by human traders', 'Coordinated manipulation by high-frequency trading firms', 'Feedback loops where algorithms respond to each other''s actions, amplifying price moves', 'Failure of exchange matching engines during peak order volumes', 'C', 'Flash crashes are often associated with algorithmic feedback loops: as prices move, multiple algorithms simultaneously trigger similar sell orders (e.g., stop-losses, volatility-based de-risking), which drives prices further down, triggering more algorithmic responses in a self-reinforcing cycle that can cause extreme intraday moves.', 4),
  ('frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning-q06', 'frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning', 'The EU AI Act classifies credit scoring models as ''high-risk AI systems.'' The primary consequence of this classification is:', 'Credit scoring AI is prohibited entirely within the EU', 'Credit scoring AI must be registered, assessed for conformity, and meet requirements for transparency, accuracy, and human oversight', 'Credit scoring AI may only be deployed by systemically important banks', 'Credit scoring AI must be open-sourced so regulators can inspect the code', 'B', 'The EU AI Act''s high-risk classification triggers a set of mandatory requirements including conformity assessment before deployment, registration in a public database, documentation of training data and methodology, mechanisms for human oversight, and ongoing monitoring of performance to ensure accuracy and non-discrimination.', 5),
  ('frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning-q07', 'frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning', 'Look-ahead bias in a machine learning model for predicting loan defaults would occur if:', 'The model is trained on a different geographic region than where it is deployed', 'The training data includes information that would not have been available at the time of loan origination', 'The model is validated on data from the same time period as the training set', 'The model uses too many features relative to the number of training observations', 'B', 'Look-ahead bias occurs when training data inadvertently includes information that was not yet available at the decision point being modeled. For example, using final settlement data or post-origination financial ratios as features in a loan origination model would inflate backtested performance and produce an unreliable live model.', 6),
  ('frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning-q08', 'frm-current-issues-ai-machine-learning', 'According to the US Federal Reserve''s SR 11-7 guidance on model risk management, which of the following is a core component of an effective model validation framework?', 'Models must be rebuilt from scratch every two years regardless of performance', 'Third-party vendors are exempt from model validation requirements', 'All risk models must be approved by the board of directors before deployment', 'Validation must be performed by individuals independent of model development, covering conceptual soundness, outcomes analysis, and benchmarking', 'D', 'SR 11-7 requires model validation to be conducted by parties independent of model development. Validation should cover three elements: evaluation of conceptual soundness, ongoing monitoring of model performance, and outcomes analysis/benchmarking comparing model outputs to actual results and alternative approaches.', 7),
  ('frm-current-issues-systemic-risk-q01', 'frm-current-issues-systemic-risk', 'The moral hazard problem associated with ''too-big-to-fail'' institutions arises because:', 'Large banks face higher capital requirements that reduce their return on equity', 'The implicit government guarantee allows SIFIs to take on excessive risk at lower funding costs than smaller institutions', 'Large institutions have insufficient information to assess counterparty risk accurately', 'Regulatory resources are insufficient to supervise the largest financial institutions', 'B', 'The too-big-to-fail problem creates moral hazard because the implicit government backstop reduces creditors'' incentive to discipline SIFIs for risk-taking, lowers their borrowing costs, and may encourage excessive leverage. This funding advantage compared to smaller institutions is a form of implicit subsidy.', 0),
  ('frm-current-issues-systemic-risk-q02', 'frm-current-issues-systemic-risk', 'The Countercyclical Capital Buffer (CCyB) is designed to:', 'Permanently increase minimum capital requirements for the largest global banks', 'Require banks to hold additional capital during credit booms that can be released during downturns to absorb losses', 'Set a floor on bank liquidity ratios throughout the economic cycle', 'Limit bank lending to specific sectors identified as systemically risky', 'B', 'The CCyB is a macroprudential tool that rises above zero when credit growth is excessive and systemic risk is building (the boom phase), and is reduced or released during stress periods to allow banks to absorb losses without curtailing lending. It is explicitly countercyclical to moderate the credit cycle.', 1),
  ('frm-current-issues-systemic-risk-q03', 'frm-current-issues-systemic-risk', 'Fire sale contagion between financial institutions occurs through which indirect channel?', 'Direct interbank lending exposures creating bilateral credit losses', 'Correspondent banking relationships in the payment system', 'Counterparty exposure through centrally cleared derivatives', 'Common asset holdings where distressed selling by one institution depresses prices for all institutions holding the same assets', 'D', 'Indirect contagion through fire sales occurs when distressed institutions liquidate common asset holdings, depressing market prices. Other institutions holding the same assets suffer mark-to-market losses, potentially triggering their own deleveraging in a self-reinforcing spiral that propagates stress without any direct bilateral exposure.', 2),
  ('frm-current-issues-systemic-risk-q04', 'frm-current-issues-systemic-risk', 'The Financial Stability Board (FSB) designates certain banks as G-SIBs (Global Systemically Important Banks) based on an assessment framework. Which of the following is NOT a factor in the G-SIB designation methodology?', 'Cross-jurisdictional activity', 'Interconnectedness with other financial institutions', 'Profitability and return on equity', 'Substitutability of the institution''s functions', 'C', 'The FSB''s G-SIB framework assesses systemic importance across five categories: cross-jurisdictional activity, size, interconnectedness, substitutability/financial institution infrastructure, and complexity. Profitability or return on equity are not systemic risk indicators included in the methodology.', 3),
  ('frm-current-issues-systemic-risk-q05', 'frm-current-issues-systemic-risk', 'Procyclicality in the financial system most directly refers to:', 'The amplification of economic cycles by financial system behavior, such as loosening credit standards in booms and tightening them in recessions', 'The tendency of banks to increase dividends during economic expansions', 'The correlation between bank stock prices and the business cycle', 'The pro-market regulatory stance adopted during economic expansions', 'A', 'Procyclicality describes how financial system behavior tends to amplify rather than dampen the economic cycle. During booms, credit standards loosen, leverage rises, and asset prices inflate; during downturns, standards tighten, deleveraging accelerates, and fire sales create a negative feedback loop that deepens the recession.', 4),
  ('frm-current-issues-systemic-risk-q06', 'frm-current-issues-systemic-risk', 'A G-SIB in Bucket 4 of the FSB''s G-SIB framework faces a higher-loss-absorbency (HLA) surcharge of:', '2.0% of risk-weighted assets', '1.0% of risk-weighted assets', '0.5% of risk-weighted assets', '3.5% of risk-weighted assets', 'A', 'The FSB G-SIB framework assigns banks to five buckets based on systemic importance scores. Bucket 1 carries a 1.0% CET1 surcharge, Bucket 2 requires 1.5%, Bucket 3 requires 2.0%, Bucket 4 requires 2.5%, and Bucket 5 (currently empty) would require 3.5%.', 5),
  ('frm-current-issues-systemic-risk-q07', 'frm-current-issues-systemic-risk', 'Shadow banking, as defined in the context of systemic risk monitoring, refers to:', 'Illegal financial activities conducted outside the formal banking system', 'Credit intermediation involving entities and activities outside the regular banking system that may create systemic risk', 'Offshore banking activities conducted in tax havens', 'The use of opaque derivatives by regulated banks to hide leverage', 'B', 'The FSB defines shadow banking as credit intermediation involving entities and activities outside the regular banking system. This includes money market funds, securitization vehicles, securities lending, and repo markets. Shadow banking can create systemic risk through leverage, maturity transformation, and liquidity mismatch without the same regulatory safeguards as banks.', 6),
  ('frm-current-issues-systemic-risk-q08', 'frm-current-issues-systemic-risk', 'A macroprudential authority imposes a loan-to-value (LTV) cap of 80% on residential mortgages. The primary objective of this measure is to:', 'Limit borrower and bank exposure to house price declines and reduce systemic risk from a housing bust', 'Increase bank profitability by reducing the volume of mortgage lending', 'Ensure that mortgage borrowers maintain minimum levels of cash savings', 'Standardize mortgage terms across lenders to improve market transparency', 'A', 'LTV caps limit how much borrowers can leverage against property values. By requiring minimum equity contributions, they reduce the probability of negative equity when house prices fall and limit lender losses in a housing downturn, thereby reducing the systemic risk from highly leveraged real estate cycles.', 7)
on conflict (id) do update set topic_id = excluded.topic_id, text = excluded.text, option_a = excluded.option_a, option_b = excluded.option_b, option_c = excluded.option_c, option_d = excluded.option_d, correct_option = excluded.correct_option, explanation = excluded.explanation, order_index = excluded.order_index;


commit;

